<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 0053EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-DisfiguredSoldier     11-29 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Disfigured Soldier,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maimed Soldier Appeals To Countrymen For Consideration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young reserve soldier whose face was burned
and mutilated by a firebomb went on television to ask fellow
Israelis to show some understanding and stop staring at him.
   Shimon Navon, a 25-year-old university student, was doing his
required duty in the occupied West Bank last June when Palestinians
hurled a firebomb at his jeep. His face was disfigured and all his
fingers had to be amputated.
   He decided to appear on an Israeli TV talk show Monday night, he
said, because his countrymen react so cruelly when they encounter
victims like himself in public.
   ``All the stares lock on you,'' he said. ``Sometimes it's
helplessness, or even fear. ... People just have no tact and they
shout things, like, `Look at this weirdo, look at this creature!'
   ``As though we are not living in a country where people should
know about this phenomenom. It happens a lot and I'm not the only
one; there are a lot like me.''
   Navon's entire face is covered with burns and scar tissue. His
ears were burned off. His fingerless hands are still wrapped in
bandages.
   He appeared on TV with his girlfriend, Miri Amiel. They began
dating about six months before he was hurt, and Ms. Amiel said they
were closer now than ever.
   ``Before, we were like any couple, going out together, studying
together, having fun. ... Now we have to deal with all these things
together,'' she said. ``Of course, Shimon has to deal with it more
than I, but I am a partner in everything.''
   They met at college, where he was taking a preparatory course
before studying for a degree.
   Amiel said she, too, is pained by the public's reaction.
   ``It's very sad for me ... to see all the stares, and hope that
Shimon doesn't notice,'' she said.
   Tragedy struck Navon at 11 p.m. on June 14, the last day of his
unit's 24-day tour of duty in the occupied areas. His jeep entered
Beit Umar village for one last patrol before returning to base for a
farewell party.
   ``I didn't want to do the extra round because it was late,'' he
said. ``I felt a ... strange feeling. ... After a moment or two I
felt the Molotov cocktail. All of me was burning. ... I couldn't
open the door to get out of the jeep.''
   Since then, Navon has undergone more than a dozen operations and
skin transplants.
   He said he began crying when he realized what he looked like and
``my brother and my girlfriend ... also started crying. ... A few
minutes later I said, O.K., guys, calm down, everything will be all
right, this isn't going to break me.''
   The television showed a photograph of Navon and Amiel, taken
before the attack and portraying a handsome young man in army
uniform.
   ``I was always a pretty realistic and rational type,'' Navon
said. ``This new situation is not simple and not easy ... but it
won't help to complain or ask why I look like this.''
   He said he was appealing to Israeli society to be kinder to burn
victims not for himself but because other burn victims were more
sensitive than he.
   At least 10 people have suffered serious burns in firebomb
attacks in the past year _ a frequent weapon in the yearlong
Palestinian uprising that has killed more than 300 Palestinians and
11 Israelis.
   Navon said he harbors no desire for revenge and no feelings of
hatred toward the Palestinians who attacked him.
   He said Palestinian insurrectionists have ``a struggle of their
own, and the way they're doing it, with violence, they won't
accomplish anything. They must sit and talk this problem out.''
</TEXT>
