<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Bearings     11-29 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Bearings,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Opts Against Limitation on Bearing Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The domestic bearing industry is operating at
or near 100 percent capacity, the Reagan administration said in
declining to limit imports of the friction-reducing components from
Europe and Japan.
   The decision, announced Monday, follows a joint study by the
Commerce and Defense departments. The Commerce Department had found
separately in July that U.S. bearing manufacturers would not be able
to meet ``all national security requirements in the event of a major
conventional war.''
   But President Reagan in August tentatively ruled out limits until
the joint study could be completed. The administration wanted to
ensure that the domestic bearing industry would be sufficiently
healthy to meet production needs in the event of an emergency,
without the United States having to rely on outside suppliers.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the joint study found
that conditions in the domestic bearing industry had improved
signficantly in the last several months. His statement said that it
was concluded that ``administration initiatives should be adequate
to bring the domestic industrial base into an acceptable posture for
national security purposes.''
   Commerce Secretary C. William Verity said in a statement that
Reagan's decision was made ``after a thorough review of the impact
of bearing imports on national security.''
   ``While recognizing the critical importance of bearings to
defense preparedness, other administration initiatives already under
way _ coupled with significantly improved economic conditions for
the industry _ make me confident that this is the right decision,''
he said.
   The decision against moving to curb imports of bearings was based
on these conclusions of the government investigators:
   _Current demand for bearings in the United States is at its
highest level in recent years, particularly as bearing-consuming
industries such as automobiles, aerospace and off-road equipment
experience heavy sales increases.
   _The U.S. bearing industry has benefited from substantial
increases in domestic demand and is operating at or near 100 percent
of capacity.
   _The industry has attracted ``significant investment'' from both
domestic- and foreign-owned producers.
   _A change in Defense Department acquisition guidelines last
August, which now require the Pentagon to use only domestic
industries for the purchase of bearings for defense-related
equipment. This could provide the domestic industry with an
estimated $40 million to $50 million in additional revenue for
domestic suppliers.
   In a separate and unrelated action, the Commerce Department said
it was ``aggressively pursuing'' an investigation of alleged unfair
trade practices by foreign suppliers of anti-friction bearings.
   ``Our preliminary findings indicate dumping margins in the 20 to
80 percent range,'' Verity said. ``If the final results of this
investigation verify these margins, the duties imposed could
contribute to leveling the playing field for this important
industry.''
   He said that a final determination on the issue of dumping of
bearings by foreign competitors in the U.S. market will be due Jan.
9, and a decision will be made 45 days later on what kind of actions
to take.
   Dumping is the selling of a product in a foreign market at a
price lower than the domestic price.
</TEXT>
