<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Fitzwater     11-29 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fitzwater,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veteran Public Affairs Official Remains On White House Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marlin Fitzwater, signed on for another hitch
as White House spokesman, says President-elect George Bush ``will
have new ways of dealing with the press'' that may include more
informal meetings with reporters.
   Fitzwater, 46, has been President Reagan's chief spokesman since
February 1987 and was Vice President Bush's press secretary for two
years before that.
   Bush, making his first appearance in the White House press
briefing room since his election Nov. 8, announced Monday that he is
retaining Fitzwater.
   It is the first time the press secretary of an outgoing president
has been named permanently to the job in a new administration,
although Pierre Salinger served President Johnson for an interim
after President Kennedy's assassination.
   Fitzwater declined to say how frequently Bush would hold
presidential news conferences, saying: ``The vice president has been
holding press conferences at the rate of one every five hours for
the last few weeks, so we'll have to see how that works out.
   ``The new president, I'm sure, will have new ways of dealing with
the press. I'm sure there will be all kinds of interviews and press
conferences and meetings.''
   When a reporter observed that Bush seems more comfortable than
Reagan in freewheeling give-and-take with reporters, Fitzwater said,
``I would agree with you that the president-elect is comfortable
with the press, he does operate informally quite effectively.''
   ``So I would suspect you might see a lot more informal _ ,'' the
spokesman said, at which point his response was cut off by a
reporter's question as to what he would recommend in the way of news
conferences.
   ``I won't talk about all the things I've recommended and not
recommended, but we'll just have to wait and see,'' he said.
   ``I think there should be as much contact with the press as
possible and it should be as regular as possible,'' the spokesman
said.
   Fitzwater is a veteran public affairs official whose federal
career began in 1972 when he was a speechwriter for Secretary of
Transportation John Volpe. Before that, Fitzwater had worked for
newspapers in his native Kansas.
   ``I think he's the best,'' Bush said. ``He represents the old and
the new. He represents the Reagan administration and he also
represents the Bush administration. ... This is continuity in the
best sense.''
   When asked if he would hold more frequent news conferences than
Reagan, the president-elect said, ``I`m going to lean heavily on
Marlin for advice on this.''
   Fitzwater's present title is assistant to the president for press
relations. Bush said that in the new administration Fitzwater will
be press secretary, a title held now by James Brady, who was wounded
in the 1981 assassination attempt on President Reagan.
   When asked whether Brady would have a role in the new
administration, Fitzwater said, ``I know the vice president is very
interested in Jim and concerned about his well-being'' and that Bush
and his advisers ``have some ideas of things they would like him to
do.''
   Fitzwater said Sheila Tate would remain Bush's press secretary
through the transition, and he would take over on Jan. 20. Ms. Tate
has said she plans to leave government.
   After Bush left the briefing room, Fitzwater opened his
presentation with a few words of gratitude to the president-elect
and president.
   Then a reporter asked him, ``Well, will you keep avoiding
briefings and will you promise to hold more news conferences?''
   ``A two-minute honeymoon,'' Fitzwater said. ``Amazing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
