<1ST_LINE>r w PM-GrainDeal     11-29 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Grain Deal,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US-Soviet Grain Agreement Extended for 27 Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration hailed the new
U.S.-Soviet grain agreement as providing a steady market for
American farm products, but a congressman from America's wheat belt
said the deal sold growers short.
   The plan ``stabilizes grain trade between our two countries by
ensuring a secure source of supply for Soviet grain imports and
secure market for U.S. grain exports,'' said a statement from Alan
F. Holmer, chief of the U.S. delegation to the Moscow meetings.
   Under a 27-month extension of the long-term agreement between the
two nations, the Soviet Union is promising to buy at the equivalent
of at least 9 million metric tons annually of U.S. grain. A metric
ton equals about 2,205 pounds.
   U.S. and Soviet negotiators signed the extension in Moscow on
Monday, breathing new life into a five-year plan that helped to turn
the Soviet Union into one of the U.S. farmer's best customers. That
agreement had expired Sept. 30.
   ``The extension will continue to stabilize grain trade between
the two countries, benefiting American farmers,'' Agriculture
Secretary Richard E. Lyng and U.S. Trade Representative Clayton K.
Yeutter said in a statement.
   The agreement calls for the Soviets to buy at least 4 million
metric tons each of wheat and corn annually as well as 1 million
metric tons of additional wheat, corn, soybeans and soybean meal, or
any combination of those commodities.
   The Soviets also are allowed to purchase up to 3 million metric
tons of additional wheat and corn annually without further
discussions.
   Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., and chairman of the House Agriculture
Committee's subcommittee on wheat, soybeans and feed grains, said
the pact has ``done nothing more than maintain the current
agreement.''
   ``This was an historic opportunity with one of our most important
grain clients and all we can say is we didn't lose any ground,'' he
said. ``That simply isn't good enough.''
   ``This administration has driven down the price of grain in order
to export more, but they don't seem to be able to close the deal,''
he said.
   The Agriculture Department said the Soviets bought 9.05 million
tons of wheat, 5.18 million tons of corn, 830,700 tons of soybeans
and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal for delivery in the fifth and
final year of the current agreement.
   The Soviets purchased U.S. wheat for the final year and a half of
the old agreement at federally subsidized prices under the
government's Export Enhancement Program, designed to offset
competition from the European Community and other suppliers.
   Under the 1985 program, the Agriculture Department pays private
exporters in kind out of stocks held by the government-owned
Commodity Credit Corp. to ship the grain at highly attractive
prices. There are no dollar estimates for these sales.
   A provision of the old plan carried over into the new version
allows the Soviets to count one ton of soybeans or soybean meal as
two tons and thus round out their purchase obligation by buying
500,000 tons of those commodities rather than a million tons of
wheat or corn.
   ``In general our impression is favorable,'' American Farm Bureau
Federation spokesman Joe Fields said. ``It's a continuation of what
we had before, which worked fairly well.''
   Barry Jenkins, a spokesman for the National Association of Wheat
Growers, said his members were pleased with the agreement but had
hoped that the amounts would have been a bit larger.
   In any case, he said, the plan was likely to have less effect on
prices than will lingering problems caused by the drought. He said
markets mainly would be relieved to get some assurance of continued
Soviet demand.
   ``It's like a security blanket for some people,'' Jenkins said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
