<DOCNO> AP881129-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 0123EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SenateLeader-Profiles     11-29 1012</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Senate Leader-Profiles,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidates for Leadership of U.S. Senate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Following are profiles of the three candidates in today's
election of the next Senate majority leader:
^With PM-Senate Leader Bjt</NOTE>
<HEAD>GEORGE M. MITCHELL: Made His Name in Iran-Contra Hearings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. George Mitchell joined the Senate eight
years ago as an appointee who had never won election to public
office. But the Maine Democrat has since proven himself a popular
vote-getter, a thoughtful lawmaker and a telegenic party spokesman.
   Mitchell, a former federal judge, won praise for his incisive
questioning of witnesses before the Iran-Contra investigating panel
last year. He also hushed the hearing room with a statement as
dramatic as the emotional testimony of Lt. Col. Oliver North.
   ``Although he's regularly asked to do so, God does not take sides
in American politics,'' Mitchell lectured the Marine. ``And in
America, disagreement with the policies of the government is not
evidence of lack of patriotism.''
   Mitchell's Iran-Contra performance solidified his status as a
potential majority leader. He was first mentioned for the job in
1986 when, as the hard-working head of the Democrats' senatorial
campaign committee, he led his party back to control of the chamber.
   Mitchell, 55, had less legislative experience than his two
opponents for Senate majority leader and was perceived as more
liberal.
   As chairman of the Senate's environmental protection
subcommittee, Mitchell led a losing fight this year for an
anti-pollution bill designed to reduce acid rain, smog and airborne
toxic chemicals. His powerful opponents included the current Senate
majority leader, Robert Byrd of West Virginia, and Rep. John
Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee. Mitchell also chairs the Finance Committee's health panel
and has proposed a major long-term health care initiative.
   Mitchell was appointed to the Senate in 1980 to succeed Edmund
Muskie, whom he had served as an executive assistant two decades
earlier. He won election in 1982 with 61 percent of the vote and
garnered 81 percent this year.
   The son of a utility company laborer and a Lebanese immigrant
mother who worked the midnight shift at a woolen mill for 27 years,
Mitchell graduated from Bowdoin College, spent two years as an Army
intelligence officer and worked as an insurance claims adjuster
while attending night classes at Georgetown University law school.
   Mitchell lost a 1974 bid to become governor of Maine. He was
appointed U.S. attorney for the state in 1977 and two years later
was named to a new federal judgeship in Bangor.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>By Jill Lawrence</HEAD>
<HEAD>DANIEL K. INOUYE: A Deep-Voiced Presence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Daniel K. Inouye of Hawaii, the most senior of
three candidates for Senate majority leader, is known for his
solemn, deep-voiced presence which commands attention whether during
a floor debate or at a hearing.
   Inouye, who has been a senator since 1962, earned national
prominence first as keynote speaker at the Democratic National
Convention in 1968, then gained added respect as a member of the
Senate Watergate committee in 1973. But the gloss was dulled
somewhat last year when Inouye was criticized for not keeping a firm
enough handle on hearings before the Iran-Contra investigating panel
he helped chair.
   In that post and as former Intelligence Committee chairman and a
senior member of the Appropriations Committee, Inouye has prided
himself on being able to work closely with Republicans. But he also
has been a party loyalist, backing President Johnson's Vietnam War
policy and defending Sen. Harrison Williams, D-N.J., in 1981 against
expulsion in the Abscam case.
   His colleagues made him secretary of the Democratic Conference,
the No. 3 party leadership position, leading many to rank him a year
ago as the top prospect to succeed Robert Byrd of West Virginia as
majority leader. But in recent months, Inouye's chances seemed to
fade as some _ particularly newer senators _ searched for a less
ponderous figure to represent their numbers on television.
   Last year, Inouye was embarrassed after it was revealed that he
had slipped into a money bill $8 million for a school in France for
North African Jews. He later was forced to rescind the provision.
   In recent years, his voting record has tended toward the liberal
side: he has favored gun control, sanctions against South Africa and
limits on political action committee contributions to candidates. He
has opposed the Star Wars defense system and aid to the Nicaraguan
Contras.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>By Jim Drinkard</HEAD>
<HEAD>J. BENNETT JOHNSTON: Cagey in the Senate's Back Rooms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. J. Bennett Johnston is an accomplished
power broker with a reputation of knowing how to swing legislative
deals while protecting his own interests.
   The Louisianan is chairman of the Energy and Natural Resources
Committee and of the energy and water development appropriations
subcommittee, posts from which he watches out for his state and its
energy industry. That was seen by some observers as a possible
disadvantage in his race for majority leader, since the House
already is led by another oil and gas advocate, Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas.
   While known for an easygoing, quotable style, Johnston is quick
to master details of legislation, has a strong grasp of Senate
procedure and is considered a cagey backroom deal-maker.
   Johnston was more conservative than either of his two rivals for
majority leader. During his second term, he was a leading opponent
of court-ordered busing to desegregate schools.
   But he now casts himself as a centrist. He dramatically came out
against President Reagan's nomination of conservative Robert Bork to
the Supreme Court last year, supported a bill aimed at reducing
pollution that causes global warming, and fought Reagan's efforts to
finance the Star Wars missile defense system.
   In the majority leader's race, Johnston sold himself as the
candidate most likely to appeal to Middle America and thus as the
best standard-bearer for the Democratic Party. He picked up
endorsements from two of the party's stars, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of
Texas and Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia.
   Now 56, Johnston entered the Senate in 1973 after a nine-year
career in the Louisiana state legislature.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>By Alan Fram</HEAD>
</DOC>
