<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CrashVictims     11-29 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash Victims,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Offers Help Pour In for Young Suvivors Of Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALLEY CITY, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Callers from around the country have
offered money, stuffed animals and other help for three young
children who survived a car-train crash that killed their parents
and three siblings, officials said.
   Two funds also were opened for 6-year-old Wayne Nelson, his
brother Daniel, 4, and sister Melinda Jo, 5.
   Their parents, Arlynn, 41, and Theresa Nelson, 29, died last week
when a freight train smashed into their car at a fog-covered
railroad crossing five miles west of Valley City. Also killed were
the children's brother Michael, 9, and two sisters, 15-month-old
Michelle and 6-week-old Kelley.
   ``I have gotten calls from all over the country,'' said Gail
Pederson, a nursing supervisor at Mercy Hospital in Valley City,
where Wayne and Daniel remained hospitalized Monday in good
condition.
   Melinda Jo remained in critical condition Monday in St. Luke's
Hospitals in Fargo. Family members said she has had at least three
operations for severe head injuries and has a badly broken arm.
   In addition to the telephone inquiries, the two funds started for
the children have raised about $900.
   Mercy Hospital employees contributed about $200 to buy U.S.
savings bonds for the children, said Joan Stoltz, a hospital
supervisor. Another $700 has come into a separate trust at First
National Bank in Valley City, spokesman Doug Anderson said.
   The Nelson boys' hospital room also is filled with gifts, Stoltz
said.
   ``They have seven or eight stuffed animals apiece, balloons and
toys ... lots of toys,'' she said. ``About the only thing they're
running out of is batteries.''
   The two boys were released from the hospital briefly Saturday for
the family's funeral in Valley City, authorities said.
   The boys remain hospitalized only because arrangements about who
they will live with have not been decided, Barb Roeber, patient
services director, said Monday.
   The children's maternal grandmother, Anna Kunze of Valley City,
is their guardian and has been making medical decisions for them.
</TEXT>
