<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador     11-29 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Claim 266 Government Casualties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas said they
killed or wounded 266 government soldiers during a week of fighting
and said they were increasing their attacks in the capital.
   The casualty claim was broadcast Monday on the rebels'
clandestine Radio Venceremos. The broadcast provided no other
details on government casualties and did not report rebel losses for
the period Nov. 20-26.
   Radio Venceremos is run by the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front, the umbrella coalition of five rebel groups
fighting the U.S.-backed government for the past nine years.
   The Armed Forces Press Office on Monday said eight rebels were
killed and 30 more wounded in clashes with government troops Nov.
18-25. It did not report government casualties.
   Rebels also claimed responsibility for the assassination last
week of the mayor of Sesori, about 95 miles northeast of San
Salvador. Monday's broadcast accused Mayor Napoleon Villafuerte of
collaborating with an army counterinsurgency battalion operating in
the area.
   The army had said Villafuerte, of the right-wing Nationalist
Republican Alliance, was kidnapped on Wednesday. His body was found
Saturday outside Sesori.
   Monday's rebel broadcast said urban guerrillas were stepping up
their operations in San Salvador, the capital.
   ``The war is increasing on the outskirts of the capital where
permanent guerrilla forces and units operate constantly,'' it said.
   Urban guerrillas on Friday boarded a San Salvador city bus and
shot to death two soldiers and wounded a third, officials said. One
passenger was killed and three were seriously injured in a firefight
between the rebels and soldiers aboard the bus, a hospital spokesman
said.
   On Wednesday, urban guerrillas killed a soldier on a bus and
wounded another in a similar attack.
</TEXT>
