<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MercyKilling     11-29 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mercy Killing,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Rests Without Calling Any Witnesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for a pathologist
accused of murder in the mercy killing his cancer-stricken wife
rested his case without presenting any testimony, saying the state's
evidence was weak.
   ``Surprise, your honor, the defense rests,'' Stanley Rosenblatt,
attorney for Dr. Peter Rosier, said after a lunch break Monday.
   ``I don't think they came close to proving any crime.''
   Lee County Circuit Judge James Thompson, who rejected defense
requests for acquittal and a mistrial declaration, scheduled closing
arguments for Wednesday. He said he would meet with attorneys today
to prepare jury instructions.
   Rosier, 47, is charged with first-degree murder, attempted
first-degree murder and conspiracy to commit murder in the death of
his terminally ill wife, Patricia, nearly three years ago.
   During the Thanksgiving weekend, Rosenblatt discussed strategy
with his client. He said he considered putting the Rosiers' two
children, Jacob, 19, and Elizabeth, 22, on the stand as character
witnesses. The decision to rest without calling a witness was not
made until Monday, the attorney said.
   The decision means Rosenblatt will have the final say to the jury
in rebuttal remarks.
   The prosecution contended Mrs. Rosier failed in a suicide attempt
by taking 20 Seconal sedatives.
   Rosier, a retired Fort Meyers pathologist, then bungled an
attempt to kill his wife with morphine injections and suppositories,
so Mrs. Rosier's stepfather, Vincent Delman, smothered her to end
her suffering, Assistant State Attorney Ed Volz contended.
   The doctor hoped to profit from his wife's painful death through
his unpublished book, which he wanted to turn into a screenplay,
Volz maintained.
   Mrs. Rosier wanted to commit suicide to avoid a horrible death
from cancer that had spread from her lungs to other organs, said
Rosenblatt.
   Rosier acted out of compassion and did nothing that could have
killed his wife of 23 years, Rosenblatt said.
   Mrs. Rosier, 43, died Jan. 15, 1986. Her lagging health and death
were chronicled by a Fort Myers television station. Broadcasts
quoting Rosier as saying he played a role in her death prompted the
murder investigation.
   Before prosecutors knew of Delman's role, he was given immunity
in return for his testimony.
</TEXT>
