<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Unrest     11-29 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Portraits of Khomeini, Islamic Banners in Streets Of Baku</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 850 people were arrested in unrest
between ethnic Armenians and Azerbaijanis, and portraits of Iranian
leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini have appeared on the streets of
the Azerbaijani capital, Soviet media reported.
   The government newspaper Izvestia printed an interview with
26-year-old Nemat Panakhov, said to have led rallies by thousands of
protesters on Baku's Lenin Square.
   Izvestia correspondents asked him to explain why ``we saw green
flags and portraits of Khomeini on the square.'' It quoted Panakhov
as saying leaders of the protests rejected such appeals to Moslem
fundamentalism.
   Azerbaijanis are predominantly Moslem, and their neighbors the
Armenians are predominantly Christian. Both republics border on
Iran, and the Soviet Union is concerned about the possibility of
Khomeini's fundamentalist Moslem revolution in Iran spreading across
the frontier to Soviet Central Asia.
   No new outbreaks of violence were reported in the troubled
southern republics, where at least seven people, including four
soldiers, were killed in ethnic violence last week.
   A strict curfew remained in effect several cities, including Baku
and the Armenian capital, Yerevan. Soldiers and tanks patrolled the
streets.
   The Soviet TV news program ``Vremya'' said most factories in
Yerevan were closed Monday and the situation in Baku remained
``complicated and strained.''
   Official Baku radio, in a report monitored in London, said 867
people were arrested in the Azerbaijani capital on Sunday night and
Monday morning, and that 18 of them were jailed.
   Quoting a report from the city's military commandant, it said,
``There were about 10,000 people on Lenin Square while the curfew is
in force, many citizens are staying away from their houses and these
people are violating the special situation.''
   Armenian activist Rafael Popoyan said in a telephone interview
that Khachik Stamultyan, a recently elected deputy to the Armenian
Supreme Soviet, was detained and later released for speaking to a
crowd on a Yerevan street.
   Stamultyan is a member of the committee pressing to have the
predominantly Armenian enclave of Nagorno-Karabakh, which is inside
Azerbaijan, annexed to Armenia. Azerbaijan and national authorities
have rejected such a move.
   ``There is nothing new in the town (Yerevan),'' Popoyan said.
``Soldiers ask any group of more than three to disperse, even knots
of people at bus stops.''
   Officials and the state media have said three of the four dead
soldiers were killed in the first wave of violence last week in the
Azerbaijani cities of Nakhichevan and Kirovabad when Interior
Ministry troops stepped in to control rioting. The fourth death was
reported Sunday in the military newspaper Red Star, which said a
soldier was run over deliberately by a truck.
   The remaining three victims were Azerbaijanis, killed in
Kirovabad by soldiers for violating the 10 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew,
according to a local Communist Party official.
</TEXT>
