<HEAD>NOW Calls for Prosecution of Anti-Abortion Extremists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Organization for Women says the
Justice Department should use federal antitrust, racketeering and
civil rights laws to combat violence against abortion clinics.
   NOW President Molly Yard on Monday likened violent attacks on
abortion clinics to terrorism. Although the Reagan administration is
concerned enough with international terrorism to deny PLO leader
Yasser Arafat a visa to address the United Nations, it ``ignores the
terrorists already operating in this country,'' she said.
   Yard said at a news conference that the administration has made
little response to NOW's repeated requests for greater enforcement.
   The Justice Department, which refused comment, has prosecuted
some anti-abortion activists for civil rights violations in
connection with abortion clinic bombings.
