<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DormRules     11-29 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dorm Rules,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dorm Rules Slightly Relaxed, Still Ban Most Opposite Sex
Overnighters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boston University's slightly relaxed rules for
dormitory guests don't go far enough, said a student who helped
organize vigorous protests of a ban on overnight visitors of the
opposite sex.
   University President John Silber on Monday announced he had
accepted the recommendations of a task force that decided to allow
some overnight guests. The task force of parents, students, faculty
and school officials was commissioned after thousands of students
demonstrated against the ban.
   Silber limited overnight guests of the opposite sex to family
members. Visits between 11 p.m. and 1 a.m. would have to be approved
in writing by all roommates 24 hours in advance.
   But students remain forbidden from being overnight hosts to
unrelated members of the opposite sex, and Kevin Carleton, a
spokesman for the 27,000-student private school, said the rules
changes probably won't go into effect until next fall.
   The recommendations don't make the rules palatable because they
don't substantially change the original decision, said Susheel
Srikonda, who, along with another student, formed a group called
Active, Concerned, Together (ACT) to fight the new policies.
   ACT wanted to take a different approach that would emphasize
roommate approval and give the resident assistants who are in charge
of dormitories a larger role, he said.
   ``They are not changed that much,'' said Srikonda, a 20-year-old
computer science major.
   Carleton disagreed.
   ``The initial policy that was proposed was that there be no
overnight guests,'' he said. ``The tone of it was to discourage
overnight guests. This is saying that there certainly can be
overnight guests. It describes the format in which that can occur.''
   The ban, announced in September, drew wide attention, including
that of television talk-show host Phil Donahue, who visited campus
to interview administration officials and student leaders.
   Silber said he approved the ban because parents ``are, in a
proportion of about 30 to 1, (were) opposed to overnight visitors of
the opposite sex.''
   He conceded the university, which has a dormitory population of
about 8,500, cannot police dormitories rigorously but said the
school is obliged to discourage certain behavior.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
