<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Sakharov     11-29 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Sakharov,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sakharov Extends U.S. Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet human rights activist Andrei D.
Sakharov has extended his first visit to the West and is resting at
the home of his wife's children.
   The 67-year-old Nobel Prize-winning physicist, who arrived in the
United States on Nov. 4, originally was scheduled to return to
Moscow on Nov. 18.
   But after visiting New York and Washington, where he met
President Reagan, Sakharov spent Thanksgiving at the suburban Boston
home of Efrem and Tatiana Yankelevich, the daughter and son-in-law
of his wife, Yelena Bonner.
   The Yankeleviches, who moved to the United States more than a
decade ago, have zealously guarded Sakharov's privacy, screening all
calls, invitations and media inquiries.
   Tatiana Yankelevich said Monday the date of Sakharov's return was
uncertain. She said he was resting and working, but declined to say
what he was working on.
   Sakharov's wife remained in the Soviet Union.
   Sakharov has been an outspoken advocate for political prisoners
in the Soviet Union and has warned that there is a dangerous
domestic backlash to Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev's reforms.
</TEXT>
