<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Dali 1stLd-Writethru   11-29 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dali, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0479,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Artist In Critical Condition, But Slightly Improved</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS 4 grafs with slight improvement. Picks up graf 3 pvs,
`Dali, one ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors treating surrealist painter
Salvador Dali today said his condition improved slightly overnight,
although it remained extremely critical.
   The 84-year-old artist is suffering from severe heart trouble
aggravated by blood clots in the lungs, government spokeswoman Rosa
Conde said.
   After a brief visit to Quiron Clinic to see Dali, Ms. Conde told
reporters Dali's doctors said ``he is better now than he was last
night. He has improved despite remaining in extremely critical
condition.''
   ``His doctors say he has serious respiratory problems complicated
by heart trouble,'' but doctors are encouraged by his strong ``will
to live,'' she said.
   She said Dali had asked for a television or a radio in his room
to permit him to listen to news coverage of his hospital stay.
   Dali, one of the founders of the Surrealist movement and one of
the best-known living artists in the world, is the last member of an
outstanding generation of Spanish painters that included Pablo
Picasso, who died in 1973, and Joan Miro, who died a decade later.
   Barcelona Mayor Pasqual Maragall visited Dali early today for 10
minutes and told Spanish National Radio that Dali ``is lucid and
responds quickly when spoken to with a very vital look.''
   ``He has difficulty breathing,'' the mayor said. ``His doctor
says he is very critical and that there is a 48-hour period of
caution to determine exactly the danger he faces.''
   News reports indicated Dali had suffered a cold for several days
last week. He developed pneumonia and heart trouble, causing his
medical team to rush him to a local hospital Sunday in his hometown
of Figueras.
   On Monday night, doctors ordered him transferred by ambulance
under police escort to the Quiron Clinic in Barcelona, 60 miles
south, where he was immediately placed in the intensive care unit
for treatment, his doctors said.
   Since August 1984 Dali has been in poor health as a result of
third-degree burns he suffered in an electrical fire that broke out
in the bedroom of his home in the village of La Pera, 40 miles south
of Figueras.
   The brush with death kept him bound to a wheelchair or in bed and
required that he be fed by tube. A team of nurses watched over him
around the clock since the fire.
   In July 1986 Dali received a heart pacemaker in surgery done in a
Barcelona hospital.
   Dali has lived in seclusion and suffered from frequent bouts of
depression since the death in 1982 of his wife, Gala, his principal
muse during a 50-year period of his career.
</TEXT>
