<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hirohito     11-29 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito's Temperature, Other Vital Signs Soar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito's temperature and other vital signs
soared today, 72 days after he fell ill with abdominal bleeding, the
Imperial Palace said.
   The emperor had a fever of 102 at dusk, well above his normal
95.9 and among the worst readings recorded since he first vomited
large amounts of blood on Sept. 19.
   Hirohito's breathing quickened and his pulse rose to 115 beats
per minute from recent levels of below 100, palace spokesman Kenji
Maeda said.
   Officials had no further comment on his condition except to say
chief physician Akira Takagi stayed beyond his normal hours tonight
at Hirohito's chambers in Fukiage Palace.
   Earlier today, Maeda said it was difficult to tell whether the
87-year-old monarch was asleep or awake. News reports say he is
losing consciousness and family members say he sleeps through their
visits.
   Doctors have transfused 45.4 pints of blood into him to combat
the bleeding and control his anemia. Hirohito has eaten almost
nothing in 72 days. There has been no official confirmation of
reports he had cancer.
   Hirohito ascended the Chrysanthemum Throne on Christmas Day 1926
and has reigned almost 62 years, longer than any of the world's
living monarchs. After Japan's defeat in World War II he became a
largely powerless symbol of the state.
</TEXT>
