<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 0759EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-NewSenators 1stLd-Writethru a0421 11-29 0891</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Senators, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0421,880</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS graf 24, Sen.-elect, to correct Robb's party</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Orientation Day for the Senate's Class of '88</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the 10 men who will take their places
as freshman U.S. senators next year felt awed by a sense of history,
but others simply wanted to find their way from here to there.
   Monday was orientation day for the Senate class of 1988. And
while the five Democrats and five Republicans all talked of tackling
the federal government's massive deficit, their immediate concerns
were more mundane: staff and office space, telephones, security and
legislative procedure.
   Committee assignments were a pressing matter.
   There was much talk of exactly how low their place will be in the
pecking order of the Senate's seniority system.
   ``Everybody's worrying about numbers _ whether they'll be number
95, 96, 97, 98 or whatever,'' said Sen.-elect Conrad Burns, R-Mont.
``I said, `Boys, you can't get any lower than 100!'''
   That's Burns' number. One hundred _ and dead last in seniority.
   Rep. Connie Mack, R-Fla., figured he would be about 94th in
seniority when all was said and done.
   ``What does that get you?'' he was asked.
   ``Not very much, to tell you the truth,'' he replied.
   There are other numbers involved.
   Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., an ardent amateur historian who keeps
track of such things, says that since the first Senate convened in
1789 there have been precisely 1,782 United States senators.
   When the 10 newcomers are sworn in with the convening of the
101st Congress in January, they will be numbered 1,783 to 1,792,
depending how on the final determination of their seniority is made
under the Senate's complicated rules and procedures for such things.
   But for now, some of the members of the class of '88 were fairly
glowing, even as they paid attention to what several called the
``nuts and bolts'' details of Senate life.
   ``It's a special day, a red letter day, a very personal day that
you'll never forget,'' said Sen.-elect Herb Kohl, D-Wis. ``But it's
also like going to college as a freshman.
   ``Think of it. Father and mother immigrants _ 65 years ago _ had
nothing. And now their son is a United States senator.''
   The son has a little more than nothing. A multimillionaire who
spent some $5 million on his election campaign, Kohl is owner of the
Milwaukee Bucks basketball team.
   Burns, a Montana farm broadcaster who upset Sen. John Melcher,
D-Mont., was asked to name the biggest challenge he faces as a new
senator.
   ``The biggest challenge to me is getting from here to there
without walking through all these cameras,'' he said, waving a hand
toward the forest of television cameras sprouting from the floor of
a Senate corridor.
   The new Democratic senators quickly found themselves the center
of attention from three Senate veterans _ Sens. Daniel K. Inouye,
D-Hawaii, Bennett Johnston, D-La., and George Mitchell, D-Maine. All
sought votes in their bids to succeed Byrd as Senate majority leader.
   Kohl said he would vote for Mitchell because ``he's a person I
feel comfortable with.''
   Joe Lieberman of Connecticut said he would make up his mind at
the last minute, adding that because he didn't know any of the three
candidates all that well, ``it comes down to a decision you make in
your gut.''
   Still, there was a sense of wonder at being in a position to make
such a choice at all.
   ``I feel a sense of history,'' said Lieberman. ``It's not going
to be an easy time to be a United States senator,'' he said, citing
budget deficits, taxes and environmental problems.
   Sen.-elect Charles Robb, a Democratic former governor of
Virginia, was told that the most frustrated senators are former
governors, shorn of the ability to make executive decisions on their
own authority.
   ``Thou sayest it,'' said Robb, who had little to say on any other
subject.
   Three members of the House _ Mack, Trent Lott, R-Miss., and James
Jeffords, R-Vt. _ are moving across the Capitol to the Senate.
   For Mack, being one of 100 senators is a lot better than being
one of 435 members of the House with its restrictive traffic-cop
rules.
   ``You have a much greater opportunity in the Senate to influence
legislation on the floor,'' Mack said.
   But for Lott, becoming a member of the Senate wasn't an automatic
step up. He gave up his No. 2 position in the House Republican
leadership to run for the seat being vacated by Sen. John Stennis,
D-Miss., a Senate veteran.
   ``You look at the House and the Senate and there certainly are a
lot of differences,'' Lott grumbled. ``Like why it takes three
months in the Senate to move in 10 guys when in the House they move
in 43 people in 30 days.''
   One new senator-to-be, Washington state Republican Slade Gorton,
was making his second debut as a freshman. He was defeated by
Democrat Brock Adams in 1986 but reinstated by the voters on Nov. 8.
   Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., who has been in the Senate for eight
years, was asked if he had any advice for the newcomers.
   ``I'll tell them to pray a lot,'' he said, grinning.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Lawrence L. Knutson covers Congress for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
