<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SAfrica-Press 1stLd-Writethru a0509 11-29 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Press, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0509,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cabinet Minister Seeks Damages From Paper</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS publisher of New Nation in 7th graf pvs ``On
Friday..''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cabinet minister with the
power to close newspapers is demanding damage payments from a major
paper because it published an article poking fun at him and a
critical letter from a reader, the newspaper said today.
   Home Affairs Minister Stoffel Botha's action against The Star
follows similar demands last week directed at a black newspaper he
has already closed once, and at the editor of an anti-apartheid
newspaper now under suspension.
   Botha has the power under the 29-month state of emergency to
close newspapers without giving reasons. Three newspapers have been
closed temporarily by him this year.
   State-of-emergency regulations restrict reporting about unrest,
security force actions, treatment of detainees, some forms of
protest, and a range of statements the government considers
subversive. Enforcement of the regulations has not been
comprehensive.
   The Star said Botha, through the state attorney, was demanding
100,000 rand ($41,800) for defamation and impairment of his dignity.
   The newspaper said police are also investigating it for alleged
violations of laws dealing with the police and prisons, because of a
photograph and a guest editorial it published.
   On Friday, Botha demanded damage payments from New Nation, a
black newspaper published by the Southern African Catholic Bishops
Conference, for publishing excerpts of a speech by Anton Harber,
co-editor of The Weekly Mail. In the speech, Harber criticized
Botha's three-month banning of his newspaper and referred to the
Cabinet minister as narrow-minded.
   Botha is threatening to sue New Nation and Harber a total of
100,000 rand ($41,800) unless they pay him directly.
   The Weekly Mail is due to resume publishing Friday. New Nation
resumed publication June 30, after Botha banned it for three months.
   The government also has threatened action against a new
Afrikaans-language weekly, Vrye Weekblad, for allegedly promoting
the aims of outlawed organizations such as the African National
Congress.
   Botha's allegation that The Star defamed him is based in part on
a feature Nov. 13 in the paper's Sunday magazine. The article said,
``On the political gossip front, it's hard to beat the restaurant at
the Houses of Parliament. This star-studded setting inspires
comments like, `Stoffel Botha's the only man I know who walks
upright without a spine.'''
   The other item in The Star cited by Botha was a letter to the
editor from a reader, David Mumford, published on Nov. 14. The
letter described Botha as ``a greater danger to South Africa than
the ANC,'' and criticized the banning of The Weekly Mail.
   The Star said police were investigating the paper because of an
Aug. 23 article by a member of the Black Sash, a civil rights group,
criticizing pending legislation to increase evictions of black
squatters and because of the publication of a photograph of
imprisoned ANC leader Nelson Mandela.
   It is illegal in South Africa to publish pictures of Mandela, but
a Star editor said the only picture of him the paper had published
was one taken from a government publication.
   The ANC is the chief guerrilla movement fighting to overthrow the
South African government and end apartheid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
