<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 0920EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShoppingBandit     11-29 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shopping Bandit,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Robber Hit Bank, Then Went On Shopping Spree,</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of robbing a bank couldn't
resist the urge to do a little Christmas shopping, so he hired a
taxi outside the bank and rode from store to store for more than an
hour before he was arrested.
   By the time police caught up with Willie Carroll Williams, 37, of
Atlanta, on Monday, the cab was stuffed with shopping bags full of
shirts, shoes and pants, officers said.
   ``When you've got the money, you might as well spend it,'' the
cab driver, who asked not be identified, quoted his passenger as
saying.
   According to police, Williams phoned for the cab at about the
same time Coast Federal Savings and Loan was robbed. Authorities did
not release the dollar loss in the robbery, a policy followed with
federal banks, said Sarasota police Sgt. Michael Schott.
   After hopping into the cab outside the bank, Williams stopped at
the Sarasota-Bradenton Airport to buy plane tickets, and then
visited several shopping centers _ running up a cab fare of $26.70.
   ``I was cracking up most of the time I was in the cab with him,''
said the cab driver. ``He was having a good time.''
   Bank employees told police they thought the suspect fled in a
taxi.
   When detectives finally tracked down the vehicle, they were
surprised to learn that the suspect was still riding around
shopping, police spokesman Michael Schott said.
   Williams was charged with armed robbery and was being held in
lieu of $10,000 bail.
</TEXT>
