<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 0923EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CadetInquest     11-29 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cadet Inquest,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brother Says He Is Looking For Vengeance In Cadet's Inquest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has opened an inquest behind
closed doors into the death of a police cadet who collapsed on the
first day of training, one of 16 cadets from the class who were
hospitalized.
   ``The bottom line is to determine whether or not one or more
persons violated criminal law or acted in criminal negligence,''
District Court Judge Irving Goldblatt said in an unusual news
conference before the proceeding began Monday.
   Timothy Shepard, 25, died Nov. 2 of blood poisoning and other
complications from the heat stroke he suffered Sept. 19 at the
regional police academy in Agawam. Fifteen other cadets among the
class of 50 were hospitalized for exhaustion and dehydration.
   He lingered for 44 days and underwent a liver transplant.
   Goldblatt said his report and witnesses' testimony will be made
public only if there are no grounds for criminal charges. But if the
judge sees evidence of a crime, the report and testimony will be
submitted to the district attorney, who will proceed to a grand
jury, he said.
   The judge also plans to visit the Agawam academy, one of six
regional centers operated by the state to train local police.
   Shepard's brother, father and widow were among the dozen people
at the inquest.
   ``I hope anybody responsible for Timmy being where he is right
now will be paid big time,'' said Christopher Shepard, 21, of
Pittsfield. ``I want them punished ... all of them.''
   Michael Hashim, an attorney for the Shepard family, said he
expected the testimony to take at least three weeks. The judge's
report is expected to take several more weeks.
   Hashim said the Shepards are the only people allowed to attend
the inquest daily, although the mother of another cadet went to the
courthouse in the vain hope of watching the proceeding.
   ``I want to know that justice is done. I felt so helpless
watching this go on,'' said the woman, who declined to give her name.
   Hashim has said the Shepard family wants criminal charges filed
against the cadet's trainers, State Troopers Blake Gilmore and John
Richardson. They led six other troopers in directing training on the
first day of the 14-week session.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
