<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru   11-29 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0496,0706</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Wound A Dozen Palestinians</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to ADD today's developments, move up violence. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HAITHAM HAMAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops reportedly
shot and ounded at least a dozen Palestinians today as
stone-throwing demonstrations erupted in four towns or cities in the
occupied territories.
   The violence broke out as some Palestinians went on strike in
response to a call by Hamas, a Moslem fundamentalist group at odds
with the PLO-backed United Leadership of the Uprising.
   To try to block anti-Israeli violence during the strike, the army
imposed curfews on 14 refugee camps and villages in the Gaza Strip
as well as seven West Bank cities and towns, confining 370,000
residents to their homes.
   The army also strengthened patrols and made preventive arrests to
reduce the likelihood of clashes.
   Troops clashed with demonstrators in the Gaza village of
Jabaliya, wounding three Palestinians, including a 33-year-old woman
who was shot in the stomach and a 14-year-old boy who was hit in the
chest, officials at the Ahli Arab hospital said.
   Nine Palestinians also were reported wounded by army gunfire in
the West Bank city of Nablus and the nearby villages of Tamoun and
Beit Leid. One of the wounded was a 10-year-old boy shot in the left
leg, hospital officials said.
   At least 316 Palestinians and 11 Israelis have been killed in the
nearly year-long revolt against Israeli occupation.
   About 1.5 million Palestinians live in the West Bank and Gaza,
occupied by Israel from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   In the biblical town of Bethlehem today, youths from rival
Palestinian factions, some brandishing knives and clubs, shouted
threats at each other today in a dispute over the strike called by
Hamas, Arabic for zeal.
   The dispute stems from a Nov. 17 declaration by the Palestine
National Congress, the PLO's parliament-in-exile, accepting U.N.
resolutions that implicitly recognize Israel.
   The strike was to mark the anniversary of one of those
resolutions, a 1947 recommendation that Palestine be partitioned
into Jewish and Arab states.
   Members of Hamas marched through the city forcing stores shut.
Slogans scribbled in green paint on city walls warned merchants,
``Today is a strike day, be sure you observe it.'' Green is the
traditional color of Islam.
   Leaders of the United Leadership of the Uprising, who ordered
their own strike a day earlier, demanded shopkeepers open their
stores in defiance of the fundamentalists. They kicked closed shop
doors, shouting to owners that they would protect them from the
Islamic extremists if the shops opened.
   The strike was widely observed in the occupied Gaza Strip and
West Bank and Arab east Jersualem. The city of Hebron, where Hamas
is a dominant Palestinian faction, was totally shuttered.
   In Ramallah, north of Jerusalem, stores were closed, but people
could be seen going to work in offices on upper stories of buildings.
   One shopkeeper said stores were closed because youths from Hamas
threatened to stone those that opened. As reporters walked away, an
elderly man told the shopkeeper, ``Don't tell these things to
outsiders.''
   Palestinian officials have canceled Christmas celebrations in
Bethlehem, where Christ was born, in solidarity with the Palestinian
revolt.
   ``We don't see any reason to celebrate Christmas,'' Bethlehem
Deputy Mayor Hanna Nasser said Monday. ``We have to show concern for
our dead and for our detainees.''
   Nasser said the town government called off all official
celebrations, such as the Christmas Eve reception for Israeli and
Palestinian dignitaries and the annual Boy Scout parade.
   Manger Square, usually decorated with bright strings of colored
lights, will remain dark and its 40-foot Christmas tree will be left
bare, he said.
   Meanwhile, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin today urged his Labor
Party to consider joining a coalition government led by the rival
Likud bloc in order to withstand demands for controversial religious
legislation.
   On Monday, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc
asked the Labor Party to join a new coalition government, offering
the rival party two of the four most powerful Cabinet posts.
   Labor leaders are meeting Wednesday to consider the offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
