<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 0949EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-HamadiTrial     11-29 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Hamadi Trial,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness Says Hijackers Threatened to Kill An American Every Five
Minutes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former hostage in the 1985
hijacking of a TWA jetliner testified today the hijackers threatened
to kill an American passenger every five minutes unless their
demands for fuel were met.
   Debra Toga, a 30-year-old nurse who was seven months pregnant at
the time of the incident, also said that at one point one of the
hijackers held a gun to her head.
   Mrs. Toga testified at the trial of confessed TWA hijacker
Mohammed Ali Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem charged with murder
and air piracy in the June 1985 hijacking. Navy diver Robert Stethem
was killed in the ordeal and 39 Americans were hostage for 17 days.
   Mrs. Toga, who was returning from a three-week vacation with her
husband Arthur when the Athens-to-Rome flight was seized, said she
was not mistreated by the hijackers, but heard other passengers
being beaten.
   She said that during a stop in Algiers, the hijackers said they
would start killing Americans if the airplane was not refueled.
   ``Uli Derickson (the flight purser) told me that they were
threatening to kill one American passenger every five minutes,''
Mrs. Toga said.
   The plane was refueled and flew to Beirut airport.
   Mrs. Toga also said that Hamadi at one point reassured her she
was safe.
   ``I was crying, but Hamadi told me that I had nothing to worry
about. He said they were interested only in young American men, but
they respected women and children,'' Mrs. Toga said.
   Stethem was killed at Beirut airport. Hamadi admits he was one of
the hijackers, but denies shooting Stethem.
   Mrs. Toga said the other hijacker _ fugitive Hassan Ezzeddine _
threatened her with a gun just before she was freed in Algiers.
   ``I was chosen to leave the plane, and at that point I saw my
husband. I wanted to stay with my husband, but the other hijacker
put the gun to my head and told me to get out,'' she testified.
   Under guidelines set by the court, Mrs. Toga was not required to
disclose her hometown. At the time of the hijacking she and her
husband lived in St. Louis, Mo.
   Before Mrs. Toga's testimony, prosecutors disclosed that they had
had Hamadi's cell searched during the weekend for secret
communications the defendant may have received from acquaintances in
Beirut.
   Prosecutor Peter Korneck said some documents were taken from the
cell and photocopied, but he did not say what they were.
   Both Hamadi and his defense attorneys charged the search was
illegal and asked that Korneck be dropped from the case. Judge
Heiner Mueckenberger made no ruling on the motion.
   The defense attorneys also asked that officials from American
television networks be called to testify at the trial.
   The attorneys said they had asked the FBI and the U.S. Justice
Department for permission to examine tapes made during the hijacking
but there had been no reply. They indicated they wanted the network
officials to present the tapes in court.
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt Airport in January 1987 after
customs officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
</TEXT>
