<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1009EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AfricaTalks     11-29 0141</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Africa Talks,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Round Set For Brazzaville</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The final round of formal negotiations to pave
the way for Namibian independence and Cuban troop withdrawal from
Angola is due to begin tomorrow in Brazzaville, The Congo.
   Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker will attend the
two-day session as the U.S. representative as the negotiators try to
wrap up such technical details as verifying the Cuban pullout.
   ``This is what we have called the final round of formal
negotiations, so the parties will go there for that purpose,''
Charles E. Redman, the State Department spokesman, said Monday.
``And then we will see what happens.''
   During the Brazzaville session, the negotiators are expected to
set a date and a site for a final signing of a complicated accord
for Cuban withdrawal and South Africa's relinquishing its control
over Namibia.
</TEXT>
