<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1103EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GoodSamaritan     11-29 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Good Samaritan,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Shot Muggers Sentenced on Drug Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``good Samaritan'' who shot two muggers asked
for leniency on a 1987 drug conviction, but a judge who imposed a
stiff sentence said he did not want to send a message to the public
that it is ``OK to go and kill people.''
   State Supreme Court Justice Joseph Slavin sentenced Clovis Fearon
to 1{ to 4{ years in prison, only slightly less than the maximum
two- to six-year sentence he could have received.
   ``If he's such a fine person, why did he have a Brazilian-made
Saturday night special?'' Slavin said at the sentencing Monday.
``You said you want to be an honest citizen; well, you can be an
honest citizen when you get out of jail.''
   Fearon, who came to New York from Jamaica five years ago, had
pleaded guilty in February 1987 to felony charges for directing two
undercover police officers to a drug dealer who sold them two vials
of crack.
   A fugitive since March 1987 who had been living under an assumed
name, Fearon's identity was revealed Nov. 2 when he came to the
rescue of a woman being robbed on the street outside his home. He
killed one man and wounded another, using an unregistered handgun.
   ``I knew that getting involved could lead to my exposure,''
Fearon said at his sentencing. ``I did not want to get involved, but
I knew I had to do something to help.''
   Slavin last year had promised Fearon a sentence of one day in
jail and five years probation on the drug conviction, but had warned
him if he did not appear for sentencing he would impose a two- to
six-year prison term.
   Fearon, who read from a written statement, told the judge Monday
that the reason he did not come to his sentencing was that an
immigration lawyer had told him that he could be deported to Jamaica.
   ``I was afraid. I did not want to go back to Jamaica because I
love America. I know it is the land of opportunity,'' Fearon said.
   He said that after he became a fugitive he made a vow to himself
to be a law-abiding citizen and had worked as many as three jobs at
a time to support a wife and two children in Jamaica.
   Slavin said he reduced the sentence ``for his _ quote _
`heroism.''' But the judge chided Fearon for going underground and
changing his name and for owning the unlicensed gun which he used to
shoot the two muggers.
   Fearon must serve the minimum of 1{ years before being eligible
for parole.
   The mugging victim, Gertrude George, was not in court on Monday
but had sent Slavin a letter urging him to be lenient. He had also
received 50 other letters of support and petitions signed by people
who lived in Fearon's neighborhood of East Flatbush.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881129-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1105EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Lawyer     11-29 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Lawyer,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Says Ohio Court Erroneously Upheld Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court ruled today that an Ohio
court erroneously upheld the rape, robbery and assault convictions
of a man whose court-appointed lawyer withdrew from the case.
   In an 8-1 decision, the high court said the Ohio Court of Appeals
should not have decided on Steven Anthony Penson's appeal of rape,
robbery and assault convictions without first appointing a new
attorney to handle the case.
   ``The need for forceful advocacy does not come to an abrupt halt
as the legal proceeding moves from the trial to appellate stage,''
Justice John Paul Stevens wrote for the court, which ordered further
hearings on the case.
   Stevens said the Ohio tribunal ``erred by failing to appoint new
counsel to represent petitioner'' after determining that Penson's
case raised several possible legal issues for appellate review.
   Penson's original court-appointed lawyer was allowed to withdraw
from the appeal after filing a statement that he found no legal
errors by the trial judge that required reversal of the convictions.
   The appeals court then denied Penson's request for a new lawyer
but later reviewed the trial record and found that the defendant had
``several arguable claims.''
   The court reversed one of the three convictions stemming from
Penson's involvement with two other men in the Aug. 4, 1984,
break-in of a Montgomery County, Ohio, home.
   But it ultimately concluded that Penson ``suffered no prejudice''
from his court-appointed lawyer's ``failure to give a more
conscientious examination of the record'' and upheld the remaining
two convictions.
   Penson, who is serving an 18-to-28-year sentence, was one of
three men convicted of breaking into the home and sexually
assaulting a man and two women, who were also robbed.
   Stevens said the Ohio court violated standards set by the high
court in a 1967 opinion for judging the effectiveness of
court-appointed lawyers handling appeals.
   ``Both stages of the prosecution, although perhaps involving
unique legal skills, require careful advocacy to ensure that rights
are not foregone and that substantial legal and factual arguments
are not inadvertently passed over,'' Stevens wrote in an opinion
that drew a dissent from Chief Justice William Rehnquist.
   ``It bears emphasis that the right to be represented by counsel
is among the most fundamental rights,'' Stevens wrote.
   ``We have long recognized that `lawyers in criminal courts are
necessities, not luxuries','' the court's majority said, quoting
from its landmark 1963 decision in Gideon v. Wainwright that
mandated court-appointed lawyers for indigent defendants.
   But Rehnquist called the decision ``a futile monument to the
court's effort to guarantee to the indigent appellant what no court
can guarantee him: exactly the same sort of legal services that
would be provided suitably by retained private counsel.''
   Rehnquist said the Ohio court's review of the trial record
without assistance of Penson's lawyer resulted in the proper finding
that the defendant's rights were not prejudiced.
   But the court's majority rejected this view, saying that the Ohio
tribunal could not justify its refusal to appoint a new lawyer on
the ground there was no merit to Penson's appeal.
   ``Finding harmless error or a lack of... prejudice in cases such
as this, however, would leave criminal appealants without any
protections'' under the 1967 decision, Stevens wrote.
   The case is Penson v. Ohio, 87-6116.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
