<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinberg,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness: Steinberg Slapped Child for No Asparent Reason</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man on trial for murder in the beating of his
illegally adopted daughter once whacked the sleeping 6-year-old in
the face ``out of the clear blue sky,'' a witness testified.
   The witness, alleged drug dealer Charles Scannapieco, on Monday
became the first person to testify that he actually saw Joel
Steinberg, a now-disbarred lawyer, strike Lisa Steinberg.
   Scannapieco said Steinberg hit the girl hard enough ``to bring
tears'' and for no apparent reason.
   Meanwhile, Steinberg faces a $3 million lawsuit filed by his
former live-in lover, Hedda Nussbaum. The suit, filed in state court
Monday, alleges Steinberg assaulted and tortured her for most of the
11 years they lived together.
   Nussbaum also charged that he used humiliation, brainwashing,
drugs and the withholding of food to teach her that ``she was a
worthless person who could only be saved through his wisdom and
special powers.''
   Nussbaum is expected to testify against Steinberg in the murder
trial.
   Scannapieco, who has been indicted on narcotics charges, had
hired Steinberg to represent him. Scannapieco said he saw Steinberg
strike Lisa on Oct. 23, 1987, as Steinberg drove them to
Scannapieco's home in Lake Katrine in upstate New York.
   More than 20 witnesses have testified against Steinberg so far,
but Scannapieco is the first to report having seen Steinberg strike
the girl.
   ``Right after she fell asleep,'' Scannapieco said, ``right out of
the clear blue sky, Mr. Steinberg took his hand and went ...
(demonstrating the blow) SMASH!''
   State Supreme Court Justice Harold Rothwax struck the word
``smash'' from the record at the request of Steinberg's lawyer, Ira
London.
   Demonstrating the blow, Scannapieco slammed the back of his hand
against the judge's bench. The judge, Steinberg and the jurors
seemed startled. Steinberg smiled and shook his head as if in
disbelief at Scannapieco's dramatic gesture.
   Scannapieco said the slap on the right side of Lisa's face ``was
pretty forceful, enough to bring tears to your eyes.''
   She woke up and looked at Steinberg, who told her to ``stop
staring at him and keep blinking and smiling. Keep blinking and
smiling _ that's what she was told to do,'' Scannapieco said. He
said Steinberg told Lisa this five or six times.
   Steinberg did not seem angry, Scannapieco said.
   Scannapieco said Steinberg told him he hit the child because she
sometimes slowed her heart and breathing, putting herself into a
near coma. He quoted Steinberg as saying it was a medical condition
that ``got so serious one time that he had to put her in the
hospital.''
   Lisa was removed unconscious from Steinberg's Greenwich Village
apartment on Nov. 2, 1987, and died of head injuries three days
later.
   Steinberg has denied hitting the child. He has said she fell
unconscious after choking on food and that he caused bruises on her
chest and back while trying to revive her.
   A report in Monday's New York Newsday quoted court sources as
saying that in the month before Lisa's death, Steinberg free-based
cocaine nightly from a kilogram that had been left with him for
safekeeping by a client.
</TEXT>
