<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Austria-NobilityDeaths     11-29 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Austria-Nobility Deaths,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Princess Died Of Cocaine Overdose, Prince Shot Himself</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cocaine overdose killed a young princess
whose husband, a great-grandson of Germany's last emperor,
subsequently killed himself in shock and grief, police said today.
   Isabelle of Hanover, 26, was found dead Monday by her husband,
Prince Ludwig Rudolf, in the bedroom of their villa at Gmunden, a
lakeside resort in Upper Austria's Salzkammergut lake district.
   Police sources in Gmunden and in Linz, the capital of Upper
Austria province, said today a preliminary autopsy showed the
Austrian-born princess died of heart and lung edema after consuming
cocaine.
   A spokesman for Upper Austria security police who asked not to be
identified said syringes and a small amount of ``powder'' were found
near the body of the princess.
   The Austria Press Agency, quoting a source in the public
prosecutor's office, said the powder was cocaine.
   The public prosecutor's office at Wels, Upper Austria, said
investigators found punctures on the arms of the dead prince and
princess, suggesting both used narcotics.
   The result of an official post-mortem was expected later this
week. Police said the case also is under court investigation.
   The 33-year-old prince, a relative of the British, Greek and
Spanish royal families, was found shot to death near a lake at
Almtal, a wooded area some 20 miles from Gmunden, police said. His
hunting rifle was beside him, police said.
   The couple is survived by their infant son, Prince Otto, who
slept next door to the bedroom where his mother was found dead,
Austrian newspapers said.
   Police said the prince and his wife dined Sunday night with
members of a West German pop group.
   The princess retired early and was found dead by her husband at
2:45 a.m. The prince called the Red Cross and told them his wife had
``probably taken cocaine,'' a police spokesman said.
   Prince Ludwig Rudolf, the second of three sons of Prince Ernst
August of Hanover, was the grandson of Emperor Wilhelm II's daughter
Viktoria Luise of Brunswick-Luneburg.
   The couple was part of the European jet set, moving in the world
of rock music and fashion. The prince spent many years in London,
and the princess attended a fashionable school in England.
</TEXT>
