<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-LiteraryPrizes     11-29 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Literary Prizes,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bernard-Henri Levy Wins Prize For Life of Baudelaire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYLYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bernard-Henri Levy, the ``enfant terrible'' of
French intellectuals, won the prestigious Interallie literary prize
today for his account of the decadent life of Romantic poet Charles
Baudelaire.
   ``The Last Days of Charles Baudelaire,'' a best-seller, is a
fictionalized biography of the 19th century author known for the
sensory imagery of his ``Flowers of Evil,'' a poetry collection
condemned in its time for obscenity.
   In his book, Levy created dialogue spoken by Baudelaire, his
mixed-race lover, his mother and his publisher to recount the
agonizing last years of a religious mystic who frequented Paris
prostitutes and died of syphilis.
   The 39-year-old Levy, known as a ``new philosopher,'' catapulted
to intellectual stardom in 1977 when he attacked Marxism, claiming
it inevitably led to totalitarianism.
   Last year, in ``L'Eloge des Intellectuals,'' (In Praise of
Intellectuals), Levy lambasted French intellectuals for remaining
silent on important social and political issues.
   In 1981, he provoked debate with ``L'Ideologie Francaise,''
(French Ideology) an essay denouncing the French mentality that
produced a World War II government that collaborated with the Nazi
occupation.
   Levy's best-selling ``Le Diable en Tete'' (The Devil Ahead), a
20th century epic, was published in 1984.
   Brilliant, handsome and not one to mince words, Levy once
described himself as ``the best writer and the most talented
essayist of my generation.''
   The winner of the Interallie prize, sponsored by the Cercle
Interallie, is awarded $765.
   This year's Chateaubriand prize was awarded today to
Jean-Francois Revel, 64, a conservative political pundit, for his
life's work.
   Revel, who is known for his writings about American society and
politics, recently wrote ``La Connaissance Inutile,'' (Useless
Knowledge). The book is a bitter attack on the news media for its
tendency to spread disinformation.
   ``The enemy is no longer ignorance, but lies,'' Revel wrote.
   The Chateaubriand prize, whose winner receives $8,500, is
sponsored by the Comite du Rayonnement Francais, an organization
that promotes French culture.
   Although the Chateaubriand has a bigger purse, the Interallie is
considered more prestigious and therefore a greater spur to book
sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881129-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1225EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NukePlant-Inspections     11-29 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuke Plant-Inspections,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Circuit Breaker Inspections Ordered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission has ordered
the nation's 110 nuclear plants to locate and test possibly
counterfeit and faulty circuit breakers installed in safety systems,
an NRC spokesman confirmed today.
   Spokesman Frank Ingram said a Nov. 22 bulletin issued by the
commission found that recent inspections ``indicate a potential
safety concern regarding electrical equipment supplied to nuclear
power plants.''
   However, a counterfeit or faulty breaker has never been blamed
for any kind of incident at a nuclear plant, Ingram said.
   The order for inspections, which must be carried out by March 1,
followed an NRC investigation that found four Southern California
companies had allegedly sold counterfeit breakers to nuclear plants.
   Pacific Gas & Electric reported in July that it had found 30
counterfeit breakers in its inventory at the Diablo Canyon nuclear
plant near San Luis Obispo.
   Southern California Edison Co. found in the same month that it
had bought 16 potentially counterfeit breakers for its San Onofre
plant, 55 miles south of Los Angeles.
   The NRC said in the bulletin that the inspections are necessary
``to provide reasonable assurance that nuclear power plants can be
operated without undue risk to the public health and safety.''
   The NRC has found ``numerous failures'' of certain types of
circuit breakers during preliminary commission-supervised tests, the
bulletin said.
   If a potentially counterfeit breaker is found already installed _
and it cannot be immediately tested _ the utility must submit ``an
analysis justifying continued operation,'' the bulletin said.
   The Los Angeles Times reported today that the inspection plan was
criticized in a memorandum attached to the bulletin by Underwriters
Laboratory, a nonprofit testing agency that certifies circuit
breakers.
   ``The test program is not adequate to provide assurance that the
tested ... circuit breakers would be suitable for their intended
purpose,'' the laboratory said.
   The NRC responded by saying that it ``considers the test program
to provide a reasonable assurance of performance requirements and
characteristics most important to ensuring reactor safety.''
   The NRC has told utilities that more than 50 companies may be
counterfeiting circuit breakers and other electrical components.
   PG&E spokesman Dick Davin said the utility was still evaluating
the order and how it would affect the Diablo Canyon nuclear plant.
   Southern California Edison Co. spokesman Dave Barron said the San
Onofre plant had not yet received the order, but that the utility
would comply.
</TEXT>
