<HEAD>Man Linked to Terrorist Group Offers to Admit Bomb Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with judge finding Kikumura
guilty, picking up 6th graf pvs, `Last month ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today found a Japanese man
linked to a terrorist group guilty of transporting bombs on the New
Jersey Turnpike after the man agreed to the government's description
of the incident.
   In a surprise announcement Monday, defense attorneys William
Kunstler and Ronald Kuby said they would accept the government's
claims about Yu Kikumura, who has been linked to the Japanese Red
Army, on the condition that Kikumura can maintain his right to
appeal pre-trial rulings in the case.
   Federal prosecutors said today in court they would accept the
condition.
   Although Kikumura admitted to the government's account of his
actions, if the pre-trial rulings, which bear on the admissibility
of evidence against him, are overturned, his conviction could be
thrown out.
   U.S. District Judge Alfred J. Lechner Jr. asked Kikumura a series
of questions to make sure he understood what he was doing in a
procedure similar to that used in guilty pleas. In essence, Kikumura
agreed to the charges and waived his right to a jury trial.
   ``There is no contest and there is no alternative,'' Lechner
said. ``I find the defendant Yu Kikumura guilty of each count of the
indictment.''
   Outside the courthouse, U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr. said
Kikumura had come to this country ``to kill people.''
   ``This man is an international terrorist who sneakd into the
United States using a skillfully forged passpport,'' Alito said.
   If he had not been stopped, ``there would have been some people
killed and maimed,'' he said.
   Kunstler later told reporters that the government had wanted to
create a ``show trial,'' and that the case was indefensible. But
because evidence was illegally seized, he predicted, the conviction
would be overturned.
   ``If you take away the constitutional rights of Yu Kikumura, you
can take away the rights of anybody,'' said Ronald Kuby, another
defense attorney.
   The defense proposed its deal Monday before jury selection began
and moments after it lost an argument to have the indictment
dismissed.
   Last month, Lechner denied a motion to disqualify evidence _
namely, the three homemade bombs made of fire extinguisher
canisters, explosives paraphernalia and numerous personal items
found in Kikumura's car when he was arrested at a rest stop April 12
in Ridgefield, less than five miles east of New York City.
   On Monday, Kuby and Kunstler asked Lechner to dismiss the
indictment after prosecutors disclosed that Kikumura's phone calls
with defense attorneys were recorded at the Metropolitan
Correctional Center in New York City.
   All inmates' calls at the institution are recorded as a matter of
course, although attorney-client calls are not supposed to be
listened to. Previously, prosecutors had said the lawyer calls were
not recorded.
   Lechner found that the defense had not shown that any evidence
was tainted or that the government benefited from the taping.
   Kunstler said his client would ``stipulate'' to the charges in
the indictment _ an acknowledgement but not a formal guilty plea _
as long as Kikumura could be allowed to appeal Lechner's ruling that
the evidence was legally seized and other issues.
   ``We want to save the court's time, we want to save the
taxpayers' money,'' Kunstler said, adding that if the government
insisted on bringing the case before a jury, it would ``cause
essentially a show trial where we will be mute.''
   U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr. angrily objected to Kunstler's
raising plea negotiations in public, calling it ``unprecedented.''
   Lechner told both sides to discuss the matter, and report back
today. He also told the 130 potential jurors to return today.
   Federal authorities have said Kikumura, 36, may be linked to the
Japanese Red Army, a terrorist organization. Court documents showed
he had traveled about 7,000 miles throughout the Northeast after
arriving in the United States fie weeks before his arrest.
   In testimony Monday, FBI agents said more than 25 agents in
cities nationwide were involved in the investigation. People from
four countries were on the government's witness list, said defense
co-counsel Ronald Kuby.
   Kuby said there were three main issues to present to an appellate
court: contentions that the stop and search of Kikumura's car was
illegal and hence the evidence inadmissible; that the charges are
repetitive because they carry 90 years in prison terms; and that the
government may have had access to privileged attorney-client
conversations through the corrections center phone recordings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
