<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BabyFound     11-29 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Found,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Thought Wife Had Just Given Birth, Unaware She Stole Baby,
Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The husband of a woman accused of
snatching an infant from a hospital nursery thought his wife had
just given birth and was unaware that she had faked her pregnancy,
police and prosecutors say.
   Sharon Newkirk, 36, was arraigned Monday on kidnapping charges in
the abduction of 2{-month-old Debra Lynn Moore, who was taken from a
crib at C.S. Mott Children's Hospital on Friday. Bond was set at
$300,000 and a hearing was set for Dec. 7.
   But authorities dropped charges against her husband, Robert.
   ``We're fairly well convinced he did not know his wife planned to
kidnap the baby,'' said Police Lt. John Atkinson. He said Newkirk
was released after he passed a polygraph test Monday.
   ``(Sharon Newkirk) was telling him she was pregnant all along,
that she has small babies and that she has them quick,'' Atkinson
said. ``She really built this up in his mind.''
   Mrs. Newkirk allegedly made medical appointments at the
University of Michigan Medical Center and told her husband she was
visiting an obstetrician, Atkinson said.
   Newkirk said he would stand by his wife.
   ``I don't think she knew what she was doing,'' he said. ``I
thought it was my child.''
   The Newkirks, of Howell, were arrested Saturday when they pulled
into the driveway of their home in Howell. Police said they found
the baby in their car.
   Witnesses said the Newkirks showed off the child at Cleary's Pub
in Howell about an hour after the 4{-pound child was reported
missing.
   Debra Lynn was receiving medication at the hospital for breathing
problems when she was taken. The premature infant also was hooked up
to electronic monitoring equipment and required feeding every three
hours to prevent dehydration. Her twin brother was left undisturbed
in his nearby crib.
   The baby's 17-year-old mother, Kimberly Sue Moore of Monroe,
wasn't at the hospital when her child was taken.
   The infant was returned to C.S. Mott on Saturday, and was listed
in good condition Monday.
</TEXT>
