<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Staggs     11-29 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Staggs,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lousiana Pardon Board Withdraws Leniency Recommendation For
Ex-Fugitive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Louisiana Pardon Board today withdrew
its recommendation of leniency for a man who killed a man nearly 20
years ago and later escaped from prison to build a new life in
Tennessee.
   The withdrawal came three weeks after Henry Staggs was arrested
in Tennessee on sexual abuse charges based on allegations made by a
stepdaughter and a niece.
   During 17 years as a fugitive from Louisiana, Staggs raised a
family and operated an auto repair shop in Columbia, Tenn.
   The FBI finally tracked him down last February, and he was
returned to Louisiana.
   After a pardon board hearing in which Staggs' attorney presented
petitions signed by 2,000 Tennessee residents asking for leniency,
the five members recommended a six-month sentence.
   Gov. Buddy Roemer refused to accept the recommendation, asking
the board to reconsider.
   Before the pardon board could reconsider, Staggs was arrested in
Tennessee.
   ``Based on the current situation in Tennessee, the indictments
being of such serious nature, the board recommended that any form of
leniency be withdrawn,'' Annette Viator, attorney for the Louisiana
Corrections Department, said today.
   ``If he's found innocent, then he could apply here again for
leniency. By law, he can do that within a year of being denied,''
she said.
   Shortly after Staggs' arrest in Tennessee on the sexual abuse
charges, the niece recanted her testimony, saying Staggs had only
touched her breast and that may have been accidental.
   A grand jury received the case on Nov. 16 and is to decide
whether to indict Staggs on three counts of aggravated sexual
battery and one count of aggravated rape.
   At a Nov. 16 hearing, Staggs' 10-year-old stepdaughter testified
about several alleged sexual encounters with Staggs.
   Prosecutors also presented a tape-recording of a 90-minute
meeting Sept. 30 between Staggs and his sister, Betty Fraser, who
was equipped with a hidden microphone by the Tennessee Bureau of
Investigation. Staggs allegedly told Mrs. Fraser that some of the
allegations his stepdaughter made were accurate.
   ``She did it on her own free will,'' Staggs said on tape. ``Tell
her that whatever happened in the past, I'm sorry for. Tell her I
don't blame her. I don't hold it against her. I need psychiatric
help.''
   Staggs was being held in the Maury County, Tenn., Jail in lieu of
$250,000 bond.
</TEXT>
