<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0429 11-29 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0429,410</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: Top 6 grafs new with judge refusing to bar prosecutors; picks
up 5th graf, Gesell has</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in Oliver L. North's Iran-Contra case
today refused to bar prosecutors from closed hearings set to begin
this week on deleting sensitive government secrets from documents to
be used as evidence.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell refused to give lawyers for
the former National Security Council aide permission to file a
motion to bar independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh from the
hearing, which is set to begin Wednesday.
   Gesell said in a brief order that barring prosecutors ``would
alter the purpose of the hearing and would result in further and
wholly unnecessary delay.''
   Defense lawyers gave no reason for their request, filed Monday.
If they had been granted permission to file the motion, they would
likely have argued that prosecutors would get an unfair preview of
their strategy if allowed to attend the hearing.
   North is charged with conspiring to divert millions of dollars in
profits from the Reagan administration's secret weapons deals with
Iran to the Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras.
   The hearings were scheduled by Gesell to consider defense
objections to the deletion of sensitive material from classified
documents that Walsh wants to use as evidence against North.
   Gesell has directed North to come to the hearing prepared to say
why the material is relevant to his defense and should not be
deleted.
   The references Walsh wants to delete include names of foreign
countries and officials as well as U.S. intelligence agents
operating abroad. The government has consented to Walsh's use of the
350 documents as exhibits in a public trial provided the sensitive
references are deleted.
   Also on Monday, North replied to Walsh's request that Gesell bar
the defense from using any of 40,000 pages of classified documents
it has proposed as trial exhibits.
   Walsh contends that North listed many of the documents in his
Nov. 14 notice simply to provoke dismissal of the charges against
him, by threatening to disclose some of the nation's best-kept
secrets.
   North's lawyers countered that Walsh is making a ``frontal
assault on defendant North's fundamental Fifth and Sixth Amendment
right to present a defense.''
   No date has been set for North's trial, the first of four ordered
by Gesell for the former presidential aide and his three
co-defendants: former national security adviser John M. Poindexter
and arms dealers Albert Hakim and retired Air Force Maj. Gen.
Richard V. Secord.
</TEXT>
