<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Activist Banned From Traveling to Receive Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white woman recently released
from detention has been denied permission to travel to New York to
receive a human rights award for her anti-apartheid work, her lawyer
said Tuesday.
   Janet Cherry, who was detained for seven weeks without charges,
was released from prison Nov. 16. She was banned from leaving her
hometown of Port Elizabeth.
   Ms. Cherry, 27, had been detained without charge twice before.
   Her lawyer, Howard Varni, said police refused Ms. Cherry's
request to travel to New York next week as a winner of the first
annual Reebok Human Rights Award ceremony at the United Nations.
   Ms. Cherry is a researcher for the Institute for Democratic
Alternatives for South Africa.
