<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Paris-Strike     11-29 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paris-Strike,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Gets Tough, Calling in Army to Ease Transport Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers in army trucks rolled into the Paris region
Tuesday to help transport hundreds of thousands of suburban
commuters stranded by a transit strike the government called ``union
guerrilla warfare.''
   The strike called by the communist-led General Confederation of
Labor paralyzed two of four lines on the regional express network
and was spreading to city subway and bus services.
   On Monday night, the French government ordered more than 350
military trucks and 1,000 soldiers to supplement private companies
called in to move passengers.
   The military contingent, from Dijon and other areas, was expected
to be in operation for morning rush hour Wednesday, with 250 trucks
at the suburban terminals of the affected lines, according to
Prefect Olivier Philip, governor of the Ile de France region.
   It was expected to take up to 48 hours for all 365 military
vehicles to be operational.
   ``Deterioration of public services forces the government to
assume its responsibilities,'' President Francois Mitterrand said.
``That is what the government has done, and done well, notably in
calling in the army.''
   The transit strike is one of a string of work stoppages plaguing
France for more than a month. Public sector employees ranging from
postal workers to nurses, ambulance drivers and even funeral parlor
employees have been striking sporadically for increased wages and
other benefits.
   Socialist Premier Michel Rocard, in power for six months, has
remained firm in the face of demands, continuing the tight spending
policies in force since 1983.
   Transport Minister Michel Delebarre ordered strikers' wages
suspended and punishment of those engaged in what he said were
illegal acts.
   He said some strikers blocked buses in their terminals, flattened
tires and sabotaged engines.
   This amounted to ``a sort of union guerrilla warfare of
harassment'' in which ``hundreds of thousands of users were being
taken hostage,'' the minister said.
   Blocked terminals, maintenance depots and lack of material were
forcing a reduction in city bus and Metro service, with buses
running at about 60 percent capacity at rush hour Tuesday and one
Metro line shut down.
   The transit authority decided over the weekend to close down the
two suburban train lines starting Monday, saying safety could no
longer be assured because of the strikers, whose strength is
concentrated in the train maintenance forces.
   Henri Krasucki, secretary-general of the labor federation,
denounced what he called government tactics of ``repression,
sanctions and intimidation'' which he said will only ``increase the
fighting spirit'' of the strikers.
   Workers, with an average monthly salary of about $1,100, are
demanding a $170 monthly increase plus improved safety measures. The
transit authority most recently proposed increases of about $25 plus
bonuses ranging from about $17 to $100.
   Opposition politicians have criticized Rocard, saying he has
failed to define a policy to deal with public sector grievances.
Mitterrand, re-elected to a seven-year term in May, had made social
peace a main campaign pledge.
   The strike action fanned by the labor federation is widely
regarded as a Communist Party effort to undermine the government and
strengthen its own hand for municipal elections in March. Party
officials deny they are using social discontent for political
benefit, and Krasucki said the idea was ``completely stupid.''
   Job grievances have affected many sectors this fall.
   Striking postal workers left Paris without mail service for three
weeks earlier this month, and mail strikes continue in Lyon, Amiens
and Clermont-Ferrand.
   Marseille has been hit with strikes by train and bus drivers and
social security workers, who are refusing to work in several
provincial cities.
   Other job actions are being carried out at nuclear plants, in
Paris pharmacies and at the Louvre Museum, where guards protesting a
change in work hours have been off the job for more than a week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
