<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Carlucci     11-29 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Carlucci,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Chief Making Final Visit to Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci next
week will visit four Arab states that have provided limited support
for American forces in the Persian Gulf, U.S. officials say.
   A stop aboard U.S. warships in the gulf also is on the itinerary
for what was expected to be Carlucci's last tour before the Reagan
administration leaves office in January, said the officials, who
asked not to be identified.
   The Defense Department said Carlucci would discuss a variety of
regional issues with officials in Oman, Bahrain, Saudi Arabia and
Kuwait. These presumably would include the scaling back of U.S.
forces following the Iraq-Iran cease-fire.
   Carlucci is including the gulf on a 10-day trip that begins with
defense meetings in Paris and at NATO headquarters in Brussels.
   Gulf-based sources, insisting on anonymity, said Carlucci's visit
was primarily in response to an invitation from Oman's defense
minister, Mutassim Bin Hamoud Busaidi. The other stops were added
for diplomatic reasons, they said.
   All four Arab states, though nominally neutral in the Iraq-Iran
war, have made facilities of one kind or another available to U.S.
forces since mid-1987, when the escalating conflict prompted a major
buildup of American and other foreign naval units in the gulf.
   Despite the Aug. 20 cease-fire, in effect ending eight years of
Iraq-Iran hostilities, 11 Kuwait-owned oil tankers reflagged by the
United States last year for protection still sail under the Stars
and Stripes.
   The sources said Carlucci's acceptance of the Omani invitation
reflected U.S. interest in nurturing a relationship that gained
strength during the war, yet remains more secretive than U.S. ties
with any other gulf Arab state.
   The Omanis permit U.S. warships to refuel at a naval depot on the
Arabian Sea. They have served three times in the past 15 months as
diplomatic go-betweens for the repatriation of Iranians captured or
rescued at sea by U.S. forces.
   The Omanis, who share control of the Strait of Hormuz, the
strategic gateway to the gulf, with Iran, have longstanding military
ties with Britain. However, they also are the only gulf state to
participate in annual ``Bright Star'' military maneuvers with the
United States, Egypt, Somalia and Sudan.
   Pentagon officials say the United States will reduce its fleet if
the Iraq-Iran truce continues to hold, but have given no timetable.
   Already trimmed by two ships from 27 to 25, it remains the
largest of six foreign navies in the region.
   The gulf-based squadron of 15 returned to full strength Sunday
when the amphibious assault ship USS Raleigh arrived after a month's
delay for repairs. It carries a 400-man U.S. Marine combat force.
   European navies are withdrawing more rapidly, with Belgium's last
minesweeper recently departed, the Netherlands' last leaving Dec. 2
and Italy's five warships heading home before Dec. 31.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
