<1ST_LINE>r p AM-QuayleSuccessor     11-29 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle Successor,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orr Not Expected To Select Quayle Successor For Two Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Robert D. Orr is expected to wait at
least two weeks before selecting someone to take over Vice
President-elect Dan Quayle's Senate seat, according to the
governor's press secretary.
   ``He does not want to wait until the last minute, but he
understands he has the entire month (of December),'' Dollyne
Pettingill said after meeting with Orr Monday.
   Earlier this month, Orr had said his appointee could benefit from
attending Senate Republican caucus elections this week, fueling
speculation that the replacement would be named quickly.
   But Ms. Pettingill said the governor has not narrowed a list of
candidates.
   ``I think that once that takes place, he will have a better idea
on the timing of the announcement. But do not look for it any time
soon,'' she said.
   Orr, a Republican, must name a replacement for Quayle before Orr
leaves office on Jan. 9 or he will lose the right to Gov.-elect Evan
Bayh, a Democrat.
   The appointee also can gain a few days of seniority over newly
elected senators if Orr makes his selection before the new Senate is
sworn in Jan. 3.
   Quayle will be sworn in as vice president Jan. 20.
