<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Bush,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis To Meet With Bush on Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis will travel to Washington
on Friday to meet with President-elect George Bush for their first
face-to-face encounter since the election that Dukakis lost to Bush,
the governor's aides said today.
   Dukakis, the defeated Democratic presidential candidate, will
meet with Bush at the vice president's residence for a session
beginning at 2 p.m., according to a statement from Dukakis's press
office.
   Dukakis spokesman Steve Crawford said the length of the meeting
is ``open-ended'' and there was no specific agenda yet.
   Bush extended the invitation to get together with the governor
two weeks ago. Dukakis immediately accepted, and their staffs have
been working since then on a time and place.
   ``He asked to meet with me (and) I am pleased to do that,''
Dukakis said last week.
   The governor suggested then that he was concerned about reports
that the Bush administration may try to balance the budget by
cutting Medicare, Medicaid and other social programs.
   But when asked if he intended to give Bush some advice, Dukakis
said: ``Well, I offered a good deal of advice during the campaign.
He is aware of that.''
