<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bomb-Animals     11-29 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bomb-Animals,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Animal Rights Activist Pleads Innocent in Bomb Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An animal rights activist accused of
planting a bomb at a surgical instruments company that experiments
on live dogs pleaded innocent today to charges of attempted murder,
possession of explosives and manufacturing a bomb.
   Fran Stephanie Trutt, 33, of New York City didn't speak during
her brief appearance in Stamford Superior Court except to say
``definitely not guilty.''
   Superior Court Judge Martin Nigro denied a motion by her public
defender to lower bail from $500,000 to $60,000, and she remains in
custody.
   Animals rights groups have disavowed any connection to Trutt, who
was arrested on Nov. 11 near U.S. Surgical Corp.'s Norwalk
headquarters.
   She was accused of hiding a powerful, radio-controlled pipe bomb
packed with roofing nails in bushes near the vacant parking space of
company Chairman Leon Hirsch.
   Three more bombs were discovered in her New York apartment after
her arrest.
   In a prison interview, Trutt said she didn't intend to kill
anyone with the bomb, but that she wanted to scare the company into
ending its practice of using live dogs to demonstrate its surgical
staples.
   Defense lawyer Monte Radler said today that Trutt planned to meet
with a private attorney and asked for a continuance. Nigro scheduled
a pre-trial hearing for Dec. 13.
   In asking that Trutt's bail be reduced, Radler noted that she has
no criminal record and that it should be obvious from her statements
that she plans to return to court to defend herself.
   Assistant State's Attorney Bruce Hudock said a $500,000 bond is
necessary because the state believes that Trutt is a danger to the
community.
</TEXT>
