<1ST_LINE>u w PM-SenateLeader 8thLd-Writethru a0604 11-29 0786</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Senate Leader, 8th Ld-Writethru, a0604,730</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs on style of Byrd, Mitchell after 14th graf
pvs, Mitchell, 55 ; deletes last 3 grafs pvs to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats today elected George Mitchell
as their majority leader and Mitchell said he was ready to ``move
forward'' with George Bush's White House on the federal deficit and
other major issues.
   The senator from Maine was elected in a closed meeting by a
unanimous voice vote after first narrowly missing a majority in his
race against Sens. Daniel Inouye of Hawaii and Bennett Johnston of
Louisiana.
   The federal deficit, health care, day care and the environment
were top priorities, said Mitchell, who planned to meet Wednesday
with Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas, re-elected by Republicans as their
leader earlier in the day.
   Asked if he would cooperate with Bush, Mitchell said, ``We hope
to move forward on a broad range of issues.''
   ``The Democrats await with interest and enthusiasm the proposals
of the next administration,'' he said.
   Mitchell, appointed to the Senate in 1980, elected in 1982 and
re-elected earlier this month, will succeed Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va.,
who decided to step down as majority leader to become chairman of
the Senate Appropriations Committee.
   Byrd, who was also elected as the Senate's President Pro Tempore,
announced the vote to reporters. He handed his gavel to Mitchell
before television cameras, then stepped back as his successor moved
to the microphones to take questions.
   Byrd will become chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee.
   Mitchell garnered 27 votes on the first ballot, one short of a
majority among the 55 Democrats in the new Senate. Inouye and
Johnston each received 14.
   Johnston then moved that Mitchell be approved unanimously; Inouye
seconded the motion. After the vote, Johnston said:
   ``The best man won. George Mitchell will be a great majority
leader.''
   Sen. Alan Cranston of California was re-elected as the party's
whip, defeating Sen. Wendell Ford of Kentucky. There was no recorded
vote.
   Although the least senior of the three candidates, Mitchell is
considered a strong spokesman for the party. A New England liberal,
the former federal prosecutor and judge has a reputation as a
skilled, thoughtful legislator.
   Mitchell, 55, is a liberal like Inouye but less tradition-bound.
He appealed to Democrats seeking someone who would appear less
ideological but still could act as a strong public speaker for the
party.
   Mitchell will bring to the post of majority leader a far
different style than Byrd, who was Democratic leader for a decade.
   Byrd's tenure was marked by his mastery and manipulation of the
Senate rules and his distinctive personality. Although very
secretive about his legislative dealings, Byrd would display before
the Senate his memory of poetry and history, both of which he would
recite at length in the chamber.
   Mitchell is less of a Senate institution and far more open
personally than Byrd. Although more liberal, Democratic colleagues
describe him as a consensus builder and not an ideologue.
   And, while relations between Byrd and Dole often seemed strained,
there is potential for a strong working relationship between
Mitchell and Dole. The two men have served together since 1981 on
the Senate Finance Committee and always speak well of each other.
   Inouye, 64, pitched himself as the most experienced of the three.
His liberal voting record is in line with traditional Democrats.
Johnston, 56, and the most conservative of the three, cited his
Southern roots and parliamentary skill.
   The three candidates, besides representing different regions,
offered different perspectives for the Democrats.
   Aside from those broad themes, the candidates appealed to their
colleagues on very personal issues such as demands for choice
committee assignments and changes in the Senate rules and schedule.
   Dole, the Kansas senator who recently has been meeting with Bush
to settle their differences, was re-elected in a voice vote that
re-installed three Republican officers who faced no opposition, said
Walt Riker, Dole's spokesman.
   Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., was re-elected minority whip; Bill
Armstrong, R-Colo., was returned as chairman of the Republican
Policy Committee, and Thad Cochran, R-Miss., was kept on as GOP
secretary, Riker said.
   The GOP conference chairman, Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., defeated
challenger Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, by 28-17 to retain his post,
Riker said. Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., defeated Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., on a vote of 28-17 to head the National Republican
Senatorial Committee.
   While the camps of all three contenders for the majority leader's
position voiced optimism before the vote, senators said Monday that
the outcome was uncertain. Each of the contestants was continually
polling the 55-member Democratic majority, but the answers received
might be more positive than the results in today's secret ballot.
</TEXT>
