<HEAD>Shultz Defends Decision on Arafat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz said today
the strong opposition to his decision to bar a visit by PLO Chairman
Yasser Arafat to the United States shows that people are forgetting
what a threat international terrorism is.
   Under questioning at a groundbreaking ceremony for a State
Department annex, Shultz said he was sorry about the breadth of the
opposition to his decision but that he will stick by it.
   In addition to Arab countries, Great Britain, West Germany and
Italy, among other allies, all have criticized Shultz's decision.
   ``To some extent the opposition suggests how important it was to
decide what was decided and to make it so clear what the basis
was,'' Shultz said.
   ``The basis (was) our concern about terrorism and I am afraid
that it's too easy for people to forget what an important problem
that is and what a threat it is to civilized society.''
