<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     11-29 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0662</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Bright & Brief</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the New Age Telephone Book, you can reach
waaaaaaaay out and touch someone.
   The directory lists psychics, healers, numerologists, gurus,
channelers, ghost hunters and almost anyone else who may appeal to
followers of New Age philosophies.
   A real estate agent, for instance, offers clients ``your own
place in the universe.'' A ``gentle dentist'' promises free wine and
stereo headphones. A medical clinic tells AIDS patients that their
best years are yet to come.
   ``We want to be the book that you pick up first if you have this
particular consciousness,'' said managing editor Caryn Goldberg.
``After all, the Pacific Bell Yellow Pages doesn't exactly have a
category for rebirthers.''
   Jeanne Cordova, the directory's publisher, and Goldberg, who also
publish gay and lesbian directories, printed 50,000 copies for
shipment mainly to stores catering to New Age clientele, where it is
distributed free.
   Ms. Cordova said that at first the New Age Telephone Book was
difficult to sell to advertisers. Even those in the New Age business
felt that customers would be naturally drawn to them.
   The New Age Telephone Book, put together earlier this year,
enters its next life soon with a second edition.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Its official name is the Ronald Reagan Center for
High Energy Physics, but a newspaper contest has yielded a
friendlier, Texas-style moniker for the ``super collider'' _ Super
Clyde.
   ``It's easy to say, and still, to the ear, it sounds like Super
C'lider,'' said Jewel P. Clark, 72, of Garland, whose winning entry
was among more than 1,000 suggestions received by The Dallas Morning
News.
   Ms. Clark's prizes include a year's supply of Atomic Fireballs
candy, a junior scientist microscope and two passes to a science
museum.
   The $4.4 billion underground atom smasher _ the world's biggest
and most powerful _ will be built in Waxahachie, south of here. The
53-mile tunnel will take eight years to build.
   An entrant who got special notice was David Thomas of Waxahachie,
who suggested the super collider be named ``The Cellar'' so ``it can
be advertised as the home of the Texas Rangers and Dallas Cowboys.''
   ``Will the employees be known as `The Atom's Family'?'' Thomas
further mused.
   Receiving honorable mention were the names Armadillotron, The Big
Bang Thang, Big Texelerator, Proton-B-Que and Waxasmashie.
   Roger Burke of Irving submitted an entry that captured the
immensity of the project: Supercolliderfragilisticexpialidocious.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Las Vegas likes its privacy and Los Angeles
would rather you write than call if a survey of unlisted phone
numbers is any indication.
   Las Vegas ranked No. 1 in the nation with 60 percent of its phone
numbers unlisted, while about 56 percent of people with numbers in
Los Angeles County do not list them in phone directories, according
to Survey Sampling Inc., a Connecticut company that sells phone
numbers to market research companies.
   In Los Angeles, the 56 percent figure was a 4 percent increase
from two years ago.
   ``The rate of unlistedness is definitely jumping, especially in
the top unlisted markets,'' said John Lamb of Survey Sampling.
``Younger people, ages 18 to 30, are tending not to list their phone
numbers. Our suspicion is that they feel it keeps telemarketers from
getting to them.''
   Not listing a number won't deter all phone solicitors, however.
Lamb noted many companies use computers that call every number in
sequence, listed or not.
   California is the leader when it comes to residents who don't
want their phone numbers listed. Ten of the top 20 unlisted cities
in the nation are in the Golden State, with Oakland, Fresno, San
Jose and Sacramento all in the top 10.
   Other communities with a high share of unlisted phone numbers are
Jersey City, N.J.; Newark, N.J.; Bergen-Passaic, N.J.; El Paso,
Texas; Houston, and Chicago.
</TEXT>
