<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Accident, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0602,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Casino-Bound Bus Flips On Side, At Least 46 Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0624 to fix overline to 46 injured; new
throughout to UPDATE with 46 injured at four hospitals, include that
rescue squads from five towns and soldiers from nearby fort
assisted.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EATONTOWN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus carrying senior citizens on a junket
to Atlantic City's casinos today flipped onto its side as it headed
south on the Garden State Parkway, and at least 46 people were
injured, authorities said.
   The bus was carrying about 49 passengers _ senior citizens from
Brooklyn, N.Y. _ when it overturned about 11:30 a.m., said parkway
communications officer Mike Cannon. The injured were taken to four
hospitals.
   Fourteen people were treated at Monmouth Medical Center in Long
Branch for what spokeswoman Jane Hollander described as mostly
slight injuries, including cuts, bruises and chest pains.
   Eleven people were taken to Riverview Medical Center in Red Bank,
some with head and back injuries, cuts and bruises, said spokeswoman
Sandra Nardone. None of the injuries appeared life-threatening, she
said.
   Ten people were taken to Jersey Shore Medical Center in Neptune,
mostly with cuts, bruises and back injuries, said spokeswoman Marie
Koppa.
   Eleven people were taken to Bayshore Community Hospital in
Holmdel, some with dizzy spells and back and shoulder injuries, said
spokeswoman Lisa O'Donnell.
   Authorities identified the bus as belonging to Leisure Lines of
Mahwah. The company referred all calls to police.
   The bus came to rest on the passenger-door side, partially
blocking the left lane of the highway. As rescue squads from at
least five towns and soldiers from Fort Monmouth reached the scene,
passengers sat dazed on the grassy shoulder, some covered with
blankets.
   The accident closed the express lanes of the heavily traveled
parkway, which traverses the state from north to south.
</TEXT>
