<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BroadcastBluff     11-29 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Broadcast Bluff,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DJ Fired After He Offers Keys To Porsche; Listener Wants Car</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Theobald thought the radio contest was too
easy: Answer a question about the first day of autumn and win ``keys
to a brand-new Porsche.''
   Two months later, Mike McDonald, the WLS-AM disc jockey who made
the offer, has been fired, and Theobald is still waiting for a
Porsche. He hasn't even gotten the keys, he says.
   ``I got through and I gave him the right answer,'' Theobald, a
21-year-old biology student at William and Mary College in Virginia,
said Monday.
   After receiving a letter from Theobald's lawyer, who also is his
brother, station managers fired McDonald. But they still say the
whole thing was obviously a joke and they have no intention of
giving away a Porsche.
   McDonald offered the keys to the first caller who could explain
``what was special'' about the day, Sept. 22. Theobald, listening to
the Chicago station from his home in Williamsburg, Va., was the
first person to call and say it was the first day of autumn.
   ``You win the keys to the car,'' McDonald said, according to a
transcript read by WLS operations manager Richard Lippincott. When
Theobald asked if it was a joke, McDonald said it wasn't, adding:
``I have absolutely no idea where the car is, but you get the keys.''
   About a month later, Theobald mentioned the incident to his
brother Ed, a Chicago attorney.
   Ed Theobald said radio contests are regulated by the Federal
Communications Commission, which requires that stations deliver what
they promise. ``It was definitely my brother's understanding that he
would win the car,'' he said Monday.
   When WLS received a letter from Tom Theobald on Nov. 14 inquiring
about the car, McDonald was suspended. He was fired three days
later, Lippincott said.
   McDonald's telephone number could not be obtained through
directory information, and the station would not provide it.
   The station doesn't plan to give away a car.
   ``I don't think we owe the guy a Porsche,'' Lippincott said.
``It's obvious from the transcript that he understood he won the
keys and not the car.''
   Meanwhile, Tom Theobald will drive his Datsun, with 140,000 miles
on it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
