<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RideCollapse     11-29 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ride Collapse,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Test Results On Midway Ride May Never Be Known, Consultant Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials say the fatal collapse of
a ride at the Broward County Fair may lead to new safety
regulations, but they may not get much help from a consultant
studying the wreckage.
   One of six arms on the ``Monster'' ride broke at a paint-covered
crack on Nov. 23, dropping four baskets carrying passengers 10 feet
to the ground. A 17-year-old girl died and six other people were
injured.
   State Agriculture Commissioner Doyle Conner, who oversees the
state's six-person Bureau of Fairs and Expositions, is studying the
accident with an eye toward improving state inspections of carnival
rides.
   Conner's senior executive assistant, Larry Shackelford, said
Conner will make recommendations to the Legislature during its
January committee meetings covering staffing, training and
inspection procedure.
   Meanwhile, a consultant studying the broken ride said he doesn't
plan to make his findings public.
   Jeffrey Tennant, dean of graduate studies and research at Florida
Atlantic University here, said Monday he is not working for the
state but for a company that insures the operator of the Broward
County Fair midway.
   His findings ``may only become available in a legal proceeding,''
Tennant said.
   After the accident, Wally Rich, director of the state's Bureau of
Fairs and Expositions, said he was counting on answers from
Tennant's metallurgical and X-ray tests.
   ``We're hoping he can tell us the speed of the ride and what
caused the fracture to become a complete break,'' Rich said last
week. ``We also want to determine how long the fracture has been
there and if there are fractures of the other (five) arms.''
   But Tennant said if any legal problems over the teen-ager's death
are settled out of court, it is possible the metal test results may
never be known.
</TEXT>
