<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Superstar singer Michael Jackson, who
recently bowed out of a series of concerts in Los Angeles, also
cannot reschedule three sold-out concerts at the Tacoma Dome,
officials said.
   Stadium director Jay Green said this week he was ``very, very
disappointed,'' although he knew rescheduling ``would be an uphill
battle.''
   More than 70,000 tickets at $23.50 each had been sold for the
performances Oct. 31 and Nov. 1 and 2 which were canceled after
Jackson's agent said he was ill.
   More recently, Los Angeles Sports Arena officials said they were
told Jackson had ``swollen vocal chords'' when he canceled his shows
there.
   But there still may be hope for Jackson's fans in Washington
state, Green said.
   A statement issued by an agency representing Jackson said the
singer ``sincerely hopes to perform in Tacoma in the near future.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elena Akhmilovskaya, a leading
Soviet chess player who secretly married the U.S. team captain and
defected during the Chess Olympiad, received permission Tuesday to
enter the United States, a U.S. consular official said.
   Akhmilovskaya, the second-ranked player on the Soviet team,
married John Donaldson, the U.S. team's non-playing captain, in
Greece on Friday during the chess tournament.
   The couple arrived in Frankfurt on Saturday to wait for an
immigrant visa for the Soviet chess expert.
   ``She received entry documents today and is cleared to enter the
United States,'' said U.S. Consulate spokesman Craig Springer.
   Donaldson, a 31-year-old international master from Seattle, met
Akhmilovskaya during a chess tournament in Cuba in 1985.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former world heavyweight boxing champion
Muhammad Ali on Tuesday promised to use his influence to encourage
more Americans to visit the East African nation, the New Vision
newspaper reported.
   ``I am going back with great memories of the people of Uganda and
I'm going to tell Americans that Ugandans have beautiful houses,
nice cars, and beautiful scenery, and persuade them also to come
over,'' Ali said at the end of a four-day visit.
   The government-owned newspaper said Ali spoke Monday at the
headquarters of the Uganda Moslem Supreme Council. Ali was in Uganda
to tour schools and clinics financed by the Khartoum, Sudan-based
Munazamat Dawa Al-Islamia, a Moslem humanitarian organization.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HASTINGS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Race car driver Gordon Johncock has been
cited for poaching a deer on his land, a state Department of Natural
Resources officer said.
   Johncock, cited for possession of an untagged deer and for
hunting with a .27-caliber rifle in a shotgun-only zone, has until
Wednesday to answer the charges or face arrest, said Lt. Rick
Schmeler of the state office.
   During the Nov. 20 incident in south-central Michigan, Johncock
also received warnings for failing to wear hunter's orange on his
clothing, for operating an all-terrain vehicle on a roadway and for
possessing a loaded rifle in the vehicle.
   Johncock, 52, is a two-time winner of the Indianapolis 500.
