<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BishopRetires     11-29 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishop Retires,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>St. Petersburg Bishop Announces Retirement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bishop W. Thomas Larkin, head of the
300,000-member Roman Catholic diocese of St. Petersburg since 1979,
announced Tuesday he is retiring for health reasons.
   Larkin, 65, said his retirement had been accepted by Pope John
Paul II. Bishops must offer their resignation at age 75.
   ``When I began my tenure as bishop I fully intended to remain
until the mandatory retirement age,'' said Larkin. ``However,
although man proposes, God disposes. During the past year my health
has not been the best and I was advised to slow down.''
   He did not disclose the nature of his medical condition.
   For nine years, the Mount Morris, N.Y., native has been head of
the growing five-county Gulf Coast diocese, which has 71 parishes
and missions, more than 200 priests, nearly 400 religious sisters
and brothers, 30 schools and 12,000 students.
   Larkin, who was ordained in Syracuse, N.Y., in 1947, was named
bishop in 1979 following the death of Charles B. McLaughlin.
   He will remain bishop until a successor is named by the pope.
</TEXT>
