<2ND_LINE>PM-Bishop Jailed, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0502,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishop Spends Overnight In Jail For Role In Abortion Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with group released. Picks up 7th
graf pvs, `We will...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>POCOPSON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic bishop and six other
anti-abortion activists were released today after serving an
overnight jail sentence for an illegal protest against a women's
clinic.
   Auxiliary Bishop Austin Vaughan of the Archdiocese of New York
and the other activists began their two-day sentences in Chester
County Prison about noon Monday, said warden Thomas G. Frame.
   Officials said they counted the time the seven spent in jail
Monday and today as two days, even though the group was there for
only parts of each day. Frame's office said all were released about
10 a.m. today.
   Officials at the National Conference of Catholic Bishops in
Washington said they know of no other bishop in recent years who has
served a jail term.
   ``No one here can recall a precedent,'' said Carl Eifert, an
information officer for the bishops' conference.
   The four men and three women were among 591 people arrested July
5 at the Women's Suburban Clinic in Paoli, 25 miles northwest of
Philadelphia, after they blocked clinic entrances in defiance of two
court orders. They were the first of more than 400 people scheduled
to go to prison.
   Earlier, Frame would not disclose whether the activists would
receive special treatment, saying their housing would be up to the
prison's classification committee.
   ``We will do what we feel is best for the prison and also for
them,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   The prison, with a capacity of 280 inmates, is holding 494, he
said.
   District Justice Robert Mull found all the defendants guilty of
defiant trespass and fined them $10 plus $50.50 in court costs
during their trials.
   Those who refused to pay on grounds of conscience were sentenced
to two days in prison to be served 10 at a time starting every
Monday, Wednesday and Friday. One man has appealed, said court
secretary Linda Miller.
   Before appearing in court, Vaughan led a Mass at nearby St.
Norbert's Church, according to the Rev. Louis Freiberg, who
estimated about 450 to 500 people, including 15 priests, attended.
   ``They're still killing 1.5 million babies a year. ... They're
the future of our country,'' Vaughan said just before going to jail.
   Of the protesters arrested, about 405 people refused to pay the
fines, said the Pro-Life Coalition of Southeast Pennsylvania in a
statement. Ms. Miller said about 100 fines had been paid.
   Chester County District Attorney James P. MacElree II had said he
was hoping the fines would repay Tredyffrin Township the more than
$12,000 in arrest and booking costs incurred the day of the protest.
   It costs $40 per day to house each inmate, Frame said.
   The protest was organized by Operation Rescue, the Binghamton,
N.Y.-based coalition that orchestrated protests at the Democratic
National Convention in Atlanta and in dozens of other cities around
the nation, resulting in about 9,000 arrests this year.
   Barbara Magera, assistant to the director of Operation Rescue,
said Vaughan was arrested during an abortion protest in New York
City in May, but those charges were dismissed.
   Besides Vaughan, those entering prison Monday were Joyce Starrs
of Parkesburg; Barbara Willsher of Reading; the Rev. Richard Doron,
pastor of the non-denominational Church of the New Covenant in
Marlton, N.J.; Priscilla Gossens of Beechwood, N.J.; the Rev. Peter
Byrne of North Tarrytown, N.Y.; and Allen Billington of Glassboro,
N.J.
</TEXT>
