<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     11-29 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissidents Demand Chun Be Tried For Corruption</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissidents called Tuesday for former
President Chun Doo-hwan to stand trial for corruption and human
rights abuses, and they urged other political groups to support
demands for a special tribunal.
   President Roh Tae-woo was studying plans to purge the government.
He was expected to fire as many as 11 ministers linked to Chun to
try to defuse public anger and present an unsullied administration.
   Dissident leaders accused the government of a cover up, charging
Roh and his colleagues were implicated in past abuses associated
with Chun.
   ``The Struggle Committee for the Arrest of Chun,'' an alliance of
dissident groups, announced a meeting Dec. 5 of political parties
and social groups to seek special legislation to investigate and try
Chun.
   The main opposition parties, which have been calling for
appointment of a special prosecutor to investigate Chun and his
wife, Lee Soon-ja, did not react immediately to the dissidents' call.
   But top opposition leader Kim Dae-jung Monday had repeated his
resistance to jailing Chun because he said he is against political
retribution.
   Chun, a former general who took power with military backing in
1980, went into rural exile at a Buddhist monastery last week after
apologizing to the nation for abuses under his seven-year
authoritarian rule.
   The furor has dominated South Korean politics with opposition
groups demanding a full accounting. The National Assembly has been
conducting public hearings into the Chun government and findings
have further fueled public anger.
   Dissidents have little public support because of their extremism,
but they have organized a series of large, often violent protests in
recent weeks to demand Chun's arrest.
   An alliance statement said Chun must face trial for widespread
corruption; the deaths and jailings of political opponents; and his
role in the bloody suppression of a 1980 uprising in the southern
city of Kwangju in which some 200 people died.
   Chun has denied personal corruption. But some of his relatives
and associates have been convicted of or charged with embezzling
government funds and other crimes involving millions of dollars.
   Roh, another former general and once a close Chun ally, appealed
to the nation Saturday for forgiveness for the former president. But
dissident and opposition groups responded by demanding a full
investigation.
   In a weekend appeal, Roh also promised to release as many
political prisoners as possible and restore to other government
opponents the civil rights of which they were stripped. People
facing trial for political protests would have their cases reviewed,
he said.
   Government officials, who declined to be identified, said at
least 200 prisoners would be freed by early December. Police said 11
students seized for trying to attack Chun's house Oct. 31 were
released Tuesday.
   Roh took power February after Chun stepped down. Roh won
presidential elections in December after the opposition split its
votes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
