<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YonkersDeseg     11-29 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yonkers Deseg,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents Sue Over Judge's Orders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Yonkers residents filed a lawsuit
Tuesday charging that a federal judge's desegregation order deprived
them of the right to live and work in neighborhoods ``free from
low-class people.''
   The suit, filed in the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals by the
Save Yonkers Federation, was the latest skirmish in an eight-year
legal battle that nearly brought the city of 195,000 to financial
ruin for defying the judge.
   The federation comprises 13 citizens' groups opposed to U.S.
District Judge Leonard Sand's order that Yonkers build 1,000 units
of low- and middle-income housing scattered throughout the city to
remedy decades of segregation.
   The suit, which lists several hundred residents and merchants as
petitioners, maintains that the order deprives them of ``the
benefits of living and-or working in neighborhoods free from low
class people (of any race) and the crime and housing rot which
nearly always accompanies their presence.''
   ``To victimize the innocent because of wrongs by others _ by
forcing upon those victims unwanted associations and by otherwise
jeopardizing them, their families and their property _ is surely to
violate a constitutional sense of justice,'' the suit said.
   It said the residnets ``have lost value in their property and
thus suffered economic injury.''
   The group's lawyer, Brooklyn Law School professor Henry Mark
Holzer, said the suit utilizes arguments never presented on behalf
of the city. Those include what he said were a First Amendment right
not to associate with certain people and the Tenth Amendment
establishment of federalism and separation of powers.
   The lawsuit was filed in an appeals court instead of U.S.
District Court because it challenges Sand's authority to impose the
desegregation plan, said Holzer. If the suit succeeds, Sand will
have to refashion a remedy, Holzer said.
   In 1985, five years after the U.S. Justice Department filed suit,
Sand found the city liable for 40 years of intentionally segregating
its schools and housing. A school desegregation plan went into
effect in 1986.
   Sand later ordered the housing desegregation plan. The City
Council defied him in August and was found in contempt, paying out
$819,000 in fines before capitulating to the threat of financial
ruin and agreeing to carry out the plan.
   Appeals of Sand's ruling have failed. The Supreme Court refused
to hear the case.
   Sand had no comment on the suit, according to his chambers.
   Jack O'Toole, president of the Save Yonkers Federation, said the
organization has received donations from all over the country and
would take the case to the U.S. Supreme Court if necessary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
