<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1918EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WarsawPact     11-29 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Warsaw Pact,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moscow Rejects NATO Report As `Propaganda Ploy'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Soviet officer Tuesday rejected
as a ``propaganda ploy'' a NATO report saying the Warsaw Pact
massively outguns the Western alliance in conventional arms.
   ``This paper ... is not useful for the purpose of the future
talks,'' Col.-Gen. Nikolai Chervov told a news conference.
   He referred to planned talks on conventional stability in Europe,
for which a mandate is being negotiated in Vienna between the 16
NATO and seven Warsaw Pact nations.
   NATO's 28-page report was billed by Secretary-General Manfred
Woerner as an attempt to publicize relative East-West troop
strengths and challenge Moscow to issue its data.
   Chervov said Moscow would publish its own figures at an
unspecified date after consulting Warsaw Pact allies.
   Woerner said the NATO report ``Conventional Forces in Europe: The
Facts,'' is not the basis for negotiators from the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization at the new conventional stability talks.
   But Chervov challenged this. The study focuses on the ground and
air forces to be discussed at those talks and ignores naval forces
that are not at issue.
   Diplomats in Vienna say they hope the talks, which will cover the
territory from the Atlantic Ocean to the Ural Mountains, will begin
early next year.
   The NATO report did not discuss the quality of East bloc weapons
and forces, only their numbers.
   It said Warsaw Pact nations have a large superiority in 11 major
arms systems. In eight of those, the Soviet Union alone outguns all
NATO nations and its Warsaw Pact allies combined, the report said.
   As a military man, Chervov said, he failed to understand the NATO
approach because ``the data provided do not make possible a real
assessment of the fighting power of the two alliances.''
   He disputed figures on the East bloc's capability and said the
NATO report erred in omitting the two military blocs' naval forces.
   ``In these areas, the United States and the NATO armed forces
hold a multifaceted superiority, including a 3-1 advantage in major
combat ships, cruisers, cruise missiles and mine sweepers and a
2.5-1 advantage in naval aircraft,'' Chervov said.
   ``The NATO paper is a propaganda ploy which cannot serve as a
basis for future negotiations,'' he said.
   The talks are expected to replace deadlocked Mutual and Balanced
Force Reduction talks on reducing troops in Central Europe.
   Negotiations for a conventional stability mandate have been upset
by a dispute between France and the United States about whether
talks should be limited to the 23 NATO and Warsaw Pact nations, or
extended to include Europe's 12 neutral and non-aligned states.
   Yuri Kashlev, chief Soviet delegate to the Helsinki review
conference, told Tuesday's news conference Moscow is ready to
include all its territory to the Urals in the new talks.
   He also said the Soviets are ready to accept Western suggestions
that certain areas of Turkey be excluded from the talks.
   The issue of how much Turkish territory to include, and a U.S.
military base at Adana in southern Turkey, is one of the last major
stumbling blocks to East-West agreement on a mandate. Both sides
expect the dispute to be resolved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
