<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Vietnam     11-29 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Vietnam,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four U.S. Teams To Search For MIAs, Talks Planned Between Sides</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has proposed talks with
Vietnam regarding future cooperation in the search for American
servicemen missing in action, the State Department said Tuesday.
   The talks would take place following a 10-day joint search by
four American and Vietnamese teams that starts Dec. 5, said
spokesman Charles Redman.
   Vietnam has agreed to a U.S. request to have four teams conduct
the search, an increase from the two teams that were allowed to
search various sites twice this year.
   ``We hope that this will enable us to make more rapid progress in
efforts to obtain the fullest possible accounting of those still
missing in action,'' Redman said.
   The U.S. teams will consist of technical personnel from the Joint
Casualty Resolution Center and the Army's Central Identification
Laboratory in Hawaii, he said. They will be investigating a number
of cases in the areas of Vinh and Dong Hoi, south of Hanoi.
   ``We have proposed to the Vietnamese to meet in Hanoi following
the conclusion of this activity, Dec. 19 to 21, to conduct technical
talks, to review our joint activities to date and our future work
program,'' Redman said. ``We appreciate the increased cooperation of
the government of Vietnam in these efforts.''
   Vietnam originally agreed to cooperate in the MIA searches for a
90-day period starting Sept. 1. The proposed talks would focus on
extending that period.
   Redman said the United States is ``hopeful that our joint
cooperation will continue for as long as necessary to obtain the
fullest possible accounting.''
   The United States says there are more than 2,400 Americans
missing in action from the Indochina war, most of them in Vietnam.
   The United States has rejected demands from the impoverished
Asian country that cooperation on the MIA issue be linked to the
establishment of diplomatic links. But it has allowed American
charitable groups to provide prosthetics and medical care for
handicapped children. Trade with Vietnam is banned by law.
</TEXT>
