<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ManImpaled     11-29 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Man Impaled,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Impaling May Have Saved Man's Life</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: first name Jakie is correct.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A construction worker fell three stories
and was impaled on a 6-foot steel rod, but that probably saved his
life, two doctors said.
   The heavy rod kept Jakie Dale Klaber from plunging six more
floors to the ground when it pierced his belly and groin, said Drs.
Tom Harris and Brian Zachariah, who treated Klaber at the scene
Monday.
   ``The rod basically arrested his fall,'' said Harris.
   Zachariah said that without the rod, Klaber ``would have
definitely gone over.''
   Harris said Klaber was lucid enough to answer routine questions
about his medical history.
   ``Given the circumstances, he was relatively calm,'' Zachariah
said.
   Firefighters cut the bar of concrete reinforcing rod and, with
the rod still imbedded in Klaber's body, lowered him to the ground
in a basket.
   The rod was removed in surgery at Humana Hospital-University of
Louisville.
   Klaber, 50, was in serious condition Tuesday with facial,
abdominal and groin injuries following the accident at a parking
garage being built by the Whittenberg Engineering and Construction
Co.
   Witnesses and a Whittenberg vice president said Klaber was
operating a crane from inside a control cab on top of the nine-story
building. He was hoisting a half-ton wooden concrete-form panel when
a wind gust apparently blew the 8-by-12-foot form into the wooden
cab, knocking it and Klaber over the edge.
   ``My first thought was that the crane ... killed the man in the
box,'' said Jefferson Circuit Judge Ken Corey, who watched from the
nearby Hall of Justice. ``I could see that guy inside as it headed
down.''
   Still inside the control cab, Klaber fell headfirst 36 feet to
the sixth-floor parking deck, which juts out farther than the top
three floors. He fell almost vertically onto the steel rod, located
within two feet of the garage's edge.
   The rod passed through some fat on Klaber's abdomen and part of
his groin, said Dr. Donald Thomas, director of university's
emergency room.
</TEXT>
