<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1928EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PolishChild     11-29 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polish Child,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indiana Woman Helps Obtain Medical Treatment For Polish Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST CHICAGO, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crippled Polish child on Tuesday
entered a Chicago hospital, where she will be treated free of charge
for birth defects, thanks to the efforts of a Polish-American woman.
   Seven-year-old Basia Rduch, who weighs just 20 pounds, flew to
Chicago from her homeland Monday, accompanied by her mother,
Daniela, a widowed seamstress from the village of Godow.
   The trip was made possible by the efforts of Terri Ward, 35, of
East Chicago.
   ``I feel very lucky,'' Mrs. Rduch said through a translator. ``I
couldn't ask for anything more. I have a lot of hope in my heart.''
   The youngster was taken Tuesday to the Shriners Hospital for
Crippled Children in Chicago, where she will undergo tests for
treatment for her birth defects, which include severe curvature of
the spine. Her deformity makes it difficult for her to walk and
causes digestive problems.
   After doctors in Poland told Mrs. Rduch they could not help her
child, she began efforts to get treatment in the United States. She
wrote to a Chicago hospital, but the letter did not have the correct
address and was in Polish. She never received a reply.
   Mrs. Rduch didn't give up hope, however. In August, she gave a
copy of that letter to a neighbor, who is Ms. Ward's cousin.
   ``My cousin sent me a copy of this letter and just asked me if I
could take it up to the hospital,'' said Ms. Ward, who speaks Polish
and whose parents were born in Poland.
   But Ms. Ward didn't stop there. She learned about the Shriners
program of providing free care to needy crippled and burned
children, and the charity's Chicago hospital was contacted.
   Ms. Ward, a purchasing director for Specialty Steel Products in
Hammond, also collected $3,500 in donations for Basia, most of it
from Polish-Americans in northwestern Indiana. That money paid for
the mother and daughter's trip.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
