<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nazi     11-29 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nazi,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witnesses Ready to Testify Against Most-Wanted Nazi War Criminal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nazi camp survivors are ready to
testify against an elderly man alleged to be one of 10 most-wanted
war criminals if Argentina upholds his extradition to West Germany,
officials said Tuesday.
   West German prosecutors have issued an arrest warrant for former
SS Capt. Josef Schwammberger, accused of killing thousands of people
while he was commander of Nazi labor camps in Poland during World
War II.
   An Argentine judge on Monday ordered that Schwammberger, arrested
a year ago in a remote village, be extradited to West Germany.
Shwammberger's lawyers say they will appeal the extradition order.
   Schwammberger, 76 has been a fugitive since he disappeared from a
train in 1948 while being taken from Germany to American military
authorities in Austria to be tried, according to renowned Nazi
hunter Simon Wiesenthal.
   Prosecutors allege the former SS commander was responsible for
the deaths of more than 5,000 people, mostly Jews. Camp survivors
have testified that he shot to death starving prisoners or set dogs
on them.
   ``He was a sadist, an evil person,'' said Edward Blonder of
Florida, who testified at a Argentine deportation hearing in July
along with two other survivors of the Przemysl and Mielec labor
camps.
   Stuttgart prosecutor Helmut Krombacher said witnesses from two
continents are expected to testify against Schwammberger if he goes
to trial in West Germany.
   ``Testimony has been taken from witnesses in the United States,
Israel and Argentina,'' Krombacher said. ``Many witnesses will be
available.''
   Wiesenthal said dozens of labor camp survivors are anxious to
recount what they saw Schwammberger do to prisoners.
   ``These are all first-class witnesses,'' Wiesenthal said in a
telephone interview from Vienna.
   He said the witnesses are living in the United States, Israel,
Denmark, and Austria.
   Schwammberger had been a member of the Gestapo, the Nazis' secret
police, in Innsbruck, Wiesenthal said.
   The former SS commander was arrested in Austria just after the
end of the war in 1945 and a large quantity of valuables were
confiscated from him, Wiesenthal said.
   ``(Authorities) found a large number of rings, gold watches,
jewelry and diamonds taken from victims in the labor camps,'' said
Wiesenthal, who had been tracking Schwammberger for four decades.
   The Nazi hunter said he learned in 1971 that Schwammberger was
living in La Plata, Argentina, and informed prosecutors in Stuttgart.
   But Schwammberger was apparently tipped off and fled before
Argentine police could arrest him, Wiesenthal said.
   Schwammberger's name was on a list of 10 most-wanted Nazi war
criminals published in 1987 by the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los
Angeles.
   The list appeared in Argentine newspapers, and authorities were
tipped off about Schwammberger's whereabouts, Wiesenthal said.
   Schwammberger was arrested on Nov. 13, 1987 in Huerta Grande, a
village about 500 miles northwest of Buenos Aires. Since then, he
has been jailed in La Plata, about 30 miles south of the capital.
   Argentine officials said they learned Schwammberger arrived in
Argentina in 1949 and worked for a chemical company for many years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
