<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Aid     11-29 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Aid,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Launches $10 Million Child Health Program In Iran, Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UNICEF has launched a $10 million campaign to
restore health services for mothers and children in war-ravaged
areas of Iran and Iraq, its director said Tuesday.
   A major effort would be made to expand existing programs in each
country aimed at reducing infant mortality, said UNICEF Executive
Director James P. Grant.
   ``This is the first action of rebuilding the war-torn areas in
which both countries are implicity involved,' Grant said. ``The fact
that children are concerned is a prelude for working together in
other areas.''
   Grant spoke to reporters after returning from a six-day trip to
Iran and Iraq during which he met health ministers and other
government officials.
   The U.N. Childrens' Emergency Fund campaign follows a
U.N.-negotiated cease-fire in the war that took effect Aug. 20.
   Grant said the new UNICEF program was aimed at war-devastated
areas of Iran and Iraq.
   Grant said the first emergency medical supplies _ equipment for
midwives and refrigerators for medical supplies and vaccines _
arrived in five provinces in Iran and seven in Iraq.
   He said he would seek funds to support the campaign from
governments and humanitarian associations, and that Sweden and Italy
already have made contributions. The initial $1 million that kicked
off the health program came from UNICEF emergency funds, Grant said.
   Grant said Iran had cut its death rate by half since 1980,
meaning that about 100,000 children have been saved through improved
conditions such as health measures involving parents, teachers and
officials.
   A similar program in Iraq has saved 30,000 children, Grant said.
</TEXT>
