<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hamadi     11-29 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hijacker Forced Woman At Gunpoint To Leave Husband Behind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   FRANKFURT, West Germany _ A hijacker of TWA Flight 847 put a gun
to the head of a pregnant U.S. passenger to force her to leave her
husband behind with other hostages aboard the commandeered plane, a
court heard Tuesday.
   Debra Toga also said the hijackers threatened to kill an American
passenger every five minutes.
   She testified at the trial of confessed hijacker Mohammed Ali
Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem charged with murder and air piracy
in the June 1985 hijacking. U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem was
killed in the ordeal and 39 Americans were held hostage for 17 days.
   Mrs. Toga, 30, was returning from a vacation and was seven months
pregnant when the Athens-to-Rome flight was seized. Although she
said she was not mistreated, Mrs. Toga said she heard other
passengers being beaten.
   During a stop at Algiers airport, the hijackers said they would
start killing Americans if the airplane were not refueled.
   Flight purser Uli Derickson ``told me that they were threatening
to kill one American passenger every five minutes,'' Mrs. Toga said.
   The plane was refueled and flew to Beirut.
   At one point, Mrs. Toga said, Hamadi reassured her that she was
safe and gave her fruit to eat.
   ``I was crying, but Hamadi told me that I had nothing to worry
about. He said they were interested only in young American men, but
they respected women and children,'' Mrs. Toga said.
   Stethem was killed at Beirut airport. Hamadi admits he was one of
the hijackers, but denies he killed the diver.
   Mrs. Toga said the other hijacker _ fugitive Hassan Ezzeddine _
threatened her with a gun just before she was freed in Algiers.
   ``I was chosen to leave the plane, and at that point I saw my
husband. I wanted to stay with my husband, but the other hijacker
put the gun to my head and told me to get out,'' she said.
   Her husband, Arthur, who testified later Tuesday, said: ``I was
petrified about what they did to my wife, I didn't know what had
happened to her.
   ``I was just sorry that I probably would never see my child,''
said Toga, 36.
   Under guidelines set by the court to protect witnesses, the
couple was not required to disclose their hometown. At the time of
the hijacking they lived in St. Louis.
   Before Mrs. Toga's testimony, prosecutors disclosed they had had
Hamadi's cell searched for drugs and secret communications he may
have received from Beirut. Prosecutor Peter Korneck said no drugs
were found but some documents were taken from the cell and copied.
   Hamadi and his lawyers said the documents were papers related to
the case. They charged the search was illegal and asked that Korneck
be dropped from the case. Judge Heiner Mueckenberger made no ruling.
   The defense attorneys also asked that officials from U.S.
television networks be called to testify.
   According to the attorneys, they had asked the FBI and the U.S.
Justice Department for permission to examine television tapes made
during the hijacking but had got no reply.
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt Airport in January 1987 after
customs officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
</TEXT>
