<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1631EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DoleThumbnail     11-29 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole Thumbnail,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole an Unlikely Water Carrier for Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Senate Leaders Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minority Leader Bob Dole, overwhelmingly
endorsed Tuesday to continue as the Senate's Republican leader for
another two years, seems an unlikely water carrier for the new
president-elect, George Bush.
   Himself a defeated presidential candidate, Dole has some of his
own ideas on one of the most serious problem facing Bush, reducing
the federal budget deficit, and the two don't always coincide.
   And despite a couple of public attempts to gloss over the wounds
from this year's campaign, the hurt from that bruising contest will
be slow to heal.
   ``We are ready to go to work with a new administration,'' Dole
said Tuesday after winning, uncontested, another two-year stint as
GOP Senate leader. ``The election is over. He won fair and square.''
   Unlike Bush, who was born into a wealthy Eastern family, Dole
clawed his way to the top of politics from a middle-class background
in tiny Russell, Kan. Bush went to Yale, while Dole attended
Washburn Municipal University in Topeka. The class differences have
aggravated the two men's rivalry.
   But both also are pragmatists. With the Congress now even more
firmly in Democratic control than before the election, cooperation
and compromise will be the Republicans' only keys to success.
   Dole now will have to forge a working relationship with his new
Democratic counterpart, Maine Sen. George Mitchell, who was selected
as majority leader.
   Although often partisan and acerbic in his rhetoric, and with a
biting wit, Dole has become best known as a crafter of consensus
since he became party leader in 1984. ``Work it out'' has been his
motto.
   With the Reagan administration, Dole sought where possible to be
the administration's policy point man. He did it with particular
enthusiasm on issues like judicial appointments and aid to the
Nicaraguan Contras.
   But he also was capable of independence, particularly where he
deemed it important to protect GOP senators' political interests. In
1988, Dole supported Reagan's position on just 68 percent of floor
votes, placing him about in the middle of the Republican pack on
that measure.
   Dole, 65, suffered machine gun wounds during World War II combat
in Italy that rendered his right arm useless. The affliction has
engendered in Dole support for programs to aid the handicapped and
the poor.
   He was first elected to the Senate in 1968 following service in
the House. His wife, Elizabeth, served as President Reagan's
transportation secretary before resigning to join Dole's
presidential campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881129-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1929EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Attack     11-29 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Attack,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Soldiers Killed In Rebel Ambush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels detonated mines
and opened fire on a truck carrying army troops Tuesday, killing
four soldiers and wounding eight, relief officials said.
   The rebels ambushed the truck near the El Angel sugar plantation,
about nine miles north of the capital, said Green Cross officials,
who asked not to be identified.
   The guerrillas, who belong to the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front, on Monday urged civilians not to board military
vehicles they said were subject to attack.
   In a broadcast over their clandestine radio, the rebels also
denied they were responsible for a bomb that destroyed a bus and
trailer owned by a Mexican musical group.
   The bomb, detonated outside a San Salvador hotel Saturday,
destroyed the vehicles and equipment belonging to Los Flamers. Army
officials blamed guerrillas for the explosion.
   The rebel radio broadcast blamed right-wing groups ``that
systematically have viewed the Mexican people as an ally of the
communists'' for the explosion. Rebel leaders in the past have been
based in Mexico City.
   But Mexican President Miguel de la Madrid, whose six-year term
ends Thursday, has backed away from publicly supporting the rebels.
</TEXT>
