<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PoliceKillings     11-29 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Killings,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Con Charged With Double Police Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ex-convict released from prison ahead of schedule
because of overcrowding was charged with first-degree murder Tuesday
in the deaths of two police officers allegedly shot with their own
guns.
   Charles Harry Street, 34, of Boynton Beach was ordered held
without bond on two murder counts by a Dade County judge.
   Street was arrested early Monday, an hour after police said he
disarmed two Metro-Dade officers, Richard Boles, 41, and David
Strzalkowski, 34. They were shot in the head and shoulders, over
their bulletproof vests.
   Authorities said Street then stole a patrol car and traded it for
another vehicle stolen at gunpoint in neighboring Broward County
before being caught by sheriff's deputies there.
   Street had been released from prison only 10 days before the
shootings after serving eight years of a 15-year attempted murder
sentence for shooting a man outside a bar. He has a 20-page criminal
record that includes numerous charges of assaulting police officers.
   Corrections officials said Street served more time than average
for a 15-year sentence because of frequent infractions in prison.
But they also said he got out nearly two years earlier than he
otherwise would have, because of overcrowing in Florida prisons.
   ``How could a prison system be so wrong in their profile of this
individual?'' asked Lisa Strachan, wife of the Oakland Park police
chief and member of a group calling for harsher penalties for
attacks on officers. ``How could a file contain 20 pages of a rap
sheet and not tell the probation and parole department that this
isn't a standard model citizen?''
   In 1980 alone, Street was arrested seven times _ three times on
charges of assaulting officers _ while free on bond on the attempted
murder charge in Palm Beach County, his record indicates.
   Palm Beach County State Attorney David Bludworth said more must
be done to stop releasing people like him.
   ``We cannot use overcrowding as an excuse to continually release
dangerous people that will commit crimes against our innocent
citizens,'' said Bludworth.
   But Metro-Dade Police Director Fred Taylor refuses to blame
corrections officials for his officers' deaths. ``I'm sure they did
not know when he was released from prison that he was violent,'' he
said.
   So far this year, five South Florida officers have been shot to
death, four of them in Dade County, counting the two officers slain
Monday.
</TEXT>
