<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FBI-Hispanics     11-29 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI-Hispanics,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI, Hispanics Recommend Ways To Assess Damages in Discrimination
Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI is proposing to hire
Spanish-speaking linguists and to bolster its equal employment
opportunity office as part of a damages package for Hispanic agents
who won a racial discrimination suit against the agency.
   The 311 Hispanic agents who sued are being asked to respond to
the proposals by Dec. 15. The damages must be approved by U.S.
District Judge Lucias Bunton in El Paso.
   In papers filed Monday with Bunton, the Hispanic agents asked the
court to assess damages according to a formula they devised, while
the FBI asked they be considered on a case-by-case basis.
   In a Sept. 30 decision, Bunton supported Hispanic agents'
contention that the FBI had discriminated against them in job
conditions, assignments and promotions.
   Bunton suggested then that the FBI pay court costs, pay
Spanish-speaking agents more for the specialized work they do, and
improve the promotion system and the equal employment opportunity
process in which discrimination complaints are made.
   Under the FBI's proposal, agency equal employment opportunity
counselors would receive better training and the office would be
supervised by an executive assistant FBI director.
   The FBI also promised to hire at least 30 Spanish-speaking
linguists to monitor wiretaps and to pay agents bonuses for
improving foreign-language fluency.
   The Hispanic agents had complained they were unfairly burdened
with undesirable wiretaps and dangerous assignments because of their
appearance and Spanish-speaking ability. They contended that
non-Hispanic agents who spoke Spanish were given better assignments.
   The FBI also said back pay might be due some agents, and proposed
having plaintiffs fill out a long forms to determine whether they
should receive back pay and how much.
   But the plaintiffs, represented by attorneys Hugo Rodriguez and
Antonio Silva, said such a process would require separate hearings
on each plaintiff. They proposed a formula to determine how much pay
each plaintiff gets, based on tenure, employment status and salary.
   Bunton set the Dec. 15 deadline for the plaintiffs to reply. The
FBI has until Dec. 30 to counter that response.
   The class-action lawsuit was filed in January 1987 by Bernardo
Matias ``Mat'' Perez, the second-in-command in the El Paso office
and at the time the highest-ranking Hispanic FBI agent.
</TEXT>
