<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FBI-CISPES     11-29 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI-CISPES,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Sues FBI To Seal Files From Anti-Terrorism Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An organization opposed to Reagan
administration policy in Central America filed suit against the FBI
on Tuesday, seeking to seal files compiled during the bureau's
anti-terrorism probe of the private group.
   The class-action lawsuit alleges that during the March 1983-June
1985 probe, the FBI spread false information about the Committee in
Solidarity with the People of El Salvador, linking it to terrorism
and hurting its efforts to raise money and enroll new members.
   The CISPES lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court, seeks an order
preventing the FBI from using records gathered during the probe and
requiring the bureau to seal the files and deposit them in the
National Archives.
   FBI Director William Sessions told the group in a letter two
weeks ago that the bureau would consider expunging the records of
individuals who believe they are named in the investigation and who
request such action.
   Margaret Ratner, a lawyer at the Center for Constitutional Rights
which helped CISPES file the suit, said the group is willing to
continue discussions with the FBI on the matter while the suit is
pending.
   The bureau, following a review by the Justice Department, ended
the CISPES investigation after failing to establish any substantial
link between CISPES and international terrorism. Sessions said in
September that the probe had been too broad and he disciplined half
a dozen FBI personnel for mishandling it.
   ``Director Sessions explained the investigation by saying that it
was an aberration,'' said Ratner. ``How can an investigation of such
massive scope be an aberration? It was the work of scores of FBI
offices around the country.''
   The suit alleges that the names of hundreds of people involved
with CISPES or other groups investigated in 178 spinoff
investigations are contained in several government computer
databanks, including the Terrorist Information System.
   Many of the names also have been disseminated to military
intelligence agencies as well as the State Department, the suit said.
   One of the plaintiffs, Catherine Cornell of Cincinnati, a
graduate student at Xavier University, said she is concerned she
will have difficulties in her teaching career because her name is in
FBI files from the CISPES probe.
   Ms. Cornell said she may be saddled with the unfounded and unfair
stigma of ``who would hire a terrorist?'' She and her husband, Paul
Knitter, who teaches theology at Xavier, have traveled to Nicaragua
and oppose the administration's Central American policies, but they
are not CISPES members.
   Ms. Cornell said a colleague of her husband's told her that the
FBI had visited him at Xavier in May 1987, two years after the
CISPES probe ended, and wanted to know about Knitter's reputation on
campus and what he was teaching.
   Mike Lent of the CISPES national office said the group has gotten
letters from contributors saying they would no longer donate money
to the group because they were afraid their names would turn up in
FBI files.
   Some private organizations ``have said they had concerns about
working with us because of the fact we were under FBI
investigation,'' said Lent.
   The suit said that although the investigation ended in 1985,
information supporting the probe's validity was disseminated during
a February 1988 appearance before the Senate Intelligence Committee
by the FBI's Oliver Revell.
   The suit also said a newspaper article last June quoted Sessions
as saying there had been a sufficient basis for the probe. In
September, however, after an internal FBI review of how the probe
was conducted, Sessions said the basis for the probe was information
provided by an informant who proved to be unreliable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
