<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Powell-Soviets     11-29 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Powell-Soviets,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan National Security Adviser Scoffs at Soviet Idea on Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's call for a ``Common European
Home'' shared by the East and West is merely an attempt to preserve
Soviet dominance over Eastern Europe, President Reagan's national
security adviser said Tuesday.
   In a speech prepared for a conference of the Institute for
Foreign Policy Analysis, Army Lt. Gen. Colin L. Powell said Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev should be praised for seeking reform
in his country.
   But at the same time, Powell, noting the 40th anniversary of the
North Atlantic Treaty Alliance in 1989, said this is no time for the
West to let down its guard.
   As an example, he cited what Gorbachev had proposed as a new
structure in Europe in which ``all nations _ East and West _ can
live in peace and harmony.''
   ``The Soviets assure us that there would be room in this house
for the United States and Canada as well,'' Powell said. ``We
appreciate the assurance. But we did not ask for it, nor do we need
it. We are in Europe, not at the invitation of the Soviet Union, but
in alliance with our Western allies.''
   Powell, who likely will be returning to full-time duty in the
Army when Reagan's term ends Jan. 20, asked his audience to consider
what lies behind the Soviet call for a ``Common European Home.''
   ``As I see it, it is an attempt to tie the future to the past, to
freeze the ... European status quo,'' he said. Powell acknowledged
that his conclusion ``may seem odd,'' given the Soviet
pronouncements about a new era of political thinking, embraced in
such terms of ``glasnost'' and ``perestroika.''
   But Powell said he believes, nevertheless, that the Soviet
proposal ``is an idea wedded to the past.''
   ``Forty years after the Soviets imposed their presence in the
middle of Europe,'' he said, ``the citizens of these countries still
look to the West as their historical, cultural and political
homeland. Their ferment today is a testament to the strength and
durability of these aspirations.''
   He also said the Soviets have ``rushed to construct a new home
for all of us'' because the European allies of the United States
have, at last, moved ``to construct a European pillar'' of strength,
challenging the Soviet goal of predominant power on the continent.
   ``If we analyze what this Soviet-built home would contain,'' he
said, ``we find some very old ideas indeed _ unbalanced disarmament
proposals, dissolution of military alliances, removal of foreign
bases and acceptance _ yes, acceptance _ of the ideological division
of Europe presently enforced by Soviet power.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
