<1ST_LINE>u w AM-MitchellProfile     11-29 0832</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mitchell Profile,790</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: With AM-Senate Leaders Bjt a0665</NOTE>
<HEAD>Mitchell: From Janitor's Son To Senate Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Mitchell, the new Senate majority
leader, first drew the nation's attention when he looked Lt. Col.
Oliver L. North in the eye and told him he had no monopoly on
loyalty.
   ``Please remember ... that it is possible for an American to
disagree with you on aid to the Contras, and still love God, and
still love this country, just as much as you do,'' Mitchell told the
fervent Marine officer at the nationally televised Iran-Contra
hearings.
   Although that moment represented something of a national debut
for the Maine Democrat, he had already made himself a hero among
fellow party members.
   Mitchell, as chairman of the Senate Democratic Campaign
Committee, helped engineer the 1986 comeback that saw Democrats
regain control of the Senate, which they had lost in President
Reagan's 1980 landslide.
   His reward: instant clout on the Democratic side of the aisle and
appointment as the Senate's deputy president pro tempore, an
unexciting post but an important measure of the esteem in which he
was held by his colleagues.
   Now, after an intensive backroom campaign launched after Sen.
Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., announced last April he would step aside as
majority leader, Mitchell has defeated two more senior colleagues to
take the prize.
   The losers were Sens. Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii and J. Bennett
Johnston, D-La.
   Mitchell's elevation to the Senate's top leadership post gives
him control of the chamber's agenda as the 101st Congress begins its
work and as President-elect George Bush launches his administration.
   It marks a new begining after Byrd's long tenure as party leader,
and many Senate Democrats hope Mitchell can use it to project a
positive, forward-looking image for their party in the wake of three
successive defeats for the presidency. He has vowed to share his
authority with colleagues saying, ``I do not intend to be a one-man
band.''
   Sen. Wyche Fowler, D-Ga., said he told his colleagues inside the
Democratic Caucus that Mitchell has the ability to create an
atmosphere of ``calm statesmanship that reaches beyond the
prejudices of regionalism ... the ability to achieve a truly
national consensus on policies that reject the easy answers.''
   Mitchell, 55, who has been active in Maine's Democratic politics
since 1968, is a protege of Sen. Edmund S. Muskie, D-Maine, whom he
served as administrative assistant in the early 1960s.
   After a number of political setbacks, including defeat in a bid
for governor in 1974, Mitchell, with Muskie's backing, was appointed
first as U.S. attorney for Maine, then as a federal district judge,
a lifetime appointment.
   In 1980, when Muskie resigned from the Senate to become secretary
of State, he recommended to Maine's Democratic governor that he
appoint Mitchell to fill the vacancy.
   Two years later, Mitchell won the seat in his own right by a
commanding 61 percent of the vote. He won a second term this year by
an even more impressive 81 percent.
   In the Senate, Mitchell compiled a largely liberal voting record
and became a champion of the environment, especially in the battle
against acid rain, and was an early and outspoken critic of Reagan
administration environmental policies.
   As chairman of the Finance Committee's health panel he is an
advocate for a major long-term health care plan.
   On the Veterans Affairs Committee, Mitchell backed successful
1984 legislation to help Vietnam veterans cope with diseases
believed to be caused by exposure to the herbicide Agent Orange.
   As a member of the Senate Iran-Contra Committee, Mitchell was a
steady, quiet, lawyerlike questioner.
   But as the hearings went on he became an increasingly outspoken
critic of those inside the Reagan administration, who, he said, had
subverted the authority of the president and the Constitution by
selling arms to Iran and arranging for the diversion of part of the
proceeds to Nicaragua's anti-leftist Contra rebels.
   In his address to North and the public watching on television,
Mitchell invoked the memory of his immigrant mother and laborer
father and the emotions he said he felt when, as a federal judge, he
conferred citizenship on immigrants.
   He told North that when he asked new immigrants why they wished
to live in the United States, many of them said the reason was that
``in America you can criticize the government without looking over
your shoulder.''
   That's what democracy is all about, the senator said. ``The
freedom to disagree with the government.''
   Mitchell's father was a utility company laborer who later worked
as a janitor. His mother, an immigrant from Lebanon, worked at a
wool mill in Waterville, Maine, where the family lived.
   Mitchell, who plays skillful cribbage and competitive tennis, is
a 1954 graduate of Bowdoin College in Maine and earned a law degree
from Georgetown University Law School in 1960. He was divorced last
year after 27 years of marriage. His daughter, Andrea, is a social
worker who lives in Massachusetts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881129-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1652EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-CorporateProfits     11-29 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Corporate Profits,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Profits Up Slightly in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. corporations reported a slight 0.2 percent
increase in profits in the July-September quarter after posting a
large gain in the previous three-month period, the government said
Tuesday.
   The Commerce Department said third-quarter profits after taxes
rose $400 million to $163.1 billion, the worst showing since a 2.5
percent loss in the final quarter of 1987.
   Robert Dederick, an economist with Northern Trust Co. in Chicago,
said profits are in part rebounding from the unusually strong 8.9
percent increase in the second quarter. But he said earnings also
were hurt because inflation is forcing companies to pay more for
labor and materials.
   ``They weren't able to pass on those cost increases that occurred
... This is a profit squeeze,'' he said. If it continues, it could
cut into U.S. corporation's strong spending to upgrade equipment and
expand production.
   Corporate cash flows, a measure intended to show the funds
corporations have available for investment, fell 0.7 percent in the
third quarter, following a 1.4 percent rise in the April-June period.
   However, if unemployment remains low, Dederick said corporations
likely will succeed in raising prices to customers and profits will
rebound, he said.
   Corporate profits before taxes were up 0.6 percent in the third
quarter to $307.7 billion, following a 6.9 percent increase in the
previous three-month period.
   Dividend payments to stockholders rose 2.5 percent to $105.7
billion in the third quarter, up from a 1.8 percent gain in the
second quarter.
</TEXT>
