<DOCNO> AP881129-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1653EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DeltaHearing Bjt   11-29 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delta Hearing, Bjt,0706</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delta Pilot Says He Might Have Bent Some Rules</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto covering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IRVING, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of a Delta Air Lines jetliner that
crashed Aug. 31, killing 14 people, testified Tuesday that some
rules might have been bent in readying the Boeing 727 for takeoff
but that preparations were adequate.
   Larry Davis admitted seeming deviations from the rules under
questioning by aerospace engineer Jeff Gorney as the National
Transportation Safety Board opened an inquiry into the crash on
takeoff at Dallas International Airport. Ninety-four people survived.
   For instance, the Delta veteran of 23 years said he had used hand
signals instead of calling out completion of each item on the
pre-flight checklist and had made a takeoff briefing at the gate
instead of on the runway.
   ``I like to get as much done as possible before we get into the
position of getting rushed,'' said Davis.
   Gorney also said a flight attendant was allowed into the cockpit
when the jet was waiting to take off, despite an Federal Aviation
Administration rule requiring a ``sterile'' cockpit once the plane
has left the gate.
   But he noted that the plane was ``waiting in a line of traffic''
and added: ``I don't believe it was a critical phase of flight, but
technically it was (in violation).''
   The FAA requires pilots to go through a checklist but does not
specifically require a verbal a ``challenge and response'' between
pilots. The agency, however, has made clear on many occasions that
such an exchange is preferable.
   According to NTSB documents, Delta procedures Aug. 31 only
suggested a verbal exchange during some phases of the checklist.
   FAA recently chastised Delta for inadequate cockpit discipline
and poor coordination and communications among pilots, and Delta has
said that it will formalize the checklist process with increased
emphasis on verbal challenges.
   Delta procedures say the pre-flight briefing should take place
``before takeoff'' but also says it could begin during the ``before
start check'' which normally occurs about five minutes before the
plane pushes back from the gate.
   Davis testified that he went to full power as soon as he felt
engine ``compressor stalls'' unlike any he had ever felt before.
   ``It was like driving a car 60 mph down the highway and driving
into a water puddle. It was pronounced deceleration,'' Davis he said
under questioning from a representative of Pratt & Whitney,
manufacturer of the airplane's engines.
   Investigators have ruled out mechanical failure as a cause of the
stalls, and have focused instead on the position of the wing flaps,
which the NTSB said were found retracted instead of extended for
takeoff in the wreckage.
   The wing flap lever in the cockpit was in the wrong position
after the crash, the board said. But in the cockpit recording, the
co-pilot can be heard saying ``15, 15, green light'' before takeoff
to verify the flaps' proper deployment.
   Davis said Tuesday he did not know if the other crew members
might have touched the flap handle as the plane was in trouble.
   ``I was too busy flying the plane. I wouldn't have seen it,'' he
said.
   A pilots union contends a ``split flap configuration'' may have
occurred, placing one flap up and one down. The union contends that
in that case, the takeoff warning system of the 727 would not
necessarily alert the crew of the danger.
   The Air Line Pilots Association has accused the NTSB of making a
premature finding of pilot error.
   Air Line Pilots Association spokesman John Mazor, listening to
Davis' testimony, said it is standard for pilots with Davis'
experience to deviate slightly from procedures.
   ``There are reams and reams of manuals and regulations. It would
be impossible to remember them all,'' Mazor said.
   Fourteen of the 108 people on board died. The three-man flight
crew was among the survivors.
   ``It's fortunate the crew is alive. That's not always the case.
We're very hopeful the crew will be able to provide assistance where
in other crashes there's no (surviving) crew,'' NTSB spokesman Mike
Benson said before the hearing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881129-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1654EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SpaceShuttle 1stLd-Writethru a0613 11-29 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Shuttle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0613,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Presses On with Atlantis Countdown Despite Unfavorable
Forecast</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE, launch decision delayed for a
day, tire leak. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Once they...' Adds 1 graf at
end with landing rehearsals.
^By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA forged ahead Tuesday with the
countdown for the secret mission of space shuttle Atlantis despite a
forecast for unacceptably high wind and rain showers at launch time.
   Because of the forecast for Thursday morning liftoff, shuttle
managers said they would meet again Wednesday for a more up-to-date
look at the situation. The five astronauts on Atlantis are to
release a huge spy satellite in orbit.
   Otherwise, said the top level NASA Mission Management Team,
``preparations for launch are going very well.''
   The managers said in a statement they weren't concerned by one
lingering problem: a leaking tire on the shuttle's main landing gear.
   The leak rate was 1.7 pounds per square inch a day on a tire that
on Tuesday held 333 pounds. The agency said at that rate the
pressure would remain high enough for a week more on the launch pad.
The tire must have at least 275 psi when the spacecraft lands at
Edwards Air Force Base.
   Technicians can't reach the tire, which is filled with gaseous
nitrogen, while the landing gear doors are closed. A refill would
require rolling the shuttle back to its hangar and separating it
from the external fuel tank, a process that would take weeks.
   The upcoming launch is being treated with as much secrecy as
possible and the Air Force has said only that it is scheduled for
Thursday between 6:32 a.m. and 9:32 a.m. EST. The precise time will
be disclosed just nine minutes before liftoff. The big countdown
clocks at the site were kept blank.
   Despite the hushed atmosphere, much is known about Atlantis'
mission. The astronauts will release a $500 million satellite _ the
first of a series called Lacrosse _ that can discern targets of
military interest in 80 percent of the Soviet Union.
   Once they have released the satellite, dropping it overboard
using the shuttle's robot crane, Atlantis will hover nearby to make
sure everything works. If it doesn't, the astronauts will retrieve
the Lacrosse and bring it back to Earth.
   NASA said there was a 70 percent probability that the weather
will be below the strict limits laid down since the Challenger
explosion Jan. 28, 1986, that claimed seven lives.
   Those rules include winds of less than 19 mph from the south or
28 mph from any direction, no rain at the pad or in the flight path
and no thunderstorms within five miles.
   The forecast was for winds of 15 to 28 mph, three layers of
clouds and isolated showers.
   The flight will be the third shuttle mission dedicated to the
military and the second flight since the Challenger disaster. No
details will be released during the flight unless something goes
wrong with the spacecraft. The other all-military flights were in
1985.
   The crew will be Navy Cmdr. Robert L. Gibson, spaceship
commander; Air Force Lt. Col. Guy S. Gardner, pilot; and mission
specialists Col. Richard M. Mullane and Lt. Col. Jerry L. Ross of
the Air Force and Navy Cmdr. William M. Shepherd.
   Gibson and Gardner practiced the landings they would have to make
on the Kennedy Space Center runway in case of engine failure,
rehearsing the steep descents in an airplane built to handle like a
shuttle. All five astronauts then were given medical examinations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881129-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 2001EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Conable     11-29 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Conable,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conable Denounces Barriers to Third World Goods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World Bank President Barber B. Conable on
Tuesday denounced trade barriers that prevent Third World nations
from selling their goods in the United States and other industrial
countries.
   Conable said aid to Third World countries was only half as much
as they could earn if they were permitted to sell their goods freely
to the donor countries.
   ``If you were to eliminate all international aid and all
trade-distorting obstacles, you would have twice as a good a
situation in terms of resource transfers for the developing world as
you've got now,'' he said.
   Conable estimated the annual value of aid from all industrial
countries at $35 billion a year, while their trade barriers
prevented exports to them worth $60 billion. That was only the
primary effect of the barriers, because additional trade would
stimulate Third World growth, he added.
   ``The Caribbean countries alone have lost three quarters _ over
$250 million worth _ of their annual sugar exports to the United
States,'' he said.
   ``In 1987 the U.S. imposed anti-dumping actions on carnations (to
limit imports) from Mexico, Costa Rica, Ecuador and Chile. All four
exported only $16 million worth of cut flowers to the U.S.; during
that same year they paid almost 150 times that amount in interest to
U.S. commercial creditors,'' he in a statement he will submit next
week in Montreal to a meeting of cabinet members of nearly 100
governments. The session will review progress toward dismantling
trade barriers.
   Conable distributed blame widely.
   He noted that West European countries became the world's biggest
exporters of beef and wheat while the share of the market supplied
by Argentina and Uruguay, two of the lowest cost producers, dropped
sharply. He said the high price paid for rice to Japanese farmers,
five times the world level, closed off sales by Thailand and
Pakistan.
   The Third World's $1.2 trillion debt is not up for discussion in
Montreal. But Conable said it clearly is related to trade since
whatever may be done about debt, the Third World will need to sell
more goods.
   Three years ago, then-Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III
proposed additional lending to Third World countries to help them
grow out of their problems. Little additional lending has been
forthcoming. More recently, Baker, whom President-elect George Bush
has tapped as his secretary of state, has been promoting a ``menu of
options'' under which debt may be reduced by agreement between
creditor banks and debtor governments.
   ``You're getting an evolution of the so-called Baker plan,''
Conable said.
   The World Bank is the biggest source of international aid. The
bank, owned by 151 countries, lends the Third World about $20
billion a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
