<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Salinas Bjt   11-29 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Salinas, Bjt,0776</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico's New President: Tough and Flexible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlos Salinas de Gortari has proved himself
tough and flexible, necessary qualities for dealing with the
economic crisis and growing political opposition he will face after
becoming president on Thursday.
   He is an economist with no experience in elective office, and at
40 will be Mexico's youngest president in half a century. That may
be fitting, since more than half the nation's 84 million people are
under 16.
   Salinas also has a disadvantage none of his predecessors has
experienced: serious division within the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, which is known by its Spanish initials PRI and has governed
Mexico since 1929.
   In addition to being the youngest president in decades, Salinas
also is one of the best educated. He has two master's degrees and a
doctorate in public administration, all from Harvard, and speaks
fluent English and French.
   The new president is short, trim and bald, dresses smartly and
has a full black mustache that enhances an expression of
half-puzzled wistfulness that often appears on his face.
   Friends who know him well, including political writer Adrian
Lajous, say the genial, shy exterior hides a man of considerable
ability and political savvy. As evidence, they offer the fact that
he won the presidential nomination from a half-dozen older PRI
rivals.
   As budget secretary under Miguel de la Madrid, the outgoing
president, Salinas revealed himself as a deft political infighter,
excellent organizer and stickler for efficiency.
   ``He is very fast mentally,'' Lajous wrote recently. ``He plucks
ideas out of thin air. His thinking is very sophisticated ... and
it's a pleasure to watch him sparring.''
   Salinas is known as a demanding boss who expects things to run on
time _ what Mexicans call ``American time'' rather than the less
precise ``Mexican time.''
   So greatly does the new president admire Japanese discipline that
he sends his children to a school run by Japanese.
   He was born April 3, 1948, in Mexico City but his family is from
Nuevo Leon, a northern industrial state. He married Cecilia Occelli
Gonzalez in 1972, seven years after they met at a dance, and they
have three children: Cecilia, 14; Emiliano 12, and Juan Cristobal, 9.
   A keen sportsman, Salinas was a member of the Mexican riding
association and the national equestrian team, winning a silver medal
at the 1971 Pan American Games. He keeps fit by running and playing
tennis and is an ardent soccer fan.
   Like his most recent predecessors, Salinas rose through the ranks
of the bureaucracy as a loyal PRI member. He comes from an old
family of seasoned PRI politicians that settled in the small town of
Agualeguas in Nuevo Leon in the 18th century, and joined the party
at age 18.
   Raul Salinas, his father, has served in the Senate and as
commerce secretary. His mother, Margarita de Gortari Carvajal, is an
economist and was active in party politics for many years.
   Mexico's president is limited to a single six-year term and
Salinas faces problems that would have given some of his
predecessors nightmares.
   An economic crisis has impoverished Mexico since the bottom fell
out of world oil prices in 1982.
   Enormous grass-roots support that kept the PRI in power for two
generations has diminished and the spendthrift days of the oil boom
are gone.
   Payments on the $102 billion foreign debt have sapped development
and prompted complaints the country's efforts to develop industry
and increase exports serve only to pay Wall Street bankers.
   Salinas won narrowly in an election July 6 that was tainted by
charges of fraud. The PRI won only 260 seats in the 500-seat Chamber
of Deputies, compared with its customary 70 percent or more.
   The wishes of his predecessors often amounted to orders, but
Salinas will have to negotiate and compromise with opposition
leaders who want to use public disaffection with the PRI as a
springboard for the 1994 election.
   Political analysts say the results last election's results
indicate people are weary of the PRI's high-handed ways and want a
change.
   At a recent rally, Salinas said the ``one-party'' era is over and
the PRI must learn to hustle for votes, but there were more charges
of fraud in recent state elections.
   In speeches and interviews, Salinas has said he will
``modernize'' Mexico, paring down the bureaucracy, getting rid of
state-owned companies that lose money, fighting corruption,
balancing the budget, reducing inflation, forcing export industries
to become more efficient and reforming the PRI.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
