<DOCNO> AP881129-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1714EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Glance     11-29 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Glance,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mexico-Salinas Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures about Mexico:
   THE LAND
   Mexico shares a 2,062-mile border with the United States. Its
neighbors on the south are Guatemala and Belize. It covers 761,064
square miles, about three times the area of Texas. The Pacific Ocean
is on the west, the Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean on the east.
The southern half is lush and tropical, the north arid. Much of the
terrain is mountainous.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE PEOPLE
   Mexico has about 84 million people, roughly half of them under
age 16, and 18 million of them live in the Mexico City metropolitan
area. About 55 percent are of Spanish-Indian descent and 29 percent
Indian. An estimated 90 percent are Roman Catholic.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE ECONOMY
   Crude oil exports are the heart of the economy, but non-petroleum
exports are growing rapidly. Sharply lower oil prices caused an
economic crisis and the standard of living has been cut in half
since 1982. Payments on the $102 billion foreign debt take money
from development, a major problem for a nation that must create 1
million jobs a year just to keep up with population growth. The
economy is a mixture of private enterprise and the government, which
runs many industries, including oil through the monopoly Pemex.
Mexico is the United States' fourth biggest trading partner; the
two-way exchange in 1987 was $35.1 billion. Inflation reached 159.2
percent in 1987 but has been reduced to less than 1 percent a month.
The daily minimum wage is $3.50.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE GOVERNMENT
   Mexico has a federal, republican form of government with a
500-seat Chamber of Deputies and a 64-seat Senate. The president is
elected every six years for a single term. The nation is divided
into 31 states and the Federal District, part of Mexico City. The
Institutional Revolutionary Party has governed since its founding in
1929. Relations with the United States are historically paramount
and often tense. Many Mexicans still resent the loss of more than
half the country's territory to the United States in the first half
of the 19th century.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
