<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FinanceMeeting     11-29 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Finance Meeting,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Treasury Secretary to Confer with Allies Early in Adminstration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady and the
finance ministers of America's major allies will meet soon after
President-elect George Bush takes office in January, a U.S.
government source said Tuesday.
   The source, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said the
session was planned to allow Brady to answer questions from his
counterparts about the new administration's economic policies.
   The Washington Post reported Tuesday that a tentative plan for
the meeting was outlined in Paris two weeks ago at a meeting
attended by Assistant Treasury Secretary David Mulford and the
deputy finance ministers of Japan, West Germany, France, Britain,
Canada and Italy.
   The seven countries, dubbed the Group of Seven, meet each year
for economic summits. Finance ministers from the nations convene
three or four times a year to further efforts to promote coordinated
economic policies.
   The source said no dramatic announcements of policy changes would
be coming from the post-inauguration meeting.
   ``The meeting is to give (Brady) a chance to reassure his
counterparts of policies under a Bush administration,'' the source
said.
   The meeting is expected to take place in late February or early
March.
   Both Bush and Brady have been forced since the election to
reassure jittery financial markets that the new administration has
no secret plan to drive down the value of the dollar as a way of
curing the nation's huge trade deficits.
   Bush has insisted that as president he will pursue the same
policy of coordinated efforts to stabilize the value of the dollar
that the Reagan administration has been pursuing since February 1987.
</TEXT>
