<1ST_LINE>r w AM-InsuranceInsolvency     11-29 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insurance Insolvency,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>States Should Move Quickly To Close Insolvent Insurers, Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State regulators should move more quickly to
liquidate insolvent insurers to minimize public harm and avoid
costly failures similar to those that have hit the savings and loan
industry, an insurance group recommended Tuesday.
   ``What we need today is a new determination by the regulators to
act swiftly,'' said Martin J. McFadden Jr., president of the
National Association of Insurance Brokers.
   ``In the real world, there are significant pressures which
encourage regulatory delay rather than fast action against insolvent
underwriters,'' McFadden told a National Press Club news conference.
   But ``the consequences for policyholders, regulators and insurers
are far more severe than they would be if regulators acted
quickly,'' he said.
   The study, ``Managing Insurer Insolvency,'' was prepared by
Stewart Economics Inc. for the NAIB. The association represents 58
international, regional and local firms that write more than 75
percent of the property-casualty insurance policies for business and
industry in the United States.
   ``Many years ago, the mission (of regulation) was to prevent
insolvencies. It was achieved by government support for cartel
pricing which covered the costs of the weak,'' the study said.
``Keeping weak insurers afloat was an accepted cost of the cartel
system.''
   But Richard Stewart, one of the study's authors and the former
superintendent of insurance of New York State, contended that
``insolvency is a result of regulation.''
   Stewart said regulators operating on principles from the
industry's ``cartel legacy'' too often focus on heroic rescues of
insolvent insurers acting ``as a doctor who needs to keep the
patient alive'' instead of allowing failing companies to go under.
   ``This won't get at the guts of the problem ... taking an
insurance company out of the marketplace before it does something
awful to save itself,'' Stewart said.
   Barbara Stewart, a co-author of the study, said changing
liability rules, catastrophic coverage, insurance of the most risky
situations and events and increased competition also were
contributing to the worsening insurer insolvency problem.
   There have been about 58 property-casualty insurer insolvencies
since 1983 according to the NAIB.
   Citing a House Energy and Commerce Committee investigation begun
this fall into the failure of Mission Insurance Co. in California _
which is estimated to cost $1.5 billion _ McFadden warned that
investigations of other failed insurers will continue next year.
   ``There appears to be growing concern among federal policymakers
that the insurance insolvency problem could parallel the savings and
loan insolvency problem if regulatory policies remain unchanged,''
McFadden said.
   ``There are disturbing similarities in the insurance industry and
S&Ls, where fraud and mismanagement resulted in the collapse of the
system,'' said John Chesson, counsel to the House subcommittee
overseeing the insurance insolvency investigations.
   Chesson said Mission's insolvency and two others the committee is
investigating, Integrity Insurance Co. in New Jersey and the Los
Angeles-based Transit Insurance Co., represent ``the three largest
failures ever in the history of insurance.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881129-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1725EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SenateLeaders-Scene     11-29 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senate Leaders-Scene,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Battle Ends With Grace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hard-fought contest for Senate majority
leader, marked by months of cajoling, concluded Tuesday in an aura
of eloquence and cordiality.
   Maybe it was the hallowed walls of the Old Senate Chamber, used
officially from 1810 to 1859, and still employed occasionally for
secret meetings like this.
   Sens. George Mitchell of Maine and Bennett Johnston of Louisiana
sat together and chatted as they awaited the opening gavel of the
third competitor, Democratic conference secretary Daniel Inouye of
Hawaii.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, the vice presidential nominee, won a
standing ovation from his Democratic colleagues and praise from
nearly every speaker.
   And when the first ballot for majority leader put Mitchell one
short of the 28 he needed to win, Johnston and Inouye rose to their
feet as one to call for a Mitchell victory by acclamation.
   ``It was extraordinarily cordial,'' said Sen. Jay Rockefeller,
D-W.Va. ``There was not one instance of rancor or disconsonance.''
   ``There was no tension at all,'' said Sen. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn.
   ``There were some extraordinarily good talks,'' said Sen. Wyche
Fowler, D-Ga.
   Seven people spoke on behalf of the three majority leader
contenders _ two for Mitchell, two for Inouye and three for
Johnston. ``I, of course, was the shortest,'' quipped Fowler, a
Mitchell partisan.
   Outside the chamber, a handful of security officers were charged
with keeping order among crowds of reporters, photographers and
lobbyists stationed at the imposing mahogany Ohio Clock, presented
by the state when it became a state.
   The eagle-topped clock ticked on for more than two hours, and a
grinning Mitchell finally emerged, flanked by his vanquished rivals
and the rest of the Democratic leadership.
   Later, surrounded by reporters in his office, Mitchell took a
series of congratulatory phone calls from President Reagan,
President-elect George Bush and Vice President-elect Dan Quayle.
   In a jovial conversation with Bush, Mitchell told him ``it is a
welcome sign of your good judgment that you have chosen to live in
Maine even though you didn't have the good fortune to be born
there.''
   On a more serious note, Mitchell told Bush: ``I want very much to
work with you. We've got serious problems and challenges and we want
to deal with them in cooperation with you.''
   Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kansas, re-elected Senate minority leader on
Tuesday, said he would be able to work well with Mitchell. The
sometimes caustic Kansan said a more confrontational approach
``would be unaccustomed to a senator like myself.''
</TEXT>
