<1ST_LINE>r w AM-McNamara-Defense     11-29 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-McNamara-Defense,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Secretary Says Pentagon Already `Bankrupt'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Defense Secretary Robert S. McNamara
called Tuesday for cancellation of a major U.S. bomber project and
two aircraft carrier groups to trim spending by an already
``bankrupt'' Pentagon.
   He said the budget will have to be cut $150 billion to $200
billion dollars over five years and the department, itself,
restructured.
   McNamara, who was defense secretary from 1961 until 1968, said he
sympathized with President-elect George Bush's unnamed choice to run
the Pentagon.
   ``There is just no question about it,'' he told the Arms Control
Association at the private group's annual luncheon meeting. ``The
Defense Department is bankrupt. They have on contract and plan for
contract more weapons than any reasonable level of a budget will
support for the next five years.''
   McNamara said cutting the budget and restructuring the Pentagon
``is going to be one hell of a job, particularly if you do it
without reducing security.''
   In fact, he said, ``it's damn near impossible and perhaps
politically impossible. You are going to have to cut two carrier
groups, either the B-1 or B-2. You are going to have to do all kinds
of things that are going to be politically unpopular.''
   In his speech, McNamara urged completion of a strategic arms
reduction treaty with the Soviet Union designed to slash U.S. and
Soviet arsenals of long-range nuclear weapons by 30 to 50 percent.
   ``The treaty can be completed in a year or less,'' he said.
   But, McNamara said, arguments raised against the treaty could
cause the process to unravel. He cited the claim the cutbacks would
make remaining U.S. land-based intercontinental ballistic missiles
more vulnerable to Soviet attack and that the numerical advantage in
Soviet ground forces would pose a greater danger to Western Europe.
   ``If the attacks continue they can prove to be decisive and we
will lose the marvelous opportunity to reduce weapons and increase
stability,'' McNamara said.
</TEXT>
