<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MultipleTransplant 1stLd-Writethru a0603 11-29 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Transplant, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0603,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toddler Gets Five New Organs in Rare Transplant</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS in 2nd graf that girl received whole stomach and part
of a large intestine and that spleen was removed; INSERTS 10 grafs
after 2nd to UPDATE with operation completed; quotes; picks up 11th
graf pvs, `Roleandrea arrived...'; SUBS 10th graf pvs, `She
received...' to conform: DELETES superfluous last graf</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PG2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A toddler's abdomen was virtually replaced
Tuesday in a rare five-organ transplant that doctors said was the
3-year-old girl's only chance for survival.
   Rolandrea Dodge of Fruitland, N.M., received a new liver,
pancreas, stomach, small intestine and a portion of a large
intestine. The young donor was not identified. Rolandrea's spleen
also was removed.
   ``The patient is doing fine,'' said Dr. Satoru Todo, who headed
the surgical team at Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh.
   Todo said the 16{-hour operation, which is considered
experimental, went smoothly except for one episode when the chilled
organs inserted into her body lowered her temperature dramatically
and her heart stopped beating for about a minute.
   He said surgeons restarted her heart with cardio-pulmonary
resuscitation techniques.
   Todo said Rolandrea's heart was functioning normally following
surgery, and she was moving her hands and legs. Her liver also was
producing bile, a positive sign, he said.
   She was in critical condition in the hospital's intensive care
unit after the operation, which ended at 3:40 p.m. Tuesday.
   ``The prognosis is very difficult to say, but I'm expecting it to
go well,'' Todo said.
   Five organs have been transplanted simultaneously only once
before. Last November, Tabatha Foster, 3{, of Madisonville, Ky.,
underwent the same operation at the same hospital. She died six
months later of a blood infection.
   Tabatha survived longer than any of the other three people in the
United States who had abdominal transplants involving two or more
organs.
   ``They (doctors) may have gone ahead with a little more
confidence knowing how far Tabatha succeeded,'' said hospital
spokeswoman Sue Cardillo.
   Rolandrea, who is known as Rolly, was born with an incurable
disease called intractable secretory diarrhea, which prevented her
intestines from absorbing food and liquids. She had to be fed
intravenously, although she was allowed occasional nibbles of candy,
potatoes and other solid food.
   Aside from brief outings, Rolly has spent her entire life in
hospitals.
   The girl's liver began failing about three months ago as a result
of her high-protein intravenous feedings, and her skin became
jaundiced.
   She received a pancreas and stomach in addition to intestines and
a liver because it is easier to implant a large portion of the
abdominal tract all at once.
   Rolandrea arrived in October to be evaluated for transplant. She
was accompanied by her parents, Branden and Cyndi Dodge, who also
have two sons. Her parents were with her before she went into
surgery.
   Doctors in New Mexico said she wouldn't survive long without a
transplant.
   Doctors began administering an experimental drug Nov. 9 in hopes
of allowing her intestines to absorb food and liquids, but it was
unsuccessful, Ms. Cardillo said. ``That was really the last
available treatment option,'' she said.
   Dodge, 27, a coal miner, said it was difficult deciding whether
to allow the transplant, but ``it's the only hope that we've got
left.''
   ``We don't have any doubts,'' he said. ``It's just the way our
Indian people are. That's just the way they taught us, try not to
think negative about things, it's going to work out.''
</TEXT>
