<1ST_LINE>r w AM-LaRouche 1stLd-Writethru a0642 11-29 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0642,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LaRouche Group Bought Property While Loans Stayed Unpaid, Trial
Told</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 7 grafs after 11th graf pvs, bgng: ``Yes' Welsh...''
to add details; picks up 12th graf pvs, bgng: ``LaRouche was...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lyndon H. LaRouche's political movement
was buying expensive Virginia properties at a time when millions of
dollars in loans to his organizations were not being repaid, the
political maverick's conspiracy trial was told Tuesday.
   Richard Welsh, a LaRouche aide, said a LaRouche real estate
company spent about $4 million on land for a security training
facility, for a summer camp for children of LaRouche employees and a
farm where LaRouche and his wife Helga live when in the United
States.
   During the same period, around May 1986, LaRouche wrote Elizabeth
Sexton, who was seeking repayment of nearly $113,000 in loans, that
she could not be repaid because no discretionary funds were
available.
   LaRouche and six associates are on trial in U.S. District Court
on charges that they conspired to defraud investors by not repaying
more than $30 million in loans that they made to LaRouche
organizations.
   LaRouche alone is charged with conspiring to defraud the Internal
Revenue Service by failing to declare as income personal and
household services provided him by his organizations.
   Welsh, who received immunity from prosecution, testified that $5
million of the loan amount eventually was repaid.
   Welsh, who was assistant treasurer of LaRouche's 1984
presidential campaign and still works for him, said the campaign
devised a plan to pay back $4 million it borrowed for that campaign
but that the repayment system broke down. He said the campaign still
owes between $1.5 million and $2 million.
   Welsh said that when lenders complained about non-repayment, the
local campaign organizer who originally secured the money was to
attempt to have the loan forgiven or a new schedule of payments
worked out.
   But Welsh said the system did not work well, because some
organizers never got back to the lender and others made an
``insufficient effort.'' In some cases, he said, lenders were told
something would be done when no action was planned.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Kent Robinson asked Welsh if lenders were
told in effect, ``the check is in the mail'' when no check had been
issued.
   ``Yes,'' Welsh replied.
   Under cross-examination from LaRouche attorney Odin Anderson,
Welsh sought to distance LaRouche from day-to-day operations of his
organizations.
   ``He is the founder and leading thinker, the primary person who
defines broad policies ... general objectives and political goals,''
Welsh said. ``I don't recall him involved in day-to-day financial
operations.''
   Welsh also told the jury that in September 1986 he launched
``Project Apollo'' to gain ``control of the loan situation.'' He
said the project involved a combination of repayments, requests for
forgiveness of loans and attempts to have promised interest rates
lowered or payments stretched out.
   He said the operation came to a sudden halt when federal and
state law enforcement authorities raided LaRouche's Leesburg, Va.,
headquarters Oct. 6, 1986, and ``seized just about every scrap of
paper having to do with any financial record.''
   Despite the raid, Welsh testified, virtually all the 3,500 people
with loans outstanding had been contacted and total debt by early
1987 was reduced by $1.5 million.
   In addition, Welsh said that in April 1987 the three main
LaRouche organizations that owed lenders money were placed in
involuntary bankruptcy, in a government action that froze the
groups' financial transactions.
   The final disruption to the repayment campaign, Welsh said, came
when several banks froze LaRouche organization accounts after it
became public knowledge that a federal grand jury in Boston was
investigating the movement's financial dealings.
   LaRouche was indicted in October on 13 counts of mail fraud,
conspiracy to commit mail fraud and conspiracy to defraud the IRS.
The mail fraud counts stem from promissory notes and letters of
credit sent through the mails by the LaRouche organization.
Conviction on all counts could carry a maximum penalty of 65 years
in prison and fines of $3.25 million for LaRouche.
   The six associates face lesser sentences if convicted of the mail
fraud and conspiracy charges, which cover the years 1983 to 1987.
   In the tax conspiracy count, the federal grand jury charged that
LaRouche has not filed a federal income tax return since at least
1979.
   On trial with LaRouche are his chief fund-raiser, William Wertz;
his legal adviser, Edward Spannaus; and four fund-raisers: Michael
Billington, Dennis Small, Paul Greenberg and Joyce Rubinstein.
</TEXT>
