<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Truce     11-29 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Truce,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Extends Nicaraguan Truce</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua extended
a truce with guerrillas through the end of December, but said
Tuesday his nation will maintain a state of alert until it sees a
change in U.S. policy.
   Ortega's leftist Sandinista government extends a March 21
cease-fire unilaterally on a monthly basis. The U.S.-backed rebels,
called Contras, say the truce is indefinite and need not be extended.
   Each side has accused the other of violations. Ortega renewed the
charges Tuesday during a news conference at the Nicaraguan
ambassador's residence.
   The truce forbids offensive military action. Ortega denied Contra
claims that soldiers have attacked, and characterized recent army
operations as defensive.
   He is in Mexico City for the Thursday inauguration of
President-elect Carlos Salinas de Gortari and said he had no plans
to meet Secretary of State George P. Shultz, who will represent the
United States.
   Ortega said he would wait and see what happens when George Bush
is installed in January as president of the United States, but told
the news conference:
   ``While the U.S. government doesn't show a changed attitude
toward Nicaragua, we can't change our own readiness, up to and
including the possibility of invasion by American troops. We are in
constant and permanent alert.''
   Other Nicraguan officials have said they expect a more
``pragmatic'' attitude toward Nicaragua by a Bush administration.
Ortega said he hopes the new administration will accept ``as a
reality that we survived all the efforts of a superpower to destroy
the Nicaraguan revolution.''
   He referred to President Reagan's support for the Contras since
they began fighting eight years ago. Congress has refused to provide
money for weapons since March.
   The Nicaraguan president said the Salinas inauguration gives
Central American presidents a good chance to discuss problems on an
informal basis, and said they should arrange a future meeting
``without preconditions.''
   Presidents Jose Napoleon Duarte of El Salvador, Jose Azcona Hoyo
of Honduras and Vinicio Cerezo of Guatemala also are to attend the
inauguration but not Oscar Arias of Costa Rica. Arias won the 1987
Nobel Peace Prize for a Central American peace plan that was agreed
upon Aug. 7, 1987, but has stalled.
   When asked if he would be willing to drop a complaint against
Honduras at the World Court in The Hague, Netherlands, Ortega said:
``We should meet without any preconditions to discuss our problems,
and not only if all our problems are solved.''
   The Sandinistas and the Contras signed a cease-fire agreement
March 23 under which the rebels were to stop fighting in exchange
for democratic reforms in Nicaragua. Both sides suspended offensive
military operations and a formal truce took effect April 1.
   Talks on details of the truce agreement broke off and no
negotiations have been held since September. Most Contra fighters
have left Nicaragua for camps in Honduras.
   Nicaragua accuses Honduras of harboring the rebels and permitting
them to launch operations from Honduran territory. That is the basis
of the World Court action.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
