<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Monet     11-29 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Monet,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Store Pays $10 Million For Monet Waterlilies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of Claude Monet's famous Impressionist
paintings of waterlilies was bought in London Tuesday night for 5.72
million pounds ($10.53 million) by Japan's Seibu department store.
   Auctioneers Sotheby's did not identify the Swiss seller but said
her husband bought the 1908 painting in Paris in 1946 for 1,500
pounds (then just over $6,000).
   The bidding started at 2 million pounds ($3.68 million) and
jumped in bursts of 200,000 pounds ($368,500) and 300,000 pounds
($552,750) in seconds to its final price in a telephone bid from
Tokyo.
   The sale took place 24 hours after another Japanese store,
Mitsukoshi, paid $38.46 million for Pablo Picasso's ``Acrobat and
Young Harlequin'' at Christie's, to make it the most expensive 20th
century work of art.
   Monet, founder of the Impressionist school of painting, depicted
the waterlilies in his garden at Giverny many times. The painting
sold Tuesday was one of an acclaimed series exhibited in Paris in
1909.
</TEXT>
