<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Marcos     11-29 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marcos,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medical Report Says Marcos Can Travel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government doctors say former Philippines
President Ferdinand Marcos is healthy enough to travel to New York
for arraignment on criminal racketeering charges, a spokesman said
Tuesday.
   ``We received word that Dr. (Francis) Weld decided the president
was healthy enough to travel to New York,'' said spokesman Gemmo
Trinidad. ``But we have received no official report on the matter
and I'm going to have to refer all other questions to our lawyers.
   ``I'm with the president, I see him every day, and it's clear he
is not well, not healthy enough to travel, no matter what the
doctors say,'' Trinidad added.
   Trinidad said he did not know when the 71-year-old exiled leader
was expected to appear and would not disclose Marcos' reaction to
the news.
   Defense lawyers contend Marcos is too frail to make the 10-hour
flight and a hearing is scheduled Monday before Judge John Keenan in
New York.
   Marcos fled to Hawaii in February 1986 after military-civilian
revolt ended his 20-year rule and catapulted Corazon Aquino to the
presidency.
   Marcos has been using a wheelchair since he and his wife, Imelda,
were indicted on criminal racketeering charges accusing them of
plundering the Philippines' treasury and stashing much of the money
in the United States.
   Marcos has been treated in the past for eye ailments, chest
pains, severe headaches and calcium deposits near the knee. In
recent appearances, he has also worn a neck brace.
   Mrs. Marcos pleaded innocent to the charges Oct. 31 in New York
and was released on $5 million bail provided by tobacco heiress
Doris Duke, a close friend who owns a home here.
   Marcos lawyers have said they would ask for medical tests by
``neutral'' physicians if their client was judged by government
physicians as fit to travel, but neither San Francisco lawyer John
Bartko nor Washington attorney Richard Hibey returned phone calls
Tuesday.
   Charles LaBella, assistant U.S. attorney in New York, was quoted
by the Honolulu Star-Bulletin as saying he spoke to Hibey about the
examination results. However, he refused to release the results of
the exam, which was conducted Oct. 31 at Tripler Army Medical Center
here.
   LaBella told The Associated Press the results would not be made
public before Monday's hearing.
   ``There's only one copy and it's in my hands,'' he said.
   At the time of the physical, aides said Marcos was examined for
about three hours by a team of doctors led by Weld, a cardiologist
at New York's Columbia Presbyterian Hospital.
</TEXT>
