<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Politics     11-29 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Likud and Labor Move Closer to Coalition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's conservative
Likud bloc and the rival Labor Party moved closer to coalition on
Tuesday and Orthodox religious parties threatened to withdraw
support for Likud.
   Shamir, who offered Labor two of the four most important Cabinet
ministries if it joins the government as a junior partner, said he
would finish forming a government in a few days.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin of Labor urged his center-left
party to join a government led by Shamir in order to block Orthodox
demands for religious legislation opposed by Jews abroad.
   Religious parties want a new ``Who Is a Jew'' law that would
accept only conversions to Judaism performed by Orthodox rabbis. The
demand has angered American Jews, most of whom belong to the Reform
or Conservative movements.
   Labor and Likud have been equal partners in a ``national unity''
coalition since the inconclusive election of July 1984. In the Nov.
1 election, Likud won 40 of the 120 Parliament seats and Labor 39.
Right-wing religious parties won 18 seats.
   The ultra-Orthodox party Shas, which made participation in a
Likud government contingent on religious legislation and control of
two ministries, threatened to withdraw its support, party spokesman
Tzvi Yakobson said Tuesday.
   ``Shamir has to promise that we will receive two ministries even
in a broad-based government,'' he said. ``Otherwise we'll see
ourselves free from the agreement with Likud.''
   Israel radio said the threat came after a ``short and stormy''
meeting between Shamir and Rabbi Yitzhak Peretz, the Shas leader, in
which Shamir refused the demands.
   The Council of Torah Sages, spiritual leaders of Agudat Israel,
another Orthodox party, met to discuss the coalition developments
and media reports said one possibility raised was a switch of
support to Labor.
   ``We're not chained in an agreement with Likud,'' Rabbi Abraham
Verdiger, the party leader, said on Israel army radio.
   Shamir could not form a right-wing coalition without Shas and
Agudat Israel, which together have ll seats in the Knesset, Israel's
parliament.
   Some in Likud urged Shamir to accept the Orthodox demand. Cabinet
minister Ariel Sharon, a rival of Shamir's who fears being bypassed
if a deal is struck with Labor, called the law a national necessity.
   Sharon wants to be defense minister, which is one of the senior
posts offered to Labor and probably would be kept by Rabin.
   The other presumably would be the Foreign Ministry held by Shimon
Peres, the Labor Party leader. Peres was prime minister and Shamir
foreign minister in the first two years of the ``national unity''
coalition.
</TEXT>
