<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CustodyBattle     11-29 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Custody Battle,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kids Whose Mother Chose Jail Will Go To Foster Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EXETER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ruled Tuesday that two children
should be placed in a foster home rather than with their mother, who
went to jail last year claiming she was hiding them from an abusive
father.
   Rockingham County Superior Court Judge Kenneth McHugh ruled that
the father, Mark Russell Murabito, should have joint custody of the
children with his ex-wife, Jesse Murabito. Previously, Mrs. Murabito
had custody, and her ex-husband had visitation rights.
   Both mother and children have been missing since Murabito, 34, of
Derry, was acquitted earlier this month of a charge of sexual
assault of his daughter, now 5{ years old. After the verdict, he
said he would seek custody of the girl and her 4-year-old brother.
   He also obtained a court order barring Mrs. Murabito from taking
the children out of the state or letting them live with anyone else.
   Mrs. Murabito, 40, of Belmont, went to jail for a week in
February 1987 rather than tell a judge where she hid the children
from their father.
   But she apparently never was served the court order later
obtained by the father, and she and the children have been missing
since the verdict. Through several media interviews, she has said
she is living with a family out of the state in a network that
protects alleged victims of sexual abuse.
   McHugh said Tuesday that Mrs. Murabito, even though she was not
served with the papers, was in enough contact through the media to
know she should not have left New Hampshire. Also, he said, in this
type of case, such an order does not have to be hand-delivered but
can be mailed, which is what the court did.
   McHugh said Mrs. Murabito is violating a visitation agreement she
had with her husband. He also said though he gave them joint
custody, it would be in the children's best interest to stay in a
foster home.
   Murabito initially had asked for joint custody with the state,
and wanted the children to be placed in a foster home.
   Through his lawyer, Murabito said his children have been
brainwashed by their mother and that it would be some time before
they learned to trust him again. He eventually wants full custody,
he said.
   State guardian Neil Reardon said Mrs. Murabito exercised poor
judgment by going into hiding because it is harmful to the
children's mental health.
</TEXT>
