<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 2024EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Archaeology     11-29 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Archaeology,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Archaeologists Uncover Ancient Port</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL HIRSCHHORN_</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAIFA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archaeologists have uncovered a Bronze Age
port on the Israeli coast with a warehouse stocked with raisins,
peas and olives dating to about 1,200 years before Christ, the
director of the excavation said.
   Professor Michal Artzy of the University of Haifa said in an
interview that the site uncovered at Tel Nami, 12 miles south of the
modern port city of Haifa, could be the oldest man-made port ever
found.
   ``In that period, seafarers tended to hug the coast, and they
used to come into port once every two days for food, so you needed
ports along the shore at set stretches,'' she said. ``There is
little reason for this site to exist, except as a port.''
   Researchers found evidence a channel was cut between the
Mediterranean and a river to form the port, Ms. Artzy said. She said
the port appeared to date to at least 2000 B.C., but further
research was needed to confirm the date.
   Objects uncovered in excavations begun last year include gold and
silver jewelry, bronze sculptures and pottery from ancient
civilizations, Ms. Artzy said.
   Ms. Artzy, who also serves on the staff of the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst, was assisted on the dig last summmer by
students from Amherst and from Texas A and M at College Station and
Cornell University in Ithaca, N.Y.
   Foodstuffs found in a warehouse were well preserved because a
fire in about 1200 B.C. apparently caused a roof to collapse,
blocking oxygen from reaching the food and damaging it, she said.
   ``We have whole examples of seeds and raisins, like your mother
used to give you when you were a kid,'' Ms. Artzy said.
   The site apparently was abandoned after the fire and never
resettled.
   She said artifacts found at the site indicated local residents
were very wealthy and that the port was an international trading
center.
   ``These were sea people with a lot of wealth,'' Ms. Artzy said.
She added: ``Whether it was from piracy or this is simply a rich
port, we don't know.''
   The pottery came Egypt, Cyprus, the ancient Greek states of Troy
and Mycenae, and elsewhere, she said.
   She displayed other items that were found, including gold rings
and earrings, a child's gold necklace, silver rings and a
hand-crafted Egyptian ring.
   So many bronze items were found that archaeologists believe a
bronze workshop may have existed at the site.
   Items include one bronze stand for incense burning that is
decorated with pomegranates and another with the figure of a woman.
   ``These are especially valuable because they are unusually well
preserved,'' she said. ``There was obviously a cult aspect to this,
the woman's body and the pomegranate, perhaps a fertility cult.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881129-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 2027EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Hart-FEC     11-29 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hart-FEC,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hart Campaign Agrees to Pay Fine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Gary Hart's 1984 presidential
campaign, still trying to clear up its debt-ridden books, must pay a
$12,000 penalty for violations cited in an agreement with the
Federal Election Commission.
   The campaign agreed to pay the civil penalty for violations that
included Hart's use of his personal credit card for campaign
expenses beyond the $50,000 the law says a candidate may contribute
to his campaign.
   In a separate penalty, the FEC cited a violation by the media
firm, Semper-Moser Associates, which agreed to pay $5,000 for
improperly advancing the Hart campaign more than $100,000 worth of
credit.
   Although the firm expected to be paid back the money, and
ironically ended up going to federal court to get $106,000 in back
payment, the credit arrangement with the campaign was illegal
because it was not ``in the ordinary course of business,'' according
to the settlement statement recently made public by the FEC.
   Election law requires that companies conduct relations with
political campaigns in the same manner that they would with any
other entity, to ensure that no special treatment is accorded the
campaigns.
   By agreeing to provide time buys and media services for Hart's TV
commercials on credit, which was not a customary practice,
Semper-Moser was making a corporate contribution, the FEC found.
Corporate donations are banned in federal elections.
   The debts relate to Hart's first race for the presidency. The
former senator from Colorado also entered the 1988 Democratic
primary race, dogged by the debts of his attempt four years earlier.
   While the 1988 campaign ended up solvent, the 1984 effort still
owes more than $1 million to creditors, according to the latest
report on file with the FEC.
   The FEC found that Hart improperly used his personal credit card
for more than $20,000 worth of expenditures above the $50,000
contribution limit he was allowed. While there was an understanding
that the campaign would pay the bills promptly, the payments were
made an average 266 days late, the FEC said.
   Hart's campaign claimed he was unaware of the tardiness and that
all the bills eventually were paid. But the FEC faulted the campaign
for failure to pay in a reasonable time.
   In addition, Hart's campaign acknowledged receiving contributions
from 49 individuals whose donations exceeded the $1,000 per-person
limit imposed by election law. The excess contributions totaled
$19,606, and the improper donations were ultimately refunded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
