<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-29 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Freezing in Florida; Snow in Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Frost and freezing temperatures reached as far south as Florida
on Tuesday, while snow fell over Minnesota, Iowa, Wisconsin and
Nebraska.
   Tallahassee, Fla., reached a low of 27 degrees. The cold spot in
Alabama was Pinson, where the temperature hit 23 degrees and
remained below freezing for 12 hours.
   Three to seven inches of snow fell in the morning in Iowa. Two
inches fell at Adams, La Crosse and Waushara, Wis., and Fairmont,
Rochester and Worthing, Minn. Advisories for snow were posted in
Minnesota, Iowa and Wisconsin.
   Up to 10 inches of snow were reported near Jay Peak, Vt., and the
high country of Colorado received between 4 and 8 inches since
Monday.
   Snowfall during the 6 hours ending at 1 p.m. EST included 3
inches at Mason City, Iowa, 2 inches at Madison, Wis., and 1 ne inch
at Omaha, Neb.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 18
degrees at Warroad, Minn., to 79 degrees at McAllen, Texas. The
nation's low Tuesday morning was 2 degrees below zero at Gunnison,
Colo.
   The forecast Wednesday was for snow from New England across
Pennsylvania and the lower Great Lakes; rain from Mississippi across
Alabama and the Florida Panhandle, and strong winds over southern
Texas and the northern Rockies.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 20s over northern Maine,
upper Michigan, Minnesota and eastern North Dakota; in the 30s and
40s over the remainder of New England, the Ohio Valley, the rest of
the Great Lakes and much of the Plains and the West; the 70s in
southern California, the desert Southwest and much of Florida, and
in the 50s and 60s over much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
