<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TitanLaunchPad     11-29 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Titan Launch Pad,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Readies Launch Pad For New Titan 4 Rocket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANDENBERG AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force is
spending $90 million to rebuild a launch pad for its new Titan 4
rockets, which will take secret military payloads into space, an
official said.
   Space Launch Complex-4 East has been used for Titan 34D launches
since 1982 and was rebuilt after one exploded in April 1986.
   The Titan 4 will carry payloads previously intended for the space
shuttle. Vandenberg's shuttle pad was dismantled in the aftermath of
the Challenger disaster.
   The 1986 explosion of the Titan 34D destroyed what was reportedly
a spy satellite and put the launch pad and one close by out of
commission for more than a year.
   The Air Force spent $50 million to rebuild the two pads so it
could continue launching the Titan 34Ds, said Col. John E. Angell,
who is in charge of Air Force space launches from Vandenberg.
   The launch pads were further rebuilt to handle the Titan 4
launches, he said.
   The first Titan 4 launched at Vandenberg likely will carry a $1
billion KH-12 spy satellite, said John Pike, a space policy expert
with the Federation of American Scientists.
   The reconnaissance satellite is capable of taking sharp
photographs of the Earth's surface through clouds, he said.
</TEXT>
