<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Tornadoes 1stLd-Writethru a0706 11-29 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tornadoes, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0706,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After Devastating Losses, Twister Victims Pick Up Pieces Of Homes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with statewide damage estimate
of
$100 million, picking up 7th graf pvs, `The dead...'. SUBS last 3
grafs, bgng `Police restricted...', with 5 grafs to UPDATE total of
looting arrests, further detail on request for disaster aid.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOBBS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The roar of chain saws and the smell of pine
from shattered trees permeated the air Tuesday as residents began
putting their lives back together and cleaning up from an estimated
$100 million in tornado damage.
   ``All my damage is minor compared to some of these people,'' said
Jeff Johnston as he and his wife, Helen, began cleanup and repairs.
Their house had broken windows and a piece of log embedded in the
wall; a tool shed was destroyed.
   The Johnstons' next-door neighbors were worse off _ the side of
their house was torn off. ``They'll have to move,'' Johnston said.
``This whole neighborhood is going to change a lot.''
   Four people died, 157 were injured and about 850 were left
homeless as the tornadoes tossed cars, houses and trees like
playthings along a 200-mile stretch of eastern North Carolina early
Monday.
   It was the first time since the state began keeping records in
1916 that tornadoes caused deaths in November, according to the
National Climatic Data Center in Asheville.
   Damage was estimated at $100 million statewide, according to the
state public safety department. Raleigh alone suffered $75 million
in damage, the city manager's office said.
   Teams from the Small Business Administration and Federal
Emergency Management Agency fanned out Tuesday to calculate damage
in all nine affected counties and determine what areas would be
eligible for federal disaster aid.
   The dead were 12-year-old Edwin ``Pete'' Fulghum and 9-year-old
Janet Barnes, both of Raleigh; and a Nash County couple, Lee Roy and
Mary Alston, who died in each other's arms when the storm hit their
mobile home.
   The Red Cross and other relief agencies said they were swamped
with offers of help.
   ``It renews your faith in humanity,'' said Helen Sibley, nurse
coordinator for the local Red Cross chapter.
   More than 300 families opened their homes to those affected by
the storm, she said, leaving only 17 people in a Wake County shelter.
   ``That's why there are not more people in the shelter,'' she
said. ``People in the city don't think other people care much about
them, but when something like this happens, we come together.''
   Businesses, individuals and churches donated food and other
supplies. A table in the school cafeteria was piled with sandwiches,
fruit, snacks, candy and desserts.
   In Raleigh, police restricted access to damaged areas, said
spokeswoman Jade Jurek. Fourteen people have been charged with
looting since the tornadoes struck, according to a Wake County
magistrate. Six Raleigh residents, including four juveniles, were
charged Monday with looting from a K mart that was flattened by the
storm.
   The state public safety department said Tuesday that 520 homes
were destroyed and more than 1,200 were damaged. Forty-one
businesses were either destroyed or damaged.
   Gov. Jim Martin asked the federal officials to declare Wake
County a disaster area, and the surveys of other counties will help
determine whether any other areas might also be eligible for
disaster aid or reduced-cost Small Business Administration loans.
   Al Warlick, a spokesman for the North Carolina Department of
Crime Control and Public Safety, said damage in Wake County is
probably extensive enough to warrant assistance from the Federal
Emergency Management Agency. A presidential disaster declaration is
required for FEMA aid to be released.
   ``We are going to send a delegation to Washington with these
letters (requesting disaster aid) to make sure that any question can
be answered face to face if necessary,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
