<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Demjanjuk 1stLd-Writethru   11-29 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Demjanjuk, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0646,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demjanjuk Attorney Dies in Plunge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to recast; INSERTS 1 graf after 7th pvs,
`Demjanjuk's son-in-law...' to UPDATE with judge calling meeting;
PICKS up 8th pvs: In a...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli attorney for convicted Nazi war
criminal John Demjanjuk died Tuesday after hurling himself from the
15th floor an office building, police said.
   Police ruled the death of Dov Eitan a suicide. A court official
said it could delay Demjanjuk's appeal of his conviction and death
sentence for Nazi war crimes, scheduled next week.
   Eitan, a 53-year-old former judge who joined Demjanjuk's defense
team in August, died after jumping from the 15th floor of the City
Towers office complex in downtown Jerusalem, police spokesman Rafi
Levy said.
   Eitan did not leave a note explaining his motives, but deputy
police spokesman Alex Lapidot said police were certain the death was
a suicide.
   ``There was no note at all, none. We are trying to determine what
was behind it,'' Lapidot said. ``But there was no criminal element.
It was suicide, 100 percent.''
   Israel radio said police found traces of polish from Eitan's
shoes on the sill of the window from which he jumped in the
15th-floor lobby of the Ayalon Hotel. Eitan entered the lobby
without being noticed by the receptionist, the only person there,
the radio said.
   Demjanjuk's son-in-law, Ed Nishnic, said the defense would
request a delay in the appeal, set to start Monday. Court spokesman
Yossi Hassin said the bench probably would grant at least a week's
delay.
   Supreme Court President Meir Shamgar invited the parties in the
case for a discussion in his chambers Wednesday morning. Shamgar is
to decide whether the appeal proceedings will start Monday or be
postponed until Demjanjuk appoints a new lawyer, Israel television
said.
   In a telephone interview from Cleveland, Nishnic said Eitan was
to have presented 60 percent of Demjanjuk's appeal and that other
lawyers would not be ready to argue the case Monday.
   ``We're very upset and concerned,'' Nishnic told The Associated
Press. ``We spoke to Eitan yesterday. He was extremely optimistic
and said he hopes to see us in Israel.''
   The Ukrainian-born Demjanjuk, 68, was convicted in April of
crimes against humanity and against the Jewish people. He was found
to have been ``Ivan the Terrible,'' a brutal guard who operated gas
chambers that killed 850,000 Jews at the Treblinka death camp in
Nazi-occupied Poland.
   Demjanjuk, who lived in the Cleveland suburb of Seven Hills
before being extradited to Israel in February 1986, claims he is a
victim of mistaken identity.
   Court spokesman Yassin said he saw Eitan on Monday and he
appeared ``very cheerful.''
   ``He was checking all the court arrangements, where the accused
would sit, where he would sit. It's all very strange,'' Hassin said.
   Demjanjuk's daughter Irene Nishnic, 27, said the family had left
a message for Demjanjuk at his maximum-security prison about Eitan's
death.
   ``I'm sure this is going to be a shock to my dad. He really got
along well with Eitan and had a lot of confidence in what he was
going to do for him,'' Mrs. Nishnic said, adding that Eitan had met
with Demjanjuk a week ago.
   An attorney who previously represented Demjanjuk, John Gill of
Cleveland, said he hoped police would investigate the death ``to see
if there was any foul play.
   ``I'm not suggesting there is or would be or was. But I do think
that would have to be explored,'' Gill said by telephone from
Cleveland.
   A defense witness, Swedish-born Anita Pritchard, tried to commit
suicide by slitting her wrists and swallowing tranquilizers on Aug.
21, 1987, after her testimony was discredited during the trial.
   Eitan served for 17 years as a Jerusalem district court judge
before retiring in 1983. His joining the defense was widely viewed
in Israel as adding prestige to the team.
   He is survived by his wife, who lives in Jerusalem, and two
children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
