<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bomb-Animals     11-29 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bomb-Animals,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Animal Rights Activist Pleads Innocent In Bomb Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An animal rights activist accused of
planting a bomb at a company that experiments on live dogs pleaded
innocent Tuesday to charges of attempted murder, manufacturing a
bomb and possession of explosives.
   ``Definitely not guilty,'' Fran Stephanie Trutt, 33, said during
a brief appearance in Stamford Superior Court. Judge Martin Nigro
then denied a motion to lower her bond from $500,000 to $60,000, and
she remained in custody.
   Animals rights groups have disavowed any connection to Trutt, who
was arrested on Nov. 11 near the headquarters of U.S. Surgical Corp.
in Norwalk.
   Police said she placed a radio-controlled pipe bomb packed with
roofing nails in bushes near the vacant parking space of company
chairman Leon Hirsch. Three more bombs were discovered in her New
York City apartment after her arrest.
   Trutt has said she didn't intend to kill anyone, but wanted to
scare the company into ending its practice of using live dogs to
demonstrate its surgical staples.
</TEXT>
