<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BishopJailed     11-29 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishop Jailed,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jailed Bishop Released For Role In Abortion Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POCOPSON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic bishop, two pastors and
four other activists were released Tuesday after spending a day in
prison for an illegal protest at an abortion clinic last July.
   Auxiliary Bishop Austin Vaughan of Newburgh, N.Y., was believed
to be the highest-ranking church official to go to prison in the
United States for an abortion protest, and drew a letter of praise
from Cardinal John O'Connor, said Joe Zwilling, spokesman for the
archdiocese of New York.
   Vaughan and the other activists left Chester County Prison about
10:15 a.m. Tuesday, said Warden Thomas G. Frame. They entered the
prison at noon Monday to serve a two-day sentence.
   Frame said the period counted for two days under the terms of the
sentence and the rules for computing time served in prison.
   The four men and three women were among 591 people arrested July
5 at the Women's Suburban Clinic in Paoli, a suburb of Philadelphia,
after they blocked entrances in defiance of two court orders. They
were the first of more than 400 people scheduled to go to prison.
   District Justice Robert Mull found all the defendants guilty of
defiant trespass for the July protest and fined them $10 plus $50.50
in court costs. Those who refused to pay on grounds of conscience
were sentenced to two days in prison.
   Vaughan and the other protesters were held in regular cells,
Frame said.
   A group of supporters held an hourlong prayer vigil outside the
prison Monday night, said Michael McMonagle, a spokesman for the
Pro-Life Coalition of Southeast Pennsylvania.
   ``His (Vaughan's) willingness to undergo imprisonment, even for
this short a time, provides a tremendous boost for our efforts,''
McMonagle said.
   Vaughan's stand also was praised by O'Connor, archbishop of New
York, in a letter Sunday to the bishop.
   ``What you do today you do for all of us who want with all our
hearts to do the same but are not free to do so at present,''
O'Connor said, telling Vaughan his example ``will give courage to
thousands of other mothers to choose life, however difficult the
choice.''
   Besides Vaughan, those released after serving the two-day
sentence were Joyce Starrs of Parkesburg; Barbara Willsher of
Reading; the Rev. Richard Doron, pastor of the non-denominational
Church of the New Covenant in Marlton, N.J.; Priscilla Gossens of
Beechwood, N.J.; the Rev. Peter Byrne of North Tarrytown, N.Y.; and
Allen Billington of Glassboro, N.J.
</TEXT>
