<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Election 2ndLd-Writethru   11-29 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Election, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0773,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules To Extradite American Wanted in California Killings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 6th, `Defense lawyer...' with Ng could
face death penalty in California, background on extradition
provision; pronouncer; PICKS up 7th pvs: Ng faces possible ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ruled Tuesday that Charles Ng
should be extradited to the United States to stand trial for a
string of sex murders in California.
   Justice Marguerite Trussler of Alberta Court of Queen's Bench
decided that the former U.S. Marine, born in Hong Kong, should be
extradited on 19 of the 25 offenses he is charged with in
California. She said she would issue a warrant that would keep Ng in
prison in Canada until he is surrendered to U.S. authorities.
   Charges of murder, kidnapping and burglary have been filed
against Ng in California. He is accused in the murders of 12 people.
   Eleven of the deaths of men, women and children involved grisly
sex slayings at a rural cabin in Calaveras County, 120 miles east of
San Francisco. The 12th involved the death of a San Francisco disc
jockey.
   Ng could face the gas chamber if convicted.
   Defense lawyer Don MacLeod said he will appeal Judge Trussler's
ruling. MacLeod said earlier arguments could take the case all the
way to the Supreme Court of Canada, which could take up to five
years.
   Ng, whose name is pronounced Ing, faces possible execution in
California. His lawyers are seeking to invoke a provision in the
Canada-U.S. extradition treaty that says extradition may be refused
unless the requesting state guarantees the fugitive will not be
executed if convicted. Canada does not have the dealth penalty.
   Ng, who was educated in British private schools, is serving a
4{-year sentence at a maximum-security federal penitentiary in
Prince Albert, Saskatchewan, for shooting a security guard in the
hand in December 1985 during a botched shoplifting attempt at a
department store in Calgary.
   Judge Trussler told a hushed courtroom she was satisfied, on
evidence filed during a six-week extradition hearing, ``that the
offenses charged in the state of California are extraditable with
one exception.''
   The exception was a charge of accessory to murder.
   The judge dismissed five other charges of kidnapping and
conspiracy to kidnap because no evidence was shown of transportation
of the three people involved, as required under Canadian law.
   She ruled evidence from Ng's alleged partner in the crimes,
Leonard Lake, should be admissible.
   Ng came to Canada after Lake was picked up for shoplifting in San
Francisco and committed suicide. Lake later was linked to the deaths
or disappearances of 22 people. That investigation led to the
charges against Ng.
   ``I am satisfied beyond a reasonable doubt based on all the
evidence ... that there was a general conspiracy that related to
weapons, money and sexual gratification,'' she held.
</TEXT>
