<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NobilityDeaths     11-29 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nobility Deaths,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Needle Marks Found On Royal Couple</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities probing the suicide of Prince
Ludwig Rudolf of Hanover, the 33-year-old great-grandson of
Germany's last emperor, and the drug overdose of his wife found
puncture wounds on their arms and syringes in their luxurious villa,
sources said Tuesday.
   Ludwig Rudolf apparently drove to a secluded woods and shot
himself in the head Sunday shortly after his wife, Princess
Isabelle, 26, overdosed on cocaine.
   Isabelle was found dead by her husband in their bedroom at the
posh Koenigin-Villa, a family property at Gmunden, a lakeside resort
in Upper Austria's Salzkammergut lake district.
   Police sources in Gmunden and in Linz, the capital of Upper
Austria province, said Tuesday that a preliminary autopsy showed the
Austrian-born woman died of heart and lung edema after consuming
cocaine.
   Ludwig Rudolf's great-grandfather was Kaiser Wilhelm II.
   A spokesman for Upper Austria security police, who spoke on the
condition of not being identified, told The Associated Press
syringes apparently used to inject drugs and a small amount of an
unspecified ``powder'' were found near the body of the princess.
   The Austria Press Agency, quoting a source in the public
prosecutor's office, said the powder was cocaine.
   The public prosecutor's office at Wels, Upper Austria, said
investigators found punctures on the arms of the dead prince and
princess, suggesting narcotics use.
   The result of an official post mortem was expected later this
week. Police said the case also is under court investigation, but
declined further details.
   Ludwig Rudolf, a distant relative of the British, Greek and
Spanish royal families, was found dead near a small lake at Almtal,
a wooded area about 20 miles from Gmunden, police said. His hunting
rifle was beside him, police said.
   The couple, married last year, left an 8-month-old son, Prince
Otto, Austrian newspapers said.
   Ludwig Rudolf, a descendant of the ancient Guelph dynasty that
includes some of Europe's top aristocracy, and his wife dined Sunday
night with members of a little-known West German pop group, police
said.
   The princess retired early and was found dead by her husband at
2:45 a.m. He called the Red Cross and told them that she had
``probably taken cocaine,'' a police spokesman said Tuesday.
   Ludwig Rudolf, a distant relative of Queen Elizabeth II, also
called his brother Ernst August in London, reportedly telling him of
his suicide plan and asking him to take care of his son.
   He then hung up abruptly, Austrian newspapers said.
   After making the telephone calls, the prince took his hunting
rifle and drove away from the villa, police said. His body was found
about four hours later.
   The couple belonged to the European jet set, moving in the world
of rock music and fashion. The prince spent many years in London,
and the princess attended a fashionable school in Kent, southeast
England, before training as a secretary in England.
   The prince was the middle son of three sons of Prince Ernst
August of Hanover and the grandson of Emperor Wilhelm II's daughter
Viktoria Luise of Brunswick-Luneburg.
</TEXT>
