<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Senate 1stLd-Writethru a0744 11-29 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Senate, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0744,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Asks GOP Senators To Give Bush Friendship, Support</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs to UPDATE with speech delivered; INSERTS 2
grafs after 5th graf pvs, bgng: ``Dole won ...'' to add color.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, expressing regret that the
Republican Party was unable to regain control of the Senate, asked
its GOP members on Tuesday to give George Bush ``the same
friendship, support and solidarity that you gave me.''
   Reagan's remarks came at a farewell dinner attended by Bush, Vice
President-elect Dan Quayle, GOP senators and their spouses.
   The president also lavished praise on Bush's onetime political
adversary, Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, as a ``good friend'' and
a man who ``has never let me down.''
   President-elect Bush and the Kansas senator met for lunch on
Monday, pledging to put their past political rivalry behind them and
promising to work together on the budget deficit and other problems.
   Dole won the leadoff Iowa caucuses in the race for the GOP
presidential nomination, but Bush recaptured the momentum by winning
New Hampshire and went on to score a near sweep of the 17 state
Super Tuesday primaries.
   After the dinner in the Great Hall of the Library of Congress,
Reagan was presented with a gift from the senators _ a large ``weed
whacker'' for his ranch in Santa Barbara, Calif.
   ``It's a high-tech, top secret device that can be used to clear
out weeds, brush, trees, rattlesnakes, desperadoes and Democrats,''
quipped Dole, who presented the device to Reagan.
   In his remarks, Reagan portrayed Dole as a pillar of the party.
   ``I want to say a special thank you to a good friend, Bob Dole,
as a man I have come to know so well,'' Reagan said, adding, ``He is
a man so widely respected and admired that even senators on the
other side of the aisle routinely steal his jokes.''
   Reagan went on to portray the newly elected Republican team as
men who will work to continue his conservative legacy.
   ``As I prepare to return to California, nothing has meant so much
to me as the knowledge that Bob Dole and George Bush and Dan Quayle,
each one of you, and our whole Republican team, will be working
together for the values we share and the future that stands before
us,'' Reagan said.
   ``My friends, we need have no regrets, we deserve to be proud,''
Reagan said, but he also added: ``I must say, I wish we could have
regained control of this body.''
   The president went on to predict that the Republican Party will
``win control of the Congress, the same way we keep winning the
White House.
   ``Sooner or later, the other party is going to have to take the
hint and put themselves out of their misery,'' Reagan said.
   Reagan, looking back on his nearly completed eight-year term and
the 1980 election that swept the Senate into Republican hands, said
of his party, ``We have succeeded beyond anyone's expectations.''
   The president bid adieu to those turned out of office, and asked
those remaining in the new Senate, which will contain 55 Democrats
and 45 Republicans, ``I know that you will continue to do honor to
America and that you will give George Bush the same friendship,
support and solidarity that you gave me.''
</TEXT>
