<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SniperAttack 1stLd-Writethru a0792 11-29 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sniper Attack, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0792,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Teen-agers Arrested in Fatal Sniper Attack on Rio Grande
Rafters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th graf, `The snipers...' to UPDATE
with injured woman's reaction; picks up 8th graf pvs, ``We have...';
Pineda cq as 2nd reference.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MARFA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two teen-agers were arrested Tuesday and
charged with murder in a sniper attack on three Rio Grande
white-water rafters that left one man dead, and authorities said the
boys apparently opened fire on a whim.
   Eduardo Pineda Rodriguez, 17, was arrested Tuesday morning at his
parents' home east of the Big Bend village of Redford, said Presidio
County Sheriff Rick Thompson. The 16-year-old, whose name was being
withheld, was arrested by Chihuahua state judicial police in
Ojinaga, Mexico, Thompson said.
   Authorities were still seeking two other people in the shootings.
   Both teen-agers were charged with murder in the Nov. 19 death of
Michael Heffley, 40, of Eastland. Pineda, a Mexican citizen who is a
resident alien of the United States, also was charged with assault
in the non-fatal shootings of Heffley's wife, Jamie, and river guide
Jim Burr.
   The group was rafting down the Rio Grande about 20 miles east of
Redford when shots were fired on them from a 300-foot-high canyon
rim on the Mexican side of the river.
   Burr suffered a gunshot to the right thigh and Ms. Heffley was
shot in the left shoulder and left side. Her husband was shot
fatally in the back as he shielded her and tried to drag her to
safety.
   The snipers stalked them from the canyon rim as they abandoned
their bullet-riddled raft and scrambled down the river bank.
   Mrs. Heffley, 32, told The Associated Press that her assailants
should be executed for the attack.
   ``I'm glad about the news but I think there are two more out
there,'' Mrs. Heffley said. ``From what I understand, I remember
that I had seen four.
   ``I'm glad that they are being caught and I think this incident
should be made a public example,'' she said. ``I think they should
be executed, because if they are not, relations will never get
better across the border. Nobody should have to go through this kind
of torture.''
   ``We have no motive for the shootings,'' Thompson said, adding
that both teen-agers gave statements implicating each other. ``They
saw them coming down the river and decided to shoot at them.''
   Thompson said police on both sides of the border, acting on a
tip, arrested the teen-agers about 8:30 a.m.
   ``It was just information that we had all received,'' Thompson
said, refusing to elaborate. ``We think the arrests of the other two
(suspects) will be in a reasonable length of time.''
</TEXT>
