<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-US     11-29 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-US,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Foreign Minister Uno Leaves For Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno left for Washington on
Wednesday for talks with President Reagan, President-elect George
Bush and other U.S. officials to promote good relations between the
two countries, Japanese officials said.
   Uno's trip is the first outside Japan by a Cabinet minister since
Emperor Hirohito fell seriously ill on Sept. 19, a Foreign Ministry
official said. The emperor remains ill.
   Uno will meet with Secretary of State George Shultz on Wednesday
to discuss international issues including Japanese-U.S. relations,
said a Japanese official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   On Thursday, Uno is to meet with Reagan and deliver a letter from
Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita expressing gratitude for the
president's strong interest in Asia and the Pacific region,
especially Japan, during his eight-year presidency, according to
news reports.
   During his three-day stay, Uno also is scheduled to meet
separately with U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter and
Secretary of State-designate James Baker, the official said.
   Uno later will proceed to Montreal, where he will attend
international trade talks held under the auspices of the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, an international trade body.
</TEXT>
