<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 2331EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BankRobbery     11-29 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Robbery,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Photographer Helps Police Nab Absent-Minded Robber</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT STERLING, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An absent-minded robber who left his
gun inside a bank during a hold-up and locked himself out of the
building was tracked by a newspaper photographer, who ordered him to
``stop or I'll shoot.''
   Photographer Bobby Warner of the Montgomery Times was near the
Montgomery-Traders branch bank and heard the robbery report on his
police scanner, Officer Joni Ward of the Mount Sterling Police
Department said Tuesday.
   Warner followed the robbery suspect, Robert Robinson of Carlisle,
and pointed out the man's location when she and a deputy sheriff
arrived after the Monday morning robbery in this eastern Kentucky
town, Ward said.
   The photographer said he followed the man to prevent his escape
but also had wanted to find a way to coax him to turn around for a
picture.
   ``I stood behind a telephone pole and I said, `Stop or I'll
shoot,''' Warner said. ``And I did shoot him, I shot his picture.''
   Warner said the man did not stop but continued running up a hill.
When Ms. Ward arrived, Warner said he yelled and pointed in the
direction of Robinson, then took photographs as police made the
arrest.
   Robinson, 34, was charged with first-degree armed robbery. He was
held in lieu of a $25,000 full cash bond Tuesday in the Montgomery
County Regional Jail.
   The robber had forced his way into the bank shortly before it
opened by holding a woman employee at gunpoint near the back door,
Ms. Ward said. He forced another female employee to unlock the vault
and had both workers fill a duffel bag with money.
   Afterward, he made them lie on the floor while he tied their
ankles together with duct tape, Ms. Ward said. The robber also took
the car keys of one of the women.
   ``While he was tying them up, he laid his gun on a pop machine.
His mistake _ he left it laying there'' when he went outside to put
the money in the woman's car. ``He forgot that the (bank) door would
lock behind him, and he couldn't get back inside.''
   By then, a third employee was arriving at the bank, and the
suspect tried to get that employee to let him back inside, but he
refused.
   ``He told him that he had robbed the bank. ... He went to the
woman's car and got the money out of it, and he started walking
off,'' Ms. Ward said. The suspect was arrested soon afterward.
   Warner said a picture he shot of the arrest ran on the weekly
newspaper's front page this week and more photos appeared inside.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
