<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 2334EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   11-29 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0638,0708</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rift Among Palestinian Factions Over Strike Observance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS two grafs with settlers launching highway patrols</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers in the occupied lands wounded
20 Palestinians Tuesday, hospital officials said, and merchants were
caught between one faction demanding a strike and another insisting
they stay open.
   Among the wounded were a 10-year-old boy shot in the leg and a
14-year-old hit in the chest, the Arab hospital officials said.
   More than 7,000 Palestinians have been wounded in a year of
rebellion against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip. At least 316 have been killed and 11 Israelis have been slain.
   Gangs of young Islamic extremists and PLO activists armed with
knives and clubs marched through Bethlehem in the West Bank on
Tuesday, shouting threats at each other and issuing conflicting
orders.
   Members of Hamas (Zeal) sprayed a warning to merchants on walls
in Islamic green: ``Today is a strike day. Be sure you observe it.''
   Followers of the Palestine Liberation Organization kicked on
closed doors, shouting to store owners that they would be protected
from Hamas if they opened.
   The strike was widely observed in the West Bank and Gaza. Hebron,
a predominantly fundamentalist West Bank town, was completely shut
down.
   Army commanders strengthened patrols and imposed curfews on more
than two dozen refugee camps, towns and villages. At least 370,000
of the 1.5 Palestinians in the territories were confined to their
homes.
   At the root of Tuesday's factional conflict was a disagreement
between Hamas and Yasser Arafat's Fatah faction of the PLO over the
proclamation Nov. 15 of an independent Palestinian state.
   The declaration is based on a 1947 U.N. partition plan that
called for both Arab and a Jewish states in Palestine.
   Hamas rejected it and called a protest strike for Tuesday, the
41st anniversary of the partition plan. The Unified National
Leadership of the Uprising, backed by the PLO, did not call for a
strike.
   In a recent leaflet, Hamas leaders said: ``How is it possible to
think that Jews want a just peace? The Jew is a Jew, regardless of
the party he belongs to.''
   Three masked Hamas followers in Jericho, a West Bank town,
flagged down Arab-run buses en route to Jerusalem and forced them to
turn back, Arab witnesses reported. The young men entered the buses
and shouted at the drivers: ``Go back! Go back!''
   Stores were closed in Ramallah, north of Jerusalem.
   One shopkeeper told reporters other merchants complied after
being threatened by Hamas loyalists. An elderly man later advised
him: ``Don't tell these things to outsiders.''
   Another group urging a strike Tuesday was the pro-Syrian Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine, which also rejected the
independence declaration.
   Palestinian leaders expressed concern about the growing rift and
said it might harm the uprising in the territories Israel captured
from Jordan and Egypt in 1967.
   ``We know about the risk of this confrontation. We are working to
stop it,'' said Sufian Khatib, a Palestinian surgeon whose views
have been identified with those of the Popular Front.
   Khatib also said the coinciding strike calls did not indicate a
new alliance between fundamentalists and hardline PLO factions
opposed to even implicit recognition of Israel.
   ``We have some points in common but we are not together in the
field,'' he told The Associated Press.
   Another Palestinian official said the independence declaration by
the Palestine National Council, which acts as the PLO legislature,
had wide support in the occupied lands.
   ``A majority of the Palestinian people are behind the PNC,'' said
Mahdi Abdul-Hadi, head of the Palestinian Academic Society for the
Study of International Affairs.
   Armed Jewish settlers in the northern West Bank launched highway
patrols on Tuesday to protect Israeli drivers from being stoned by
Palestinians. Three cars patrolled the roads, each bearing a large
Israeli flag, said organizer Yacov Eshel.
   He said soldiers stopped one car at an army checkpoint near the
Palestinian town of Qalqiliya and told the driver he could not enter
unless he removed the flag. The driver refused, and was turned back.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
