<DOCNO> AP881129-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 2318EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru   11-29 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0730,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deputy Foreign Minister: Iran Will Work To Free Foreign Hostages</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 3 grafs SUB for 7th graf pvs, Genscher has ..., UPDATING with
remark on possible resumption of ties with Washington. Picks up 8th
graf pvs, Genscher's good ... with minor editing to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DETLEF RUDEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government official indicated Tuesday that
Iran is linking efforts to free foreign hostages in Lebanon with the
fate of Iranians believed held there.
   ``There aren't just American hostages in Lebanon, but there also
are Iranian hostages, who are in the hands of Christian
militiamen,'' Mohammed Javad Larijani, Iran's deputy foreign
minister, said.
   He made the comment after meeting with West German Foreign
Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher, whose three-day visit to Tehran was
dominated by the hostage issue.
   Larijani was refering to three Iranians who disappeared with
their Lebanese driver in 1982 and were presumed kidnapped by
Christian Phalangist gunmen. The four are widely believed to have
died. No group claimed responsibility for their kidnapping.
   ``Western nations, especially the United States, have close ties
to (the Phalangists),'' Larijani told reporters. ``We want all
hostages to be free, the Iranians as well, and we will work as much
as we can so that they are freed.''
   He did not specify what actions Iran might take.
   In remarks quoted by the official Islamic Republic News Agency
and monitored in Cyprus, Larijani also did not rule out resuming
ties with the United States.
   ``If one day we were to resume ties with the U.S. such a
relationship would certainly be on the basis of mutual respect and
non-interference in each other's affairs,'' he was quoted as saying.
   Genscher has offered to act as mediator in gaining the release of
14 foreign hostages, including nine Americans, believed held in
Lebanon by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem extremists, West German
government sources in Bonn said.
   Genscher's good contacts with Tehran throughout the Iran-Iraq war
were seen as key factors in the release of two West German hostages
held in Lebanon.
   Before ending his visit on Tuesday, Genscher told reporters he
urged Iran's leaders to ``to use all possibilities toward
contributing to the release of all hostages in Lebanon.''
   During his stay, Genscher held talks with Larijani, President Ali
Khamenei, Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati and other Iranian
officials.
   Genscher said he raised the hostage issue in each of his
discussions.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
Tuesday that Genscher ``is not an emissary'' of the United States
and is not representing the U.S. government in the discussions in
Iran. ``He is not speaking in our behalf,'' the spokesman said.
   ``Obviously we're interested to hear whatever comes up in these
talks,'' Fitzwater said, adding that ``I'm not aware of any new
hope'' for release of the American hostages.
   Longest held of the 14 hostages is Terry Anderson, 41, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press, who was
kidnapped in Beirut on March 16, 1985.
   In addition, Peter Winkler, 32, a Swiss employee of the Red
Cross, was abducted by three unidentified gunmen Nov. 17 in Sidon,
25 miles south of Beirut. No group claimed responsibility.
   Earlier Tuesday, Genscher and Velayati signed a cultural
agreement designed to lead to the reopening of the
government-sponsored Goethe Institute in Tehran. The institute
provides information on German culture and language instruction.
   Genscher was accompanied to Iran by a 30-member delegation that
included West German industry leaders. One purpose of the visit was
to discuss ways to help Iran rebuild its war-ravaged economy.
   West Germany is one of Iran's most important trade partners.
   Iran and Iraq, who began fighting in September 1980, agreed to a
United Nations-sponsored truce in August and have been negotiating
for a lasting peace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
