<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0538</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC oil ministers have ended nearly two
weeks of tense discussions with a formal agreement to limit
production and pump prices back toward the cartel's benchmark of $18
per barrel.
   But before the day was out, one oil minister indicated Monday
that his new quota was not official, causing futures prices to back
off after a sharp runup.
   The accord, which ended the winter meeting of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries, set an output ceiling of 18.5 million
barrels a day for the 13 OPEC members, well under the 22.5 million
that analysts estimate the cartel currently is pumping.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major U.S. banks have boosted their prime lending
rates a half percentage point to 10.5 percent, the highest level
since mid-1985.
   The increase announced Monday will mean a jump in rates on a
variety of consumer loans pegged to the prime, including home-equity
loans. It also will raise borrowing costs for many companies that
rely on banks for financing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The imbalance between what America imports and
sells abroad narrowed to $28.53 billion in the July-September
quarter, a 5.4 percent decline, the government reports. It was the
third straight quarterly drop.
   Through the first nine months of the year, the deficit is running
at an annual rate of $125.2 billion, compared with last year's
record $160.3 billion deficit, the Commerce Department said Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. farm export volume hit a 6-year peak of
147.5 million metric tons in the year ended Sept. 30, with Japan
again the biggest customer, the Agriculture Department says.
   U.S. agricultural exports climbed to $35.2 billion this past
year, while imports of farm products rose to a record $21 billion,
the USDA said Monday.
   That left the United States with a net agricultural trade surplus
of $14.2 billion for fiscal 1988, compared with $7.22 billion a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and U.S. trade negotiators have agreed
to extend through 1990 an agreement calling for the Soviet Union to
buy at least 9 million metric tons of grain a year from the United
States.
   The 27-month extension signed Monday in Moscow revived a
five-year pact that expired Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal savings and loan regulators have
proposed an ``early intervention'' plan allowing the government to
take over a failing institution before it becomes insolvent.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which oversees the nation's
3,028 federally insured S&Ls, also proposed Monday regulations
requiring institutions with riskier commercial and stock investments
to hold more capital, or reserve funds, than institutions investing
mostly in residential mortgages, the traditional mainstay of the
thrift industry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Speculators have bid RJR Nabisco Inc.'s stock
higher on the hunch that fattened offers would emerge in the
unprecedented auction for the food-and-tobacco giant, which has
lured price tags as high as $26.8 billion.
   Monday's price rise came as a company-imposed deadline for a
second round of bids approached today for the biggest corporate
takeover ever.
</TEXT>
