<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed and trading in a narrow range
in Europe today. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign currency dealers said trading was light because of
expectations the U.S. Federal Reserve will raise interest rates.
Dealers said the market was also waiting for Friday's scheduled
release of U.S. unemployment statistics for November.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.15 yen to a closing 122.15 following reported Bank
of Japan intervention. Later, in London, it was quoted at 121.83 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.7333 West German marks, up from 1.7332; 1.4480
Swiss francs, down from 1.4515; 5.9200 French francs, down from
5.9225; 1.9552 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9547; 1,284.40 Italian
lire, down from 1,285.50; 1.1955 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1918.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8430, more expensive for
buyers than late Monday's $1.8385.
   Gold prices were lower in quiet trading. Bullion dealers said the
market was seeking new direction following the price and production
agreement by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries on
Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $422.50 a troy ounce,
down from $423.85 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $422.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $422.00, down from $423.25 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.29 to close at a bid $423.31.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.13 a troy ounce,
down from Monday's $6.16.
