<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     11-29 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Inches Up, Stocks Surge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose slightly against the Japanese yen
today, and share prices sharply rebounded on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 122.15 yen, up from Monday's close of 122.00
yen. The currency opened higher following its advance overnight in
New York, then gradually slid back. Sources said the Bank of Japan
bought dollars to stabilize the currency when it was about to fall
below the 122-yen mark in the early afternoon. The central bank does
not comment on its activities.
   Dealers attributed the dollar's rise in New York to the increase
Monday in the U.S. prime interest rate from 10 percent to 10.5
percent, and the agreement by the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries to reduce production.
   OPEC members meeting in Vienna agreed to a daily production quota
of 18.5 million barrels and a target price of $18 a barrel.
   The announcement triggered a $1-a-barrel increase in oil prices.
But Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said the agreement's effect on
exchange rates was mostly psychological and it would not immediately
affect the world economy.
   Mitsuhiko Kinugasa of Daiwa Bank said the dollar fell after its
initial jump because speculators in Tokyo had expected an increase
in the U.S. prime rate and its occurrence did not change market
sentiment for a weaker dollar.
   ``Many market players still tend to think they should get rid of
the dollar now,'' Kinugasa added.
   An exchange dealer with the Bank of Tokyo, speaking anonymously,
said other traders were awaiting the release of U.S. gross national
product figures for the July-September period, due later today, and
U.S. unemployment figures for November, expected on Thursday.
   Meanwhile, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average regained 334.98
points, or 1.2 percent, to return to 29,318.30. On Monday, the index
dropped 380.27 points, its largest one-day decline since Sept. 1.
   The index gained 79.53 points shortly after trading began Tuesday
and advanced further in the afternoon, boosted by the stabilized
currency market, dealers said.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at 1.1 billion shares
in active trading.
</TEXT>
