<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 0830EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DalkonShield     11-29 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dalkon Shield,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Removes Chairman And Two Trustees Of Dalkon Shield Fund</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has removed the chairman and
two trustees supervising the $2.4 billion trust for victims of the
Dalkon Shield birth control device after a complaint that they had
shown bad judgment resulting in inaction and delays.
   U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr., who is supervising the
bankruptcy proceeding of the A.H. Robins Co., on Monday ordered the
immediate removal of Barbara B. Blum of New York, the chairman of
the Dalkon Shield Claimants Trust; Gene Locks, a lawyer in
Philadelphia; and Ann Samani of Lexington, Ky., a former member of
the Dalkon Shield Claimants Committee.
   Merhige did not outline his reasons for removing the trustees in
his two-page order. But he noted that an opinion would be filed
today in Richmond, headquarters of A.H. Robins, manufacturer of the
Dalkon Shield.
   The complaint by claimaints in the case against Dalkon Shield
contended the trustees used poor judgement in voting to retain as
counsel the Washington firm of Cadwalader, Wickersham and Taft,
which represents the separate Dalkon Shield Claimants Committee.
   U.S. District Judge Albert V. Bryan Jr. disqualified the firm
from representing the trust.
   The complaint also accused the trustees of taking steps seen as
being confrontational toward Merhige's supervision of their work.
   The ousted trustees were among five appointed under A.H. Robins'
bankruptcy plan to set up a method for compensating victims of the
Dalkon Shield intrauterine device.
   Robins filed for protection under Chapter 11 of the Federal
Bankruptcy Code in 1985 after hundreds of women filed suit claiming
the birth control device had killed some women and injured scores of
others.
   Under the reorganization plan, Robins would be acquired by
American Home Products Corp. of New York and would put $2.3 billion
in cash into the trust. In September, lawyers representing more than
100 claimants asked for removal of the trustees, arguing that they
were inexperienced and had not moved quickly enough to set up a
claims center.
   The lawyers also charged thatMs. Samani's presence on the board
presented a conflict of interest.
   Ms. Samani said she was among the women injured by the Dalkon
Shield intrauterine device, manufactured in the early 1970s by A.H.
Robins. She withdrew her claim to serve as a trustee. Merhige's
order permits her to reinstate her claim.
   The remaining trustees, Washington lawyer Kenneth Feinberg and
University of Virginia law professor Stephen A. Saltzburg, will
nominate successors. The nominations are subject to approval by
Merhige.
   Michael Sheppard, director of the trust's claims resolution
facility, said the trust's bylaws will be amended to permit a quorum
of two trustees to conduct business.
   ``We expect no slowdown,'' Sheppard said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
