<1ST_LINE>r f PM-France-TransitStrike     11-29 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Transit Strike,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commuter Trains, Buses Disrupted; Army Ordered to Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strike-bound suburban commuters crowded into scarce
buses or drove their cars on jammed expressways today, while the
government ordered out army trucks to move stranded passengers.
   The strike called by the Communist-led General Confederation of
Labor halted all trains on two of the four regional express networks
and disrupted subway and bus routes.
   The first army vehicles were expected to arrive in the capital
late today with as many as 400 expected to be on hand for Wednesday
morning's rush hour, the Defense Ministry said.
   Transport Minister Michel Delebarre announced the military
intervention on national television Monday night and accused the
union of waging ``a sort of union guerrilla warfare of harassment.
This is not in the French union tradition.''
   Delebarre said strikers blocked buses in their terminals,
flattened tires and sabotaged engines. The transit agency's
management was being ordered to stop paying striking workers and to
start disciplinary proceedings against lawbreakers, he said.
   General Confederation of Labor Secretary-General Henri Krasucki
said on French radio today that the government was mistaken if it
planned to solve the labor dispute ``with police, troops or military
trucks.''
   At midday today, the Paris regional transit agency reported the
regional A and B lines halted, only 60 percent of buses operating
and service reduced by up to 25 percent on some subway lines.
   Premier Michel Rocard's Socialist government has been hit by
striking nurses, postal employees, government office workers and
other public service employees demanding wage increases that Rocard
says would be inflationary.
   ``The real motive of these strikes is political,'' the
conservative newspaper Le Figaro said in today's editorial. ``The
Communists are trying to exert unbearable pressure on the Socialists
with a view toward the municipal elections of next March.''
   The Communist share in recent French elections slipped to less
than 10 percent of the total vote. But the party appears to see a
chance to grab the role of the only authentic leftist force, as the
Socialists continue the economic policies of the conservatives who
controlled the government from 1986 until last May.
   Krasucki dismissed repeated suggestions that the strikes were
intended to increase Communist chances in next year's municipal
elections as ``completely stupid.''
   His union is demanding increased safety measures and
across-the-board pay increases of $170 a month. The transit
authority Sunday offered raises of $42.50 a month. A typical transit
worker earns a top-scale monthly wage of $1,400.
   The two regional express lines paralyzed since Monday usually
carry more than 600,000 of the roughly 10 million people who commute
to Paris by bus, train or car.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
