<HEAD>Man Successfully Appeals Age-Discrimination Suit Against
Westinghouse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Westinghouse Electric Co. employee
will get his day in court on an age-discrimination lawsuit against
the company under a ruling by a federal appeals court.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled Monday that the case
should have gone to trial and ordered the case back to U.S. District
Court in Pittsburgh, which had granted Westinghouse a summary
judgment in the suit by James White.
   White was fired in 1986 at age 51 from his engineering position
as part of a Westinghouse plan to reduce its staff by up to 10
percent, according to court records. Of the nine employees in
White's department, two were older than White.
   White had worked for Westinghouse for 29 years and nine months.
He contends Westinghouse chose him for termination because if he had
remained on the job three more months, he would have been eligible
for more retirement benefits.
   Westinghouse maintained that he was chosen because of low
performance ratings and because his position was the most expendable.
