<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Chrysler-Kenosha     11-29 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler-Kenosha,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dec. 23 Date Set For Stopping Kenosha Production</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. will end passenger car production
at its Kenosha, Wisc., plant on Dec. 23 putting about 5,300 people
out of work, a spokesman for the automaker says.
   Chrysler spokesman Lloyd Northard said Monday that the former
American Motors Corp. plant would retain a work force of about 1,200
people, including 200-250 salaried workers, in the engine operation
at Kenosha once the car assembly lines shut down.
   The Kenosha plant now has about 6,500 employees, including 600
salaried workers.
   ``After Dec. 23, Chrysler will stop building passenger cars in
Kenosha,'' Northard said.
   ``Obviously there will be people needed after Dec. 23 in the
L-body tear-down operation and workers will also be needed to
dismantle the M-body tooling.''
   The M-body production is being discontinued by Chrysler, while
the L-body production is being shifted to Chrysler's Jefferson
Avenue plant in Detroit.
   Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca had announced earlier this year
that auto production at Kenosha would stop by the end of this year.
   Ed Steagall, president of United Auto Workers Local 72 at
Kenosha, said he thinks Chrysler is making a serious mistake by
shutting down the Kenosha car production.
   ``The quality levels and the sales levels are there'' for both
the L-body and the M-body lines, he said.
   He said the union was preparing for the assembly shutdown. Some
workers will retire, some will relocate and some will return to
school, he said.
   ``It's going to be devastating and it's terrible'' that the
shutdown comes just before Christmas, he said.
   Chrysler initially said it would stop some Kenosha production by
July and the rest by September, but Iacocca later announced car
production would continue through December because of strong sales.
</TEXT>
