<DOCNO> AP881129-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 0955EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-AutoIncentives     11-29 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Incentives,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Inventories, Production Increases Mean New Incentives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN L. ADLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The math is simple: when too many new cars are
built and too few are sold, incentives result. Auto analysts say the
latest round will arrive in time for Christmas.
   ``We're going to have to have some type of programs,'' analyst
Joseph Phillippi of Shearson Lehman Hutton in New York said Monday.
``The companies would much rather give away part of the gross profit
than cut production.''
   Auto giant General Motors Corp. may have a 100-day backlog of
cars by the end of December, an inventory nearly 50 percent larger
than considered comfortable.
   ``If you just look at the recent reactions of the car companies
to inventory bulges, it's obvious they will do something,''
Phillippi said. ``Incentives of varying proportions and programs
have been part of the landscape for four years now.''
   Each of the Big Three have incentives in effect. Chrysler Corp.'s
incentives programs have no set expiration; many of Ford Motor Co.'s
programs are set to expire Dec. 5, while some GM programs expire
Wednesday.
   Ford, in the best shape of the Big Three as far as inventories
go, plans to build more cars in the first quarter of 1989 than it
announced two weeks ago. Its latest production schedule for the
first three months of 1989 shows 501,000 cars to be built compared
with 475,000 announced a few weeks ago.
   ``In the case of Ford, it is losing some sales because of a lack
of certain models, especially the Probe and the Continental,'' said
David Healy of Drexel Burham Lambert in New York. ``That's an up
side, but there's not very much good about this.''
   GM has begun trimming some first quarter production schedules,
Healy said.
   Whether the incentives will take the form of cash, interest rate
discounts or other, more exotic lures is a closely guarded industry
secret.
   ``They've got a bookshelf full of these programs, guys whose only
job it is to dream up new programs,'' Healy said. ``What they'll
basically do is what has worked best in the past for specific
models.''
   The prime interest rate rose by half a percentage point Monday to
10.5 percent at major New York banks. The prime rate is what banks
charge their best customers to borrow money, and the new rate means
consumers will pay more to finance a new car.
   ``If a dealer offers a guy an $800 rebate on a new car and he
goes to the bank and finds out the interest rate is 13\ percent, the
buyer may walk away,'' Phillippi said. ``It might be smarter to say
`The car costs this much. We'll give it to you at 7.9 percent
interest.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
