<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney: Pillsbury Searched In Vain For Different Buyer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pillsbury Co. found no takers among 15
third parties it asked to buy the company on friendly terms after
Grand Metropolitan PLC launched its takeover bid, an attorney for
Pillsbury shareholders says.
   ``They have surveyed the world and they haven't come up with
anything better than what Grand Met is offering,'' attorney Karl
Cambronne said Monday.
   ``The game is over. They need to redeem their (poison) pill or
negotiate with Grand Met,'' he said.
   Cambronne said the failed attempt to find a friendly suitor is
confirmed in a Securities and Exchange Commission filing in which
Pillsbury says it has abandoned the search.
   He commented after a Hennepin County District Court hearing at
which Judge Thomas Carey took under advisement renewed arguments
from the shareholders' group on its request to have the poison pill
invalidated, force Pillsbury to negotiate with Grand Met and block
the planned spinoff.
   Pillsbury asked Carey to force Grand Met to put its best offer on
the table so Pillsbury can accept or reject it, Cambronne said.
   Grand Met, meanwhile, on Monday extended for the fifth time its
$60 a share, all-cash tender offer for Pillsbury stock.
   The tender offer now will expire at midnight EST Friday unless
extended again. By Saturday, 85.3 percent of Pillsbury's outstanding
shares had been tendered and not withdrawn, Grand Met said.
   The liquor, gambling and specialty products conglomerate launched
its $5.23 billion hostile takeover bid Oct. 4. Pillsbury's board of
directors has rejected it as inadequate and has refused to meet with
Grand Met Chairman Allen Sheppard.
   Pillsbury's investment bankers valued the company at $62 to $78 a
share in mid-October, said Lowell Sachnoff, one of the shareholders'
attorneys.
   Standing in the way of a takeover are Pillsbury's poison pill
defense and a plan to spin off its Burger King subsidiary into a
separate company.
   Grand Met and dissident Pillsbury shareholders are suing the food
and restaurant company to invalidate the poison pill and prevent the
spinoff.
   Burger King Chairman Jerry Levin will be questioned Thursday for
five hours in Miami by attorneys for the shareholders and Grand Met
as part of the litigation, Carey said.
   ``Hopefully we'll find out more about the (Burger King) plan,''
said John Cochrane, an attorney for the shareholders.
   Grand Met has said a separate Burger King would create a huge tax
liability for Grand Met if the takeover is successful. In addition,
Burger King franchisees have announced opposition to the plan,
saying it would add too much debt to the already troubled fast-food
chain.
   The poison pill, or shareholders' rights plan, would make the
acquisition prohibitively expensive and the tender offer is
conditioned on its removal, Grand Met has said.
</TEXT>
