<2ND_LINE>PM-Prime Computer,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Rejects Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NATICK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. announced today that its
board of directors has unanimously rejected a $20-per-share buyout
bid by MAI Basic Four Inc.
   A release by the computer company called the offer by Choice
Corp., a wholly owned subsidiary of MAI, ``inadequate and not in the
best interests of the company and its stockholders.''
   The board recommended that Prime stockholders reject the offer
and not tender their shares in response to the MAI offer.
   Prime Chairman David Dunn said the board considered several
factors, including Prime's business and financial condition, its
future prospects, recommendations from the company's financial
advisers and the recent value of its stock.
   Prime Computer stock opened on the New York Stock Exchange this
morning at $15{ per share.
   Board members also noted that Prime's next annual meeting
scheduled for May 12, 1989 comes before the expiration of MAI's
offer. According to the Prime directors, the current market price of
Prime common stock reflects the negative effects of the costs and
expenses associated with the acquisition of Computervision.
   On the other hand, the company expects belt-tightening measures
in certain areas to improve near-term and long-term operating
results of the company and increase values for stockholders.
   ``We believe the unsolicited $20 offer by Choice fails to
recognize either the intrinsic value of the company today or the
long-term values achievable by the company for all its
stockholders.''
   Financier Bennett LeBow heads MAI, which is a much smaller
computer business than Prime. Prime is second to International
Business Machines Corp. in the field of computer-aided design and
manufacturing systems. Prime acquired Computervision in February for
$435 million.
   There has been some speculation that LeBow undertook the takeover
attempt to induce Prime to buy his company instead, in what is
commonly called a Pac Man defense of acquiring the suitor.
   MAI Basic, a small concern based in Tustin, Calif., owns 4.1
percent of Prime's 48.5 million shares outstanding and is offering
$20 a share for the rest in a tender offer to the shareholders. The
offer, valued at $970 million, was made Nov. 15.
</TEXT>
