<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Mixed In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures were narrowly mixed in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade after opening
slightly lower.
   The wheat market got a bit of a boost on prospects for a pickup
in export sales and in response to an Agriculture Department report
indicating an increase in export shipments last week, analysts said.
   Corn was up slightly on buying by traders who had sold borrowed
contracts earlier, and soybeans were little changed.
   Analysts said the opening sell-off, like the previous day's sharp
decline, seemed tied to disappointment that the U.S.-Soviet grain
deal signed Monday was only a 27-month extension of a 5-year pact
that expired on Sept. 30.
   ``I think we're getting, in all these markets, some general
disappointment that the grain agreement really didn't have anything
new to offer from the old agreement,'' said Walter Spilka, an
analyst in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent lower to { cent higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.19 a bushel; corn was \
cent to 1{ cents higher with December at $2.58} a bushel; oats were
{ cent to 2{ cents lower with December at $2.02{ a bushel; soybeans
were 1 cent lower to 2 cents higher with January at $7.49{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed in early trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange while pork futures were mostly higher.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .13 cent higher with December
at 73.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .20
cent higher with January at 82.55 cents a pound; live hogs were .02
cent lower to .45 cent higher with December at 40 cents a pound; and
frozen pork bellies were .20 cent to .48 cent higher with February
at 43.22 cents a pound.
   Cattle settled lower on Monday and pork futures finished higher.
</TEXT>
