<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0420</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices drifted aimlessly today after the
government's report on the gross national product had little impact
on Wall Street.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fluctuated in a
narrow range through the morning, and was up 4.26 to 2,085.70 as of
noon EST.
   Declining issues were neck-and-neck with advancers, with 626
stocks falling, 619 rising and 526 unchanged on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   Among broader indicators, the NYSE index of all its listed stocks
was up 0.16 to 151.41, while the American Stock Exchange's market
value index slipped 0.43 to 291.24.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled a light 51.13 million shares by
midday.
   The Commerce Department said the economy, as measured by the GNP,
expanded at a moderate 2.6 percent annual rate in the third quarter.
That was up from the government's preliminary estimate last month of
2.2 percent growth, but below the 2.9 percent to 3 percent expected
by Wall Street, said Larry Wachtel, a market analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The GNP news sent the dollar lower and bond prices higher, and
therefore had a neutral effect on stock trading, Wachtel said.
   Analysts said many investors were waiting for Friday's
unemployment figures from the Labor Department, which might give
some clue as to whether the Federal Reserve Board is likely to
tighten or relax credit.
   Traders anticipated the Fed would raise its discount rate, but in
the meantime, the market was meandering without conviction or
direction, said Michael Metz, an analyst with Oppenheimer & Co.
   ``They're waiting for the bad news to get out and over with,'' he
said.
   The most actively traded issue on the NYSE today was Northeast
Utilities, which was unchanged at 20].
   RJR Nabisco was up ~ at 89~ as today's 5 p.m. EST deadline for
bids for the tobacco and food company neared.
   IBM was down \ to 118| after arbitrators announced Fujitsu Ltd.
would pay the computer giant hundreds of millions of dollars for the
use of information about the software that runs IBM mainframe
computers. The market had expected IBM would receive a much larger
award.
   TW Services was up 2] to 24~ after Coniston Partners said it had
received enough TW shares to boost its stake in the company to 81.3
percent. Coniston has offered to buy the food services firm for $29
a share, or $1.14 billion.
