<1ST_LINE>a f BC-CroplandPaved Adv03-04   11-29 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Cropland Paved, Adv 03-04,0687</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 3-4 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Houses, Malls Encroach on California Croplands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VISALIA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The problems of attorney Dan Dooley, who
farms a small parcel east of here, show how difficult it's getting
to balance the interests of agriculture and development in
California.
   Residents in the area complain about dust, noise, bugs and
traffic congestion caused by slow-moving tractors, while farmers
suffer from vandalism to farm and irrigation equipment and trash
from weekend picnickers.
   Repeated complaints by neighbors finally forced Dooley to change
his cropping patterns.
   ``We just don't grow cotton on our ranch anymore. The conflicts
are just too severe,'' he said.
   Rapid growth in the fertile San Joaquin Valley, locked between
San Francisco and Los Angeles, may eventually ruin farming in what
is regarded as the world's richest agricultural region.
   A Department of Agriculture study shows as many as 50,000 acres
of productive crop land in the state are paved over or removed from
production each year because of urbanization.
   Air pollution primarily brought on by heavy vehicle traffic is
making serious cuts in production of some crops, such as grapes,
according to Fresno County Supervisor Vernon Conrad, a panelist at a
recent discussion here sponsored by the California Rural Development
Committee.
   ``We can preserve the land, but if we can't preserve the
production, what good is it?'' Conrad said of the air pollution
issue. ``If we don't do some planning and take care of some of the
obvious shortfalls, it's going to be too late.''
   About 815,000 acres of farm land will be lost in California
between now and the year 2000, estimated John C. Williamson, a
former assemblyman who sponsored the state's strong farmland
conservation measures in the early 1960s.
   ``All efforts now being made are inadequate for the purpose of
protecting farm land,'' Williamson said.
   Will Shafroth, director of the American Farmland Trust, agreed
that current preservation efforts are inadequate but said public
officials have a number of tools available to spare crop lands from
a layer of fresh asphalt.
   Shafroth called for strict land-use regulations to prevent
``leap-frog'' development, or housing subdivisions and industrial
parks situated in the middle of productive fields. Such development
in North Natomas area of Sacramento County has led to the demise of
once-productive rice farms.
   Eugene Smith, planning and development director for Tulare
County, said planners must regard agriculture as an industry when
examining housing development proposals.
   ``Just as locating a residence in an industrial park leads to
conflict and does not make sense, locating a residence in the middle
of an agricultural area does not make sense,'' said Smith.
   ``Rural residential growth right now in the San Joaquin Valley is
the greatest threat to preservation of farm land,'' Smith said.
   The practice of splitting off small parcels of the farm so family
members can build homes or ``rural ranchettes'' is a common way
development encroaches on agriculture, he said.
   Dooley said his farm can't use certain chemicals because of the
nearby homes, and the materials he does use can only be applied by
ground spray rigs, not by aerial cropdusters.
   To keep developers at bay, farmers are being encouraged to retain
their land when inflated prices make selling out a lucrative option.
The sale of development rights to public agencies is another option.
   Under such agreements, a public agency pays a farm owner the
difference between the farm land's current and potential value for
housing or other urban uses. When development rights are conveyed,
future development is restricted in the property deed, but the
farmer retains ownership of the land.
   A similar concept is used to acquire land in the Lake Tahoe basin
to stop excessive development and improve environmental quality.
   While financing such a program is unclear, officials have
suggested such options as bond issues, taxes on sales of converted
farm land, or local taxing districts.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 3-4</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881129-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1239EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-HoneywellSale     11-29 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Honeywell Sale,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honeywell To Sell Colorado Semiconductor Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc. said Tuesday it plans to sell
its semiconductor operation in Colorado Springs, Colo.
   The Colorado Springs unit manufactures custom and semi-custom
integrated circuits for the computer merchant market, as well as for
Honeywell's internal needs and select military customers.
   ``The decision to sell the Colorado Springs operation is
consistent with our desire to concentrate on our core businesses,''
said James J. Renier, Honeywell president and chief executive
officer.
   ``With the divestiture of the computer business at the end of
1986 and actions since then to focus on our leadership position in
controls, we no longer need such an extensive facility for circuits
used internally, nor is it in our strategic interest to be in the
merchant chip business,'' Renier added.
   ``Except for highly proprietary circuits, most of our
semiconductor needs can be satisfied on the outside,'' he said.
   The Colorado Springs operation is part of the company's Solid
State Electronics Division, which also includes a research and
development facility in Plymouth. Honeywell had previously said it
intended to restructure the division to fit the company's strategic
direction.
   Honeywell said it would maintain the Plymouth facility as a
modest captive operation. It will transfer a limited number of
fabrication technologies and products from Colorado Springs to
Plymouth to aid in meeting future internal and military customer
requirements for proprietary integrated circuits.
   The company is seeking a buyer who will also continue to support
external customers and also Honeywell's internal requirements during
a transition period.
   About 1,100 employees work in the four-building Colorado Springs
complex and Honeywell said it expects employees to transfer to the
new owner at the time of sale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
