<HEAD>IC Acquires Two Wisconsin Pepsi Bottlers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   IC Industries Inc., the nation's second-largest
bottler of Pepsi-Cola products, said Tuesday it had agreed to
purchase two Pepsi bottling operations in Wisconsin for an
undisclosed sum.
   The franchises in Oshkosh and Wisconsin Rapids will become part
of Pepsi-Cola General Bottlers Inc., an IC subsidiary that bottles
about 125 million cases of soda pop annually, Chicago-based IC said
in a statement.
   The Wisconsin operations, both owned by the Pennau family of
Oshkosh, bottle a total of 5 million cases annually, IC said.
   Pepsi-Cola General handles 12 percent of Pepsico Inc.'s domestic
soft-drink volume, second only to the Pepsi-Cola Bottling Group,
which is wholly owned by Pepsico and accounts for 33 percent of the
company's domestic volume.
   Pepsico, based in Purchase, N.Y., owns 20 percent of Pepsi-Cola
General.
   IC, which will change its name to Whitman Corp. on Thursday, is a
consumer goods and services company with four major operating
companies _ Pepsi-Cola General, Pet Inc., Hussman Corp. and Midas
International.
