<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1441EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     11-29 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0431</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices moved higher today, supported by
strength in the dollar and Treasury bonds and by a round of program
buying.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which fluctuated
in a narrow range through the morning, was up 16.89 to 2,098.33 as
of 2 p.m. EST.
   Advancing issues had a 2-to-1 lead over decliners, with 936
stocks rising, 466 falling and 484 unchanged on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   Among broader indicators, the NYSE index of all its listed stocks
was up 0.99 to 152.24, while the American Stock Exchange's market
value index rose 0.23 to 291.90.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled a light 87.68 million shares by
midday.
   Firmness in the bond market and an improvement by the dollar in
foreign exchange trading boosted stock prices, said Peter
Vandenberg, a market analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Program buying also added some fuel to the Wall Street rally,
Vandenberg said. However, he noted, trading was very light.
   Analysts said many investors were waiting for Friday's
unemployment figures from the Labor Department, which might give
some clue as to whether the Federal Reserve Board is likely to
tighten or relax credit.
   Traders anticipated the Fed would raise its discount rate, but in
the meantime, the market was meandering without conviction or
direction, said Michael Metz, an analyst with Oppenheimer & Co.
   ``They're waiting for the bad news to get out and over with,'' he
said.
   The Commerce Department reported early today that the economy, as
measured by the GNP, expanded at a moderate 2.6 percent annual rate
in the third quarter. That was up from the government's preliminary
estimate last month of 2.2 percent growth.
   Analysts said the report had a muted effect on Wall Street.
   The most actively traded issue on the NYSE today was RJR Nabisco,
up 1 at 90. The company's deadline for takeover bids was 5 p.m. EST
today.
   IBM was unchanged at 118~ after arbitrators announced Fujitsu
Ltd. would pay the computer giant hundreds of millions of dollars
for the use of information about the software that runs IBM
mainframe computers. The market had expected IBM would receive a
much larger award.
   TW Services picked up 2] to 24~ after Coniston Partners said it
had received enough TW shares to boost its stake in the company to
81.3 percent. Coniston has offered to buy the food services firm for
$29 a share, or $1.14 billion.
</TEXT>
