<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   11-29 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gains In Crop Futures Tied To Late Profit-Taking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of wheat, corn and soybeans closed
mostly higher Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade in a late flurry
of buying by traders who had sold contracts earlier in the session.
   Analysts attributed the closing rally almost entirely to
``short-covering,'' a form of profit-taking that amounts to selling
high, then buying low instead of buying low, then selling high.
   ``The last 10 minutes just turned into a very good rally on
short-covering,'' said Jon Horton, a research analyst with Research
Department Inc., a Chicago-based analytical firm. ``They just ran
out of selling there toward the close and everyone started to
cover.''
   Oat futures plunged for the second day in a row in a continuing
reaction to abundant supplies of feed-quality oats, said Jay Homan,
an independent trader.
   Homan also said the oat market was shrinking away from the
inflated prices caused by drought-related panic buying during the
summer.
   At the close of trading, wheat was 1\ cents to 5 cents higher
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.23{ a bushel; corn
was } cent to 1 cent higher with December at $2.56{ a bushel; oats
were 5 cents to 9{ cents lower with December at $1.95{ a bushel;
soybeans were 7{ cents lower to 5{ cents higher with January at
$7.55 a bushel.
</TEXT>
