<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1921EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ConstructionContracts     11-29 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Construction Contracts,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says October Construction Contracts Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release after 5:30 p.m. EST; time set by source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New construction contracts rose slightly in
October after a three-month slump, on the strength of residential
building everywhere except in the Northeast, a business-research
company reported Tuesday.
   The F.W. Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill Information Services Co. said
that new construction projects last month were up 1 percent to an
annualized value of $240.2 billion. Construction contracts fell 3
percent in September, following drops in the previous two months.
   George A. Christie, a McGraw-Hill economist, said that while the
October improvement was welcome, it ``should be interpreted as a
pause rather than a turnaround for the sagging construction sector.''
   ``The prospect of a post-election rise of interest rates presents
the risk of a further setback for this credit-sensitive industry,''
Christie said. ``Housing, which provided most of October's support,
is especially vulnerable.''
   Housing starts were up by about 7 percent in October, with the
value of contracts for one- and multi-family houses rising 4 percent
to an annualized $120.8 billion, the report said.
   The report said that all regions shared in the improved housing
activity but the Northeast, which experienced a 10 percent decline
from September's rate of contracting.
   October contracting for nonresidential buildings fell 8 percent
to an annualized $75.6 billion, the report said. It said the biggest
declines were in office buildings, down 23 percent, and in schools,
down 22 percent.
   For the first 10 months, new construction starts on an unadjusted
basis totaled $213.4 billion, down 3 percent from the same period in
1987, the report said. The South, with a shortfall of 6 percent,
remained the nation's weakest building market in 1988, while the
West held even with last year, it said.
</TEXT>
