<FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 1616EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Takeovers-Profits Bjt   11-29 0744</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Takeovers-Profits, Bjt,0768</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shareholder Windfalls From Megadeals: Where Will All That Money Go?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billions of dollars in potential shareholder
profits from two staggering takeover deals have aroused a debate
over how the money will be reinvested, with some strategists saying
the outcome could determine the future direction of stocks and the
economy.
   In one of the biggest takeovers ever, Philip Morris Cos. will buy
Kraft Inc. for $12.6 billion or $106 a share. For owners of Kraft
shares prior to the takeover plan _ first disclosed last month, when
the stock traded at about $60 _ that represents a profit of more
than 76 percent.
   An even bigger deal looms for RJR Nabisco Inc., which has been
the target of competing bids valued at between $21.3 billion to
$26.8 billion, or $94 a share to $118 as share.
   For holders of RJR shares, which traded at about $56 in
mid-October, that means a potential maximum profit of nearly 111
percent.
   If a significant part of the money from the megadeals is plowed
back into the stock market, it would be considered a strong sign of
confidence that the country is growing and recession is unlikely for
a while.
   On the other hand, if most of the money goes into
interest-bearing accounts or government bonds, it will reinforce
fears that stocks will head lower and an economic downturn isn't far
off.
   ``My opinion is the stock market is in a major peak,'' said
Charles M. LaLoggia, author of Special Situation Report, a widely
followed market newsletter based in Rochester, N.Y.
   ``My advice, to anybody lucky enough to own stock in a takeover
target taken out in a peak, is to put it to work in a Treasury
bill,'' LaLoggia said.
   A few optimists have predicted that because of the sheer volume
of this money, some will find its way into the stock market and
could serve as the octane to drive up prices, perhaps snapping Wall
Street out of its slump.
   But the prevailing view appears to be that most shareholders _
the majority of them large institutional investors _ likely will
park their profits in safe, short-term government Treasury bonds.
   The 8.3 percent yield of a three-month Treasury bill represents a
better investment than components of the Standard & Poor's 500-stock
index, a widely watched barometer of the general stock market's
health, which has risen about 8.7 percent the entire year.
   ``With interest rates moving up, and three-month Treasuries
yielding more than 8 percent, it's hard to justify giving up that
safety for the risk of the stock market,'' said David Blitzer, chief
economist for Standard & Poor's Corp.
   ``That suggests to me that whoever owns shares in whatever
celebrated buyout is going on, if he listens to most investment
advisers, he won't put it back into the stock market,'' Blitzer
said. ``He'll wait for a sunnier day.''
   Countering this view is the theory that while demand for stocks
continues, the number of stocks is shrinking, partly because of
takeovers and mergers such as the Kraft and RJR Nabisco deals.
According to Federal Reserve figures, the amount of available stock
has shrunk by about $75 billion in each of the past two years.
   If that's true, some strategists say, simple laws of supply and
demand will dictate that stock prices rise, making them more
attractive and drawing more investors _ including those who made
windfall profits in the two big takeovers.
   ``I would assume part of that money would be going into the stock
market,'' said Rao Chalasani, a market strategist at the
Cleveland-based firm Prescott Ball & Turben Inc.
   ``I think there are other stocks priced similarly to those two
companies prior to when the takeovers were announced,'' he said.
``Some of the money would go into these companies, regardless of
whether they will be taken over.''
   Others say the supply-demand theory is a fiction promoted by the
securities industry when it's clear the stock market has hit a
cyclical high.
   ``I regard all the work I've seen that says there's a
supply-demand situation to be nonsense,'' said James Cramer, owner
of Cramer & Co., a New York money management firm.
   ``The main reason is, you can buy all the GE you want, you can
buy all the IBM you want, and the prices aren't rising,'' he said.
``There are too many stocks that nobody wants and too few that
everybody wants.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
