<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     11-29 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0240</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices closed higher today as a rally in
the dollar and Treasury bonds helped Wall Street break out the
doldrums.
   However, volume was light, and analysts said investors were
waiting for Friday's unemployment figures from the Labor Department,
which might give some clue as to whether the Federal Reserve Board
is likely to tighten or relax credit.
   The market meandered its way through the first few hours of
trading, fluctuating in a narrow range as it did on Monday.
   But in the early afternoon, program buying set in and investors
responded to firmness in the bond market and an improvement by the
dollar, said Peter Vandenberg, a market analyst with Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc.
   Ralph Acampora, an analyst with Kidder, Peabody & Co., said Wall
Street's oversold condition has cleared the way for buying.
   ``I think the negatives are all on the table,'' he said.
``Eveyrone who wanted to sell, sold.''
   More traders didn't join today's rally because ``no one believes
it,'' he said.
   The Commerce Department reported today that the economy, as
measured by the GNP, expanded at a moderate 2.6 percent annual rate
in the third quarter. That was up from the government's preliminary
estimate last month of 2.2 percent growth.
   Analysts said the report had a muted effect on Wall Street.
</TEXT>
