<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-29 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped sharply and then recovered
most of its ground Tuesday in a confused session dominated by
speculation about the direction of U.S. interest rates.
   The dollar declined after the government reported an upward
revision in the third-quarter U.S. gross national product to 2.6
percent from 2.2 percent.
   Some traders said the dollar fell because the market had been
anticipating growth of closer to 3 percent during the July-September
period. Others said the growth was healthy and did not account
entirely for the dollar's drop.
   The dollar's rise, which picked up momentum in the early
afternoon in New York, appeared to be unrelated to any economic
news, traders said.
   Some big banks may have bid the dollar up in an effort to put a
squeeze on ``shorts'' _ that is, traders who had borrowed dollars in
hopes that the currency would decline and they would be able to make
a profit by paying back the lenders with cheaper dollars, said James
M. Pugh, vice president for foreign exchange at Bear, Stearns & Co.
   ``It caught a lot of people by surprise,'' said John Lyman,
senior corporate foreign-exchange dealer for the Bank of Tokyo in
New York.
   Traders were looking ahead to Friday's report on U.S.
unemployment in November, which could give a hint about the Federal
Reserve's future monetary policy.
   Traders have chosen to focus in recent weeks on the outlook for
interest rates in the United States. Tighter monetary policy would
push up short-term U.S. interest rates, making dollar-denominated
securities more attractive to investors.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8425, more expensive for
buyers than Monday's $1.8385. Later in New York, the pound rose to
$1.8443 from $1.8399 Monday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 122.15 Japanese yen, up from
122.00. In London the dollar traded lower at 121.65 yen. In New
York, the dollar fell to 121.83 yen from 122.28 yen Monday.
   Other late rates in New York, compared with Monday's late rates,
included: 1.7348 West German marks, down from 1.7355; 1.4500 Swiss
francs, down from 1.4524; 1.1913 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1931;
5.9310 French francs, up from 5.9273; and 1,282.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,286.25.
   Other late rates in Europe, compared with Monday's late rates,
included: 1.7285 West German marks, down from 1.7332; 1.4481 Swiss
francs, down from 1.4515; 5.9125 French francs, down from 5.9225;
1.9530 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9547; 1,281.25 Italian lire, down
from 1,285.50; and 1.1930 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1918.
   Gold prices rose in Asian trading but fell later in the day in
Europe and the United States.
   In Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid of $423.31 an ounce, up from
$422.02.
   In London, the major European trading center for the precious
metal, gold closed at $422.75 a troy ounce, down from $423.85. The
closing price in Zurich, Switzerland, was $422.25 an ounce, down
from $423.25.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $421.90 a troy ounce from $423.30.
   Later, Republic National Bank of New York said gold bullion was
bid at $421.50 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down from $422.10 late
Monday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $6.09 a troy ounce, down
from $6.16. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery
fell to $6.030 a troy ounce from $6.113 late Monday.
</TEXT>
