<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TWServices     11-29 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TW Services,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coniston Extends $29-a-Share Offer to All of TW Service Shares</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor group pursuing TW Services Inc. said
Tuesday its tender offer for some of TW Services' shares attracted
about twice as many shares as sought and that it was extending its
$29-a-share offer to all of the food services company's stock.
   The group, Coniston Partners, said its amended offer of $1.14
billion in cash for the 81 percent of TW Services that it does not
already own would expire at 12:01 a.m. on Dec. 13.
   Coniston also said it had asked the Delaware Chancery Court to
require the TW Services board to redeem or invalidate the
poison-pill rights that would otherwise make its bid for control of
the company prohibitively expensive.
   In response, TW Services said its board would consider Coniston's
amended offer ``in due course.''
   Its chairman and chief executive, Frank L. Salizzoni, said the
substantial number of shares tendered was ``irrelevant'' because the
partial tender was ``designed from the outset to stampede
shareholders into tendering their stock in hopes of forcing the
company into another transaction.''
   He said the amended Coniston offer for all TW stock ``remains
highly conditional.''
   ``Given that it is conditioned, among other things, on TW
Services entering into a satisfactory merger agreement, it remains
merely an invitation to enter merger negotiations,'' he said in a
statement.
   Coniston, a New York-based investment firm that already owns
about 9.3 million of TW Services' 48.6 million shares, launched a
tender offer for 15.75 million of TW Services shares in late October.
   The combination of those shares with what Coniston already owned
would give it about 51 percent of the company.
   Coniston said that when its partial tender offer expired at 12:01
a.m. Tuesday, nearly 30.2 million shares had been tendered which
would have given Coniston nearly 82 percent of TW Services'
outstanding shares.
   Under its two-step plan, Coniston said it would then acquire the
remaining shares in a merger for $29 a share in cash.
   Coniston said the two-step plan was devised to get around the
Delaware anti-takeover law that restricts uninvited bidders from
building a stake in a company based in that state.
   Paul E. Tierney Jr., a Coniston principal, said he expects the
only obstacle that would prevent Coniston from buying tendered stock
after its offer expires next month would be the poison pill.
   Coniston has said that if it acquires TW Services, it plans to
sell the company's health services operations, which include 27
skilled nursing facilities and two retirement living centers.
   TW Services' other operations include 1,200 Denny's restaurants,
400 Hardee's fast-food restaurants and Canteen Corp., a food
services company.
</TEXT>
