<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-29 0792</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0818</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sugar Rallies On Supply Fears, Technical Factors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sugar futures prices surged Tuesday on New York's Coffee, Sugar &
Cocoa Exchange despite a lack of fresh news, a sign of the market's
increasing concern about the possibility of a supply shortage,
analysts said.
   On other markets, grains and soybeans finished mostly higher;
energy futures were mixed; precious metals were lower; livestock and
meat were mixed; and stock-index futures advanced.
   Sugar for delivery in March settled .33 cent higher at 11.30
cents a pound, the contract's highest close since Aug. 8, which also
was the last day March sugar closed above 11 cents.
   During Tuesday's session, the March contract traded as high as
11.33 cents a pound, challenging the previous day's intra-day peak
of 11.34 cents, a four-month high.
   Since falling below 9 cents a pound in late September, sugar
futures have risen fairly steadily on indications that world sugar
production in the current crop year may fall short of consumption,
reducing already-low inventories to critical levels.
   The United States, China and the Soviet Union all are rumored to
be looking for more sugar in the September-through-August crop year,
yet Cuba reportedly has asked China to accept deferred delivery of
scheduled shipments, analysts said.
   Last week, the West German statistics firm F.O. Licht reduced its
estimate of this year's European sugar-beet crop by 750,000 metric
tons, increasing fears of a production defict instead of the surplus
that had been expected only a few months ago.
   ``There have been concerns that if there is a sudden increase in
demand from the physical market, the sugar might not be available.
Now that there's the possibility of a production deficit, those
concerns are being felt even more strongly,'' said Judith Ganes, a
sugar market analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Analyst Arthur Stevenson of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in
New York said technical signals _ the chart patterns on which many
speculators base their trading decisions _ were extremely bullish.
   Wheat, corn and soybean futures finished mostly higher on the
Chicago Board of Trade in a late flurry of buying by traders who had
sold contracts earlier in the session.
   Analysts attributed the closing rally almost entirely to
``short-covering,'' a form of profit-taking that amounts to selling
high, then buying low instead of buying low, then selling high.
   Oat futures plunged for the second straight day in a continuing
reaction to abundant supplies of feed-quality oats, said Jay Homan,
an independent trader.
   Homan also said the oat market was shrinking away from the
inflated prices caused by drought-related panic buying during the
summer.
   Wheat settled 1 cent to 5 cents higher with December at $4.23{ a
bushel; corn was { cent lower to 1 cent higher with December at
$2.56} a bushel; oats were 5 cents to 9{ cents lower with December
at $1.95{ a bushel; soybeans were { cent to 4\ cents higher with
January at $7.53} a bushel.
   Energy futures settled mixed on the New York Mercantile Exchange
as the markets began consolidating the sharp gains of recent
sessions.
   After the close of trading, the American Petroleum Institute
released figures showing a 2.7 million-barrel drawdown in U.S.
crude-oil stocks and a 2.5-million-barrel decline in U.S. gasoline
stocks last week. Stocks of petroleum distillates increased by 1.76
million barrels, according to the API.
   Crude futures were expected to open higher Wednesday in reaction
to the report.
   West Texas Intermediate crude settled 11 cents lower to 15 cents
higher with January at $14.92 a barrel; heating oil was .86 cent
lower to .80 cent higher with December at 47.79 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .01 cent lower to .70 cent higher with
December at 46.87 cents a gallon.
   Intra-day weakness in crude prices, coupled with the weakness of
the dollar pressured precious-metals futures on New York's Commodity
Exchange, said Bernard Savaiko, a metals analyst with PaineWebber
Inc. in New York.
   Gold settled 50 cents to $1.40 lower with December at $421.90 a
troy ounce; silver was 8.5 cents to 9 cents lower with December at
$6.03 a troy ounce.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle settled .10 cent
to .47 cent lower with December at 73.10 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .15 cent lower to .25 cent higher with January at 82.70
cents a pound; hogs were .35 cent lower to .45 cent higher with
December at 39.47 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .05 cent
to .13 cent lower with February at 43.05 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures advanced moderately on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 settled 2.20 points higher at 271.15. The contract is
worth $500 a point.
</TEXT>
