<HEAD>Campeau Sells Ann Taylor to Investor Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. announced Tuesday it is selling its
Ann Taylor division for $430 million to an investor group that
includes the specialty store chain's management and Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets.
   The group also includes Joseph E. Brooks, former chairman of Lord
& Taylor, the department store chain owned by May Department Stores
Co.
   Campeau announced in June it would sell Ann Taylor, a division of
Allied Stores Corp., and get out of the specialty store business
altogether.
   The Toronto-based company's retail holdings now consist solely of
department stores.
   Allied includes Bon Marche, Maas Brothers, Jordan Marsh and
Sterns department stores, while Campeau's Federated Department
Stores unit comprises the Bloomingdale's, Goldsmith's, Lazarus,
Burdine's, Abraham and Straus and Rich's chains.
   Ann Taylor, which operates 114 upscale clothing stores, had 1987
sales of $249 million.
