<1ST_LINE>u f AM-GE-Fraud 2ndLd-Writethru f0290 11-29 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GE-Fraud, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0290,0682</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Charges GE with Defrauding Army of $10 Million</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: DELETES 11th graf pvs, The Army... as unnecessary. SUBS
penultimate graf to DELETE redundant reference to May 1985.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. and two employees were
indicted Tuesday on federal charges of hiding $10 million worth of
savings in a contract to make a battlefield computer system.
   GE, the nation's third-largest defense contractor, said the
indictment was ``unfair'' and ``sensationalized,'' adding that the
company intends to fight the charges.
   GE also said an internal investigation showed pricing
discrepancies totaling $3.69 million, which the company already has
refunded.
   GE faces a maximum penalty of $71.871 million plus restitution,
the government said.
   ``We look forward to the opportunity to have a jury judge the
merits of the case,'' said Thomas H. Lee II, first assistant U.S.
attorney.
   The defense case was not the first involving GE. In 1985, the
company pleaded guilty to unrelated contract-fraud charges.
   In Washington, the Defense Department said no decisions have been
made as yet on suspension or debarment of GE to bid on defense
contracts.
   ``The allegations will now have to be reviewed by the Army,''
said William Caldwell, a Pentagon spokesman.
   The 321-count indictment charges that GE, through its
wholly-owned subsidiary Management and Technical Services Co. in
King of Prussia, Pa., negotiated subcontracting costs less than
anticipated and hid the lower prices from the Army.
   GE was awarded a $250 million contract in June 1983 to make the
``decentralized automated service support system'' for the Army.
   The company and the two employees lied to the Defense Department
about the prices the company was paying for parts and raw materials
and double-billed for some materials, according to the indictment.
   The government also charges James Badolato, 41, of Springfield,
Pa., formerly the subcontracts manager for MATSCO, with trying to
cover up the scheme by altering dates of purchase orders and
withholding information from government auditors.
   The other employee, Gerald A. Leo, 51, of King of Prussia,
formerly the materials manager for MATSCO, was also charged with
lying to a federal auditor.
   In its statement, GE denied any criminal wrongdoing and said the
employees maintained their innocence. Leo and Badolato referred
reporters to the company attorneys.
   ``The simple fact is that the case against GE revolves around a
negotiaion in the spring of 1983 in which the two employees at MASCO
allegedly failed to notify the Army that they had succeeded in
negotiating lower subcontract prices with several vendors than had
originally been projected,'' GE said in a written statement.
   ``Any legitimate governmental interest could be served by an
appropriate civil resolution of this matter,'' GE said.
   GE is charged with five counts of mail fraud and 312 counts of
presenting false claims to the government.
   Leo was charged with racketeering, five counts of mail fraud and
two counts of making false statements and concealing material facts
from a federal agency.
   Badolato was charged with one count of racketeering, five counts
of mail fraud, one count of obstructing agency proceedings and one
count of making false statements and concealing material facts from
a federal agency.
   Leo and Badolato have since been transferred to other parts of
GE, the government said.
   In 1987, GE did $5.8 billion worth of business with the Defense
Department, the government said.
   If convicted, Leo faces a maximum of 55 years in jail, $1.276
million in fines and forfeiture of salary bonuses and company stock
derived from the racketeering. Badolato faces the same penalties
plus $5,000 more in fines if convicted.
   Nicholas C. Harbist, assistant U.S. attorney said he did not know
the amount of bonuses the men received.
   GE pleaded guilty in May 1985 to contract-fraud charges, paying a
$1.04 million fine and rembursing the government $800,000.
   The company was indicted in March 1985 for forging employee time
cards and manipulating costs to recover losses on the Minuteman
missles.
</TEXT>
